3    /* Copyright (c) 2012-2017 The ANTLR Project. All rights reserved.

8    // This implementation of {@link TokenStream} loads tokens from a
9    // {@link TokenSource} on-demand, and places the tokens in a buffer to provide
10   // access to any previous token by index.
11   //
12   // <p>
13   // This token stream ignores the value of {@link Token//getChannel}. If your
14   // parser requires the token stream filter tokens to only those on a particular
15   // channel, such as {@link Token//DEFAULT_CHANNEL} or
16   // {@link Token//HIDDEN_CHANNEL}, use a filtering token stream such a
17   // {@link CommonTokenStream}.</p>
18   
19   var Token = require('./Token').Token;
20   var Lexer = require('./Lexer').Lexer;
21   var Interval = require('./IntervalSet').Interval;
22   
23   // this is just to keep meaningful parameter types to Parser
24   function TokenStream() {
25   	return this;
26   }
27   
28   function BufferedTokenStream(tokenSource) {
29   
30   	TokenStream.call(this);
31   	// The {@link TokenSource} from which tokens for this stream are fetched.
32   	this.tokenSource = tokenSource;
33   
34   	// A collection of all tokens fetched from the token source. The list is
35   	// considered a complete view of the input once {@link //fetchedEOF} is set
36   	// to {@code true}.
37   	this.tokens = [];
38   
39   	// The index into {@link //tokens} of the current token (next token to
40   	// {@link //consume}). {@link //tokens}{@code [}{@link //p}{@code ]} should
41   	// be
42   	// {@link //LT LT(1)}.
43   	//
44   	// <p>This field is set to -1 when the stream is first constructed or when
45   	// {@link //setTokenSource} is called, indicating that the first token has
46   	// not yet been fetched from the token source. For additional information,
47   	// see the documentation of {@link IntStream} for a description of
48   	// Initializing Methods.</p>
49   	this.index = -1;
50   
51   	// Indicates whether the {@link Token//EOF} token has been fetched from
52   	// {@link //tokenSource} and added to {@link //tokens}. This field improves
53   	// performance for the following cases:
54   	//
55   	// <ul>
56   	// <li>{@link //consume}: The lookahead check in {@link //consume} to
57   	// prevent
58   	// consuming the EOF symbol is optimized by checking the values of
59   	// {@link //fetchedEOF} and {@link //p} instead of calling {@link
60   	// //LA}.</li>
61   	// <li>{@link //fetch}: The check to prevent adding multiple EOF symbols
62   	// into
63   	// {@link //tokens} is trivial with this field.</li>
64   	// <ul>
65   	this.fetchedEOF = false;
66   	return this;
67   }
68   
69   BufferedTokenStream.prototype = Object.create(TokenStream.prototype);
70   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.constructor = BufferedTokenStream;
71   
72   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.mark = function() {
73   	return 0;
74   };
75   
76   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.release = function(marker) {
77   	// no resources to release
78   };
79   
80   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.reset = function() {
81   	this.seek(0);
82   };
83   
84   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.seek = function(index) {
85   	this.lazyInit();
86   	this.index = this.adjustSeekIndex(index);
87   };
88   
89   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.get = function(index) {
90   	this.lazyInit();
91   	return this.tokens[index];
92   };
93   
94   BufferedTokenStream.prototype.consume = function() {
95   	var skipEofCheck = false;
96   	if (this.index >= 0) {
97   		if (this.fetchedEOF) {
98   			// the last token in tokens is EOF. skip check if p indexes any
99   			// fetched token except the last.
100  			skipEofCheck = this.index < this.tokens.length - 1;
101  		} else {
102  			// no EOF token in tokens. skip check if p indexes a fetched token.
103  			skipEofCheck = this.index < this.tokens.length;
104  		}
105  	} else {
106  		// not yet initialized
107  		skipEofCheck = false;
108  	}
109  	if (!skipEofCheck && this.LA(1) === Token.EOF) {
110  		throw "cannot consume EOF";
111  	}
112  	if (this.sync(this.index + 1)) {
113  		this.index = this.adjustSeekIndex(this.index + 1);
114  	}
115  };
116  
117  // Make sure index {@code i} in tokens has a token.
118  //
119  // @return {@code true} if a token is located at index {@code i}, otherwise
120  // {@code false}.
121  // @see //get(int i)
122  // /
123  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.sync = function(i) {
124  	var n = i - this.tokens.length + 1; // how many more elements we need?
125  	if (n > 0) {
126  		var fetched = this.fetch(n);
127  		return fetched >= n;
128  	}
129  	return true;
130  };
131  
132  // Add {@code n} elements to buffer.
133  //
134  // @return The actual number of elements added to the buffer.
135  // /
136  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.fetch = function(n) {
137  	if (this.fetchedEOF) {
138  		return 0;
139  	}
140  	for (var i = 0; i < n; i++) {
141  		var t = this.tokenSource.nextToken();
142  		t.tokenIndex = this.tokens.length;
143  		this.tokens.push(t);
144  		if (t.type === Token.EOF) {
145  			this.fetchedEOF = true;
146  			return i + 1;
147  		}
148  	}
149  	return n;
150  };
151  
152  // Get all tokens from start..stop inclusively///
153  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.getTokens = function(start, stop, types) {
154  	if (types === undefined) {
155  		types = null;
156  	}
157  	if (start < 0 || stop < 0) {
158  		return null;
159  	}
160  	this.lazyInit();
161  	var subset = [];
162  	if (stop >= this.tokens.length) {
163  		stop = this.tokens.length - 1;
164  	}
165  	for (var i = start; i < stop; i++) {
166  		var t = this.tokens[i];
167  		if (t.type === Token.EOF) {
168  			break;
169  		}
170  		if (types === null || types.contains(t.type)) {
171  			subset.push(t);
172  		}
173  	}
174  	return subset;
175  };
176  
177  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.LA = function(i) {
178  	return this.LT(i).type;
179  };
180  
181  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.LB = function(k) {
182  	if (this.index - k < 0) {
183  		return null;
184  	}
185  	return this.tokens[this.index - k];
186  };
187  
188  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.LT = function(k) {
189  	this.lazyInit();
190  	if (k === 0) {
191  		return null;
192  	}
193  	if (k < 0) {
194  		return this.LB(-k);
195  	}
196  	var i = this.index + k - 1;
197  	this.sync(i);
198  	if (i >= this.tokens.length) { // return EOF token
199  		// EOF must be last token
200  		return this.tokens[this.tokens.length - 1];
201  	}
202  	return this.tokens[i];
203  };
204  
205  // Allowed derived classes to modify the behavior of operations which change
206  // the current stream position by adjusting the target token index of a seek
207  // operation. The default implementation simply returns {@code i}. If an
208  // exception is thrown in this method, the current stream index should not be
209  // changed.
210  //
211  // <p>For example, {@link CommonTokenStream} overrides this method to ensure
212  // that
213  // the seek target is always an on-channel token.</p>
214  //
215  // @param i The target token index.
216  // @return The adjusted target token index.
217  
218  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.adjustSeekIndex = function(i) {
219  	return i;
220  };
221  
222  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.lazyInit = function() {
223  	if (this.index === -1) {
224  		this.setup();
225  	}
226  };
227  
228  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.setup = function() {
229  	this.sync(0);
230  	this.index = this.adjustSeekIndex(0);
231  };
232  
233  // Reset this token stream by setting its token source.///
234  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.setTokenSource = function(tokenSource) {
235  	this.tokenSource = tokenSource;
236  	this.tokens = [];
237  	this.index = -1;
238  	this.fetchedEOF = false;
239  };
240  
241  
242  // Given a starting index, return the index of the next token on channel.
243  // Return i if tokens[i] is on channel. Return -1 if there are no tokens
244  // on channel between i and EOF.
245  // /
246  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.nextTokenOnChannel = function(i, channel) {
247  	this.sync(i);
248  	if (i >= this.tokens.length) {
249  		return -1;
250  	}
251  	var token = this.tokens[i];
252  	while (token.channel !== this.channel) {
253  		if (token.type === Token.EOF) {
254  			return -1;
255  		}
256  		i += 1;
257  		this.sync(i);
258  		token = this.tokens[i];
259  	}
260  	return i;
261  };
262  
263  // Given a starting index, return the index of the previous token on channel.
264  // Return i if tokens[i] is on channel. Return -1 if there are no tokens
265  // on channel between i and 0.
266  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.previousTokenOnChannel = function(i, channel) {
267  	while (i >= 0 && this.tokens[i].channel !== channel) {
268  		i -= 1;
269  	}
270  	return i;
271  };
272  
273  // Collect all tokens on specified channel to the right of
274  // the current token up until we see a token on DEFAULT_TOKEN_CHANNEL or
275  // EOF. If channel is -1, find any non default channel token.
276  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.getHiddenTokensToRight = function(tokenIndex,
277  		channel) {
278  	if (channel === undefined) {
279  		channel = -1;
280  	}
281  	this.lazyInit();
282  	if (tokenIndex < 0 || tokenIndex >= this.tokens.length) {
283  		throw "" + tokenIndex + " not in 0.." + this.tokens.length - 1;
284  	}
285  	var nextOnChannel = this.nextTokenOnChannel(tokenIndex + 1, Lexer.DEFAULT_TOKEN_CHANNEL);
286  	var from_ = tokenIndex + 1;
287  	// if none onchannel to right, nextOnChannel=-1 so set to = last token
288  	var to = nextOnChannel === -1 ? this.tokens.length - 1 : nextOnChannel;
289  	return this.filterForChannel(from_, to, channel);
290  };
291  
292  // Collect all tokens on specified channel to the left of
293  // the current token up until we see a token on DEFAULT_TOKEN_CHANNEL.
294  // If channel is -1, find any non default channel token.
295  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.getHiddenTokensToLeft = function(tokenIndex,
296  		channel) {
297  	if (channel === undefined) {
298  		channel = -1;
299  	}
300  	this.lazyInit();
301  	if (tokenIndex < 0 || tokenIndex >= this.tokens.length) {
302  		throw "" + tokenIndex + " not in 0.." + this.tokens.length - 1;
303  	}
304  	var prevOnChannel = this.previousTokenOnChannel(tokenIndex - 1, Lexer.DEFAULT_TOKEN_CHANNEL);
305  	if (prevOnChannel === tokenIndex - 1) {
306  		return null;
307  	}
308  	// if none on channel to left, prevOnChannel=-1 then from=0
309  	var from_ = prevOnChannel + 1;
310  	var to = tokenIndex - 1;
311  	return this.filterForChannel(from_, to, channel);
312  };
313  
314  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.filterForChannel = function(left, right, channel) {
315  	var hidden = [];
316  	for (var i = left; i < right + 1; i++) {
317  		var t = this.tokens[i];
318  		if (channel === -1) {
319  			if (t.channel !== Lexer.DEFAULT_TOKEN_CHANNEL) {
320  				hidden.push(t);
321  			}
322  		} else if (t.channel === channel) {
323  			hidden.push(t);
324  		}
325  	}
326  	if (hidden.length === 0) {
327  		return null;
328  	}
329  	return hidden;
330  };
331  
332  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.getSourceName = function() {
333  	return this.tokenSource.getSourceName();
334  };
335  
336  // Get the text of all tokens in this buffer.///
337  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.getText = function(interval) {
338  	this.lazyInit();
339  	this.fill();
340  	if (interval === undefined || interval === null) {
341  		interval = new Interval(0, this.tokens.length - 1);
342  	}
343  	var start = interval.start;
344  	if (start instanceof Token) {
345  		start = start.tokenIndex;
346  	}
347  	var stop = interval.stop;
348  	if (stop instanceof Token) {
349  		stop = stop.tokenIndex;
350  	}
351  	if (start === null || stop === null || start < 0 || stop < 0) {
352  		return "";
353  	}
354  	if (stop >= this.tokens.length) {
355  		stop = this.tokens.length - 1;
356  	}
357  	var s = "";
358  	for (var i = start; i < stop + 1; i++) {
359  		var t = this.tokens[i];
360  		if (t.type === Token.EOF) {
361  			break;
362  		}
363  		s = s + t.text;
364  	}
365  	return s;
366  };
367  
368  // Get all tokens from lexer until EOF///
369  BufferedTokenStream.prototype.fill = function() {
370  	this.lazyInit();
371  	while (this.fetch(1000) === 1000) {
372  		continue;
373  	}
374  };
375  
376  exports.BufferedTokenStream = BufferedTokenStream;

386  var InputStream = require('./InputStream').InputStream;

388  var isNodeJs = typeof window === 'undefined' && typeof importScripts === 'undefined';
389  var fs = isNodeJs ? require("fs") : null;

391  // Utility functions to create InputStreams from various sources.
392  //
393  // All returned InputStreams support the full range of Unicode
394  // up to U+10FFFF (the default behavior of InputStream only supports
395  // code points up to U+FFFF).
396  var CharStreams = {
397    // Creates an InputStream from a string.
398    fromString: function(str) {
399      return new InputStream(str, true);
400    },
401  
402    // Asynchronously creates an InputStream from a blob given the
403    // encoding of the bytes in that blob (defaults to 'utf8' if
404    // encoding is null).
405    //
406    // Invokes onLoad(result) on success, onError(error) on
407    // failure.
408    fromBlob: function(blob, encoding, onLoad, onError) {
409      var reader = FileReader();
410      reader.onload = function(e) {
411        var is = new InputStream(e.target.result, true);
412        onLoad(is);
413      };
414      reader.onerror = onError;
415      reader.readAsText(blob, encoding);
416    },
417  
418    // Creates an InputStream from a Buffer given the
419    // encoding of the bytes in that buffer (defaults to 'utf8' if
420    // encoding is null).
421    fromBuffer: function(buffer, encoding) {
422      return new InputStream(buffer.toString(encoding), true);
423    },
424  
425    // Asynchronously creates an InputStream from a file on disk given
426    // the encoding of the bytes in that file (defaults to 'utf8' if
427    // encoding is null).
428    //
429    // Invokes callback(error, result) on completion.
430    fromPath: function(path, encoding, callback) {
431      fs.readFile(path, encoding, function(err, data) {
432        var is = null;
433        if (data !== null) {
434          is = new InputStream(data, true);
435        }
436        callback(err, is);
437      });
438    },
439  
440    // Synchronously creates an InputStream given a path to a file
441    // on disk and the encoding of the bytes in that file (defaults to
442    // 'utf8' if encoding is null).
443    fromPathSync: function(path, encoding) {
444      var data = fs.readFileSync(path, encoding);
445      return new InputStream(data, true);
446    }
447  };
448  
449  exports.CharStreams = CharStreams;

459  //
460  // This default implementation of {@link TokenFactory} creates
461  // {@link CommonToken} objects.
462  //
463  
464  var CommonToken = require('./Token').CommonToken;
465  
466  function TokenFactory() {
467  	return this;
468  }
469  
470  function CommonTokenFactory(copyText) {
471  	TokenFactory.call(this);
472      // Indicates whether {@link CommonToken//setText} should be called after
473      // constructing tokens to explicitly set the text. This is useful for cases
474      // where the input stream might not be able to provide arbitrary substrings
475      // of text from the input after the lexer creates a token (e.g. the
476      // implementation of {@link CharStream//getText} in
477      // {@link UnbufferedCharStream} throws an
478      // {@link UnsupportedOperationException}). Explicitly setting the token text
479      // allows {@link Token//getText} to be called at any time regardless of the
480      // input stream implementation.
481      //
482      // <p>
483      // The default value is {@code false} to avoid the performance and memory
484      // overhead of copying text for every token unless explicitly requested.</p>
485      //
486      this.copyText = copyText===undefined ? false : copyText;
487  	return this;
488  }
489  
490  CommonTokenFactory.prototype = Object.create(TokenFactory.prototype);
491  CommonTokenFactory.prototype.constructor = CommonTokenFactory;
492  
493  //
494  // The default {@link CommonTokenFactory} instance.
495  //
496  // <p>
497  // This token factory does not explicitly copy token text when constructing
498  // tokens.</p>
499  //
500  CommonTokenFactory.DEFAULT = new CommonTokenFactory();
501  
502  CommonTokenFactory.prototype.create = function(source, type, text, channel, start, stop, line, column) {
503      var t = new CommonToken(source, type, channel, start, stop);
504      t.line = line;
505      t.column = column;
506      if (text !==null) {
507          t.text = text;
508      } else if (this.copyText && source[1] !==null) {
509          t.text = source[1].getText(start,stop);
510      }
511      return t;
512  };
513  
514  CommonTokenFactory.prototype.createThin = function(type, text) {
515      var t = new CommonToken(null, type);
516      t.text = text;
517      return t;
518  };
519  
520  exports.CommonTokenFactory = CommonTokenFactory;

523  //
524  /* Copyright (c) 2012-2017 The ANTLR Project. All rights reserved. 
525   * Use of this file is governed by the BSD 3-clause license that 
526   * can be found in the LICENSE.txt file in the project root.

530  //
531  // This class extends {@link BufferedTokenStream} with functionality to filter
532  // token streams to tokens on a particular channel (tokens where
533  // {@link Token//getChannel} returns a particular value).
534  //
535  // <p>
536  // This token stream provides access to all tokens by index or when calling
537  // methods like {@link //getText}. The channel filtering is only used for code
538  // accessing tokens via the lookahead methods {@link //LA}, {@link //LT}, and
539  // {@link //LB}.</p>
540  //
541  // <p>
542  // By default, tokens are placed on the default channel
543  // ({@link Token//DEFAULT_CHANNEL}), but may be reassigned by using the
544  // {@code ->channel(HIDDEN)} lexer command, or by using an embedded action to
545  // call {@link Lexer//setChannel}.
546  // </p>
547  //
548  // <p>
549  // Note: lexer rules which use the {@code ->skip} lexer command or call
550  // {@link Lexer//skip} do not produce tokens at all, so input text matched by
551  // such a rule will not be available as part of the token stream, regardless of
552  // channel.</p>
553  ///
554  
555  var Token = require('./Token').Token;
556  var BufferedTokenStream = require('./BufferedTokenStream').BufferedTokenStream;
557  
558  function CommonTokenStream(lexer, channel) {
559  	BufferedTokenStream.call(this, lexer);
560      this.channel = channel===undefined ? Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL : channel;
561      return this;
562  }
563  
564  CommonTokenStream.prototype = Object.create(BufferedTokenStream.prototype);
565  CommonTokenStream.prototype.constructor = CommonTokenStream;
566  
567  CommonTokenStream.prototype.adjustSeekIndex = function(i) {
568      return this.nextTokenOnChannel(i, this.channel);
569  };
570  
571  CommonTokenStream.prototype.LB = function(k) {
572      if (k===0 || this.index-k<0) {
573          return null;
574      }
575      var i = this.index;
576      var n = 1;
577      // find k good tokens looking backwards
578      while (n <= k) {
579          // skip off-channel tokens
580          i = this.previousTokenOnChannel(i - 1, this.channel);
581          n += 1;
582      }
583      if (i < 0) {
584          return null;
585      }
586      return this.tokens[i];
587  };
588  
589  CommonTokenStream.prototype.LT = function(k) {
590      this.lazyInit();
591      if (k === 0) {
592          return null;
593      }
594      if (k < 0) {
595          return this.LB(-k);
596      }
597      var i = this.index;
598      var n = 1; // we know tokens[pos] is a good one
599      // find k good tokens
600      while (n < k) {
601          // skip off-channel tokens, but make sure to not look past EOF
602          if (this.sync(i + 1)) {
603              i = this.nextTokenOnChannel(i + 1, this.channel);
604          }
605          n += 1;
606      }
607      return this.tokens[i];
608  };
609  
610  // Count EOF just once.///
611  CommonTokenStream.prototype.getNumberOfOnChannelTokens = function() {
612      var n = 0;
613      this.fill();
614      for (var i =0; i< this.tokens.length;i++) {
615          var t = this.tokens[i];
616          if( t.channel===this.channel) {
617              n += 1;
618          }
619          if( t.type===Token.EOF) {
620              break;
621          }
622      }
623      return n;
624  };
625  
626  exports.CommonTokenStream = CommonTokenStream;

656  //
657  /* Copyright (c) 2012-2017 The ANTLR Project. All rights reserved. 
658   * Use of this file is governed by the BSD 3-clause license that 
659   * can be found in the LICENSE.txt file in the project root. 
660   */
661  //
662  
663  var Token = require('./Token').Token;
664  require('./polyfills/codepointat');
665  require('./polyfills/fromcodepoint');
666  
667  // Vacuum all input from a string and then treat it like a buffer.
668  
669  function _loadString(stream, decodeToUnicodeCodePoints) {
670  	stream._index = 0;
671  	stream.data = [];
672  	if (stream.decodeToUnicodeCodePoints) {
673  		for (var i = 0; i < stream.strdata.length; ) {
674  			var codePoint = stream.strdata.codePointAt(i);
675  			stream.data.push(codePoint);
676  			i += codePoint <= 0xFFFF ? 1 : 2;
677  		}
678  	} else {
679  		for (var i = 0; i < stream.strdata.length; i++) {
680  			var codeUnit = stream.strdata.charCodeAt(i);
681  			stream.data.push(codeUnit);
682  		}
683  	}
684  	stream._size = stream.data.length;
685  }
686  
687  // If decodeToUnicodeCodePoints is true, the input is treated
688  // as a series of Unicode code points.
689  //
690  // Otherwise, the input is treated as a series of 16-bit UTF-16 code
691  // units.
692  function InputStream(data, decodeToUnicodeCodePoints) {
693  	this.name = "<empty>";
694  	this.strdata = data;
695  	this.decodeToUnicodeCodePoints = decodeToUnicodeCodePoints || false;
696  	_loadString(this);
697  	return this;
698  }
699  
700  Object.defineProperty(InputStream.prototype, "index", {
701  	get : function() {
702  		return this._index;
703  	}
704  });
705  
706  Object.defineProperty(InputStream.prototype, "size", {
707  	get : function() {
708  		return this._size;
709  	}
710  });
711  
712  // Reset the stream so that it's in the same state it was
713  // when the object was created *except* the data array is not
714  // touched.
715  //
716  InputStream.prototype.reset = function() {
717  	this._index = 0;
718  };
719  
720  InputStream.prototype.consume = function() {
721  	if (this._index >= this._size) {
722  		// assert this.LA(1) == Token.EOF
723  		throw ("cannot consume EOF");
724  	}
725  	this._index += 1;
726  };
727  
728  InputStream.prototype.LA = function(offset) {
729  	if (offset === 0) {
730  		return 0; // undefined
731  	}
732  	if (offset < 0) {
733  		offset += 1; // e.g., translate LA(-1) to use offset=0
734  	}
735  	var pos = this._index + offset - 1;
736  	if (pos < 0 || pos >= this._size) { // invalid
737  		return Token.EOF;
738  	}
739  	return this.data[pos];
740  };
741  
742  InputStream.prototype.LT = function(offset) {
743  	return this.LA(offset);
744  };
745  
746  // mark/release do nothing; we have entire buffer
747  InputStream.prototype.mark = function() {
748  	return -1;
749  };
750  
751  InputStream.prototype.release = function(marker) {
752  };
753  
754  // consume() ahead until p==_index; can't just set p=_index as we must
755  // update line and column. If we seek backwards, just set p
756  //
757  InputStream.prototype.seek = function(_index) {
758  	if (_index <= this._index) {
759  		this._index = _index; // just jump; don't update stream state (line,
760  								// ...)
761  		return;
762  	}
763  	// seek forward
764  	this._index = Math.min(_index, this._size);
765  };
766  
767  InputStream.prototype.getText = function(start, stop) {
768  	if (stop >= this._size) {
769  		stop = this._size - 1;
770  	}
771  	if (start >= this._size) {
772  		return "";
773  	} else {
774  		if (this.decodeToUnicodeCodePoints) {
775  			var result = "";
776  			for (var i = start; i <= stop; i++) {
777  				result += String.fromCodePoint(this.data[i]);
778  			}
779  			return result;
780  		} else {
781  			return this.strdata.slice(start, stop + 1);
782  		}
783  	}
784  };
785  
786  InputStream.prototype.toString = function() {
787  	return this.strdata;
788  };
789  
790  exports.InputStream = InputStream;

802  /* stop is not included! */
803  function Interval(start, stop) {
804  	this.start = start;
805  	this.stop = stop;
806  	return this;
807  }
808  
809  Interval.prototype.contains = function(item) {
810  	return item >= this.start && item < this.stop;
811  };
812  
813  Interval.prototype.toString = function() {
814  	if(this.start===this.stop-1) {
815  		return this.start.toString();
816  	} else {
817  		return this.start.toString() + ".." + (this.stop-1).toString();
818  	}
819  };
820  
821  
822  Object.defineProperty(Interval.prototype, "length", {
823  	get : function() {
824  		return this.stop - this.start;
825  	}
826  });
827  
828  function IntervalSet() {
829  	this.intervals = null;
830  	this.readOnly = false;
831  }
832  
833  IntervalSet.prototype.first = function(v) {
834  	if (this.intervals === null || this.intervals.length===0) {
835  		return Token.INVALID_TYPE;
836  	} else {
837  		return this.intervals[0].start;
838  	}
839  };
840  
841  IntervalSet.prototype.addOne = function(v) {
842  	this.addInterval(new Interval(v, v + 1));
843  };
844  
845  IntervalSet.prototype.addRange = function(l, h) {
846  	this.addInterval(new Interval(l, h + 1));
847  };
848  
849  IntervalSet.prototype.addInterval = function(v) {
850  	if (this.intervals === null) {
851  		this.intervals = [];
852  		this.intervals.push(v);
853  	} else {
854  		// find insert pos
855  		for (var k = 0; k < this.intervals.length; k++) {
856  			var i = this.intervals[k];
857  			// distinct range -> insert
858  			if (v.stop < i.start) {
859  				this.intervals.splice(k, 0, v);
860  				return;
861  			}
862  			// contiguous range -> adjust
863  			else if (v.stop === i.start) {
864  				this.intervals[k].start = v.start;
865  				return;
866  			}
867  			// overlapping range -> adjust and reduce
868  			else if (v.start <= i.stop) {
869  				this.intervals[k] = new Interval(Math.min(i.start, v.start), Math.max(i.stop, v.stop));
870  				this.reduce(k);
871  				return;
872  			}
873  		}
874  		// greater than any existing
875  		this.intervals.push(v);
876  	}
877  };
878  
879  IntervalSet.prototype.addSet = function(other) {
880  	if (other.intervals !== null) {
881  		for (var k = 0; k < other.intervals.length; k++) {
882  			var i = other.intervals[k];
883  			this.addInterval(new Interval(i.start, i.stop));
884  		}
885  	}
886  	return this;
887  };
888  
889  IntervalSet.prototype.reduce = function(k) {
890  	// only need to reduce if k is not the last
891  	if (k < this.intervalslength - 1) {
892  		var l = this.intervals[k];
893  		var r = this.intervals[k + 1];
894  		// if r contained in l
895  		if (l.stop >= r.stop) {
896  			this.intervals.pop(k + 1);
897  			this.reduce(k);
898  		} else if (l.stop >= r.start) {
899  			this.intervals[k] = new Interval(l.start, r.stop);
900  			this.intervals.pop(k + 1);
901  		}
902  	}
903  };
904  
905  IntervalSet.prototype.complement = function(start, stop) {
906      var result = new IntervalSet();
907      result.addInterval(new Interval(start,stop+1));
908      for(var i=0; i<this.intervals.length; i++) {
909          result.removeRange(this.intervals[i]);
910      }
911      return result;
912  };
913  
914  IntervalSet.prototype.contains = function(item) {
915  	if (this.intervals === null) {
916  		return false;
917  	} else {
918  		for (var k = 0; k < this.intervals.length; k++) {
919  			if(this.intervals[k].contains(item)) {
920  				return true;
921  			}
922  		}
923  		return false;
924  	}
925  };
926  
927  Object.defineProperty(IntervalSet.prototype, "length", {
928  	get : function() {
929  		var len = 0;
930  		this.intervals.map(function(i) {len += i.length;});
931  		return len;
932  	}
933  });
934  
935  IntervalSet.prototype.removeRange = function(v) {
936      if(v.start===v.stop-1) {
937          this.removeOne(v.start);
938      } else if (this.intervals!==null) {
939          var k = 0;
940          for(var n=0; n<this.intervals.length; n++) {
941              var i = this.intervals[k];
942              // intervals are ordered
943              if (v.stop<=i.start) {
944                  return;
945              }
946              // check for including range, split it
947              else if(v.start>i.start && v.stop<i.stop) {
948                  this.intervals[k] = new Interval(i.start, v.start);
949                  var x = new Interval(v.stop, i.stop);
950                  this.intervals.splice(k, 0, x);
951                  return;
952              }
953              // check for included range, remove it
954              else if(v.start<=i.start && v.stop>=i.stop) {
955                  this.intervals.splice(k, 1);
956                  k = k - 1; // need another pass
957              }
958              // check for lower boundary
959              else if(v.start<i.stop) {
960                  this.intervals[k] = new Interval(i.start, v.start);
961              }
962              // check for upper boundary
963              else if(v.stop<i.stop) {
964                  this.intervals[k] = new Interval(v.stop, i.stop);
965              }
966              k += 1;
967          }
968      }
969  };
970  
971  IntervalSet.prototype.removeOne = function(v) {
972  	if (this.intervals !== null) {
973  		for (var k = 0; k < this.intervals.length; k++) {
974  			var i = this.intervals[k];
975  			// intervals is ordered
976  			if (v < i.start) {
977  				return;
978  			}
979  			// check for single value range
980  			else if (v === i.start && v === i.stop - 1) {
981  				this.intervals.splice(k, 1);
982  				return;
983  			}
984  			// check for lower boundary
985  			else if (v === i.start) {
986  				this.intervals[k] = new Interval(i.start + 1, i.stop);
987  				return;
988  			}
989  			// check for upper boundary
990  			else if (v === i.stop - 1) {
991  				this.intervals[k] = new Interval(i.start, i.stop - 1);
992  				return;
993  			}
994  			// split existing range
995  			else if (v < i.stop - 1) {
996  				var x = new Interval(i.start, v);
997  				i.start = v + 1;
998  				this.intervals.splice(k, 0, x);
999  				return;
1000 			}
1001 		}
1002 	}
1003 };
1004 
1005 IntervalSet.prototype.toString = function(literalNames, symbolicNames, elemsAreChar) {
1006 	literalNames = literalNames || null;
1007 	symbolicNames = symbolicNames || null;
1008 	elemsAreChar = elemsAreChar || false;
1009 	if (this.intervals === null) {
1010 		return "{}";
1011 	} else if(literalNames!==null || symbolicNames!==null) {
1012 		return this.toTokenString(literalNames, symbolicNames);
1013 	} else if(elemsAreChar) {
1014 		return this.toCharString();
1015 	} else {
1016 		return this.toIndexString();
1017 	}
1018 };
1019 
1020 IntervalSet.prototype.toCharString = function() {
1021 	var names = [];
1022 	for (var i = 0; i < this.intervals.length; i++) {
1023 		var v = this.intervals[i];
1024 		if(v.stop===v.start+1) {
1025 			if ( v.start===Token.EOF ) {
1026 				names.push("<EOF>");
1027 			} else {
1028 				names.push("'" + String.fromCharCode(v.start) + "'");
1029 			}
1030 		} else {
1031 			names.push("'" + String.fromCharCode(v.start) + "'..'" + String.fromCharCode(v.stop-1) + "'");
1032 		}
1033 	}
1034 	if (names.length > 1) {
1035 		return "{" + names.join(", ") + "}";
1036 	} else {
1037 		return names[0];
1038 	}
1039 };
1040 
1041 
1042 IntervalSet.prototype.toIndexString = function() {
1043 	var names = [];
1044 	for (var i = 0; i < this.intervals.length; i++) {
1045 		var v = this.intervals[i];
1046 		if(v.stop===v.start+1) {
1047 			if ( v.start===Token.EOF ) {
1048 				names.push("<EOF>");
1049 			} else {
1050 				names.push(v.start.toString());
1051 			}
1052 		} else {
1053 			names.push(v.start.toString() + ".." + (v.stop-1).toString());
1054 		}
1055 	}
1056 	if (names.length > 1) {
1057 		return "{" + names.join(", ") + "}";
1058 	} else {
1059 		return names[0];
1060 	}
1061 };
1062 
1063 
1064 IntervalSet.prototype.toTokenString = function(literalNames, symbolicNames) {
1065 	var names = [];
1066 	for (var i = 0; i < this.intervals.length; i++) {
1067 		var v = this.intervals[i];
1068 		for (var j = v.start; j < v.stop; j++) {
1069 			names.push(this.elementName(literalNames, symbolicNames, j));
1070 		}
1071 	}
1072 	if (names.length > 1) {
1073 		return "{" + names.join(", ") + "}";
1074 	} else {
1075 		return names[0];
1076 	}
1077 };
1078 
1079 IntervalSet.prototype.elementName = function(literalNames, symbolicNames, a) {
1080 	if (a === Token.EOF) {
1081 		return "<EOF>";
1082 	} else if (a === Token.EPSILON) {
1083 		return "<EPSILON>";
1084 	} else {
1085 		return literalNames[a] || symbolicNames[a];
1086 	}
1087 };

1089 exports.Interval = Interval;
1090 exports.IntervalSet = IntervalSet;

1100 var Set = require('./Utils').Set;
1101 var BitSet = require('./Utils').BitSet;
1102 var Token = require('./Token').Token;
1103 var ATNConfig = require('./atn/ATNConfig').ATNConfig;
1104 var Interval = require('./IntervalSet').Interval;
1105 var IntervalSet = require('./IntervalSet').IntervalSet;
1106 var RuleStopState = require('./atn/ATNState').RuleStopState;
1107 var RuleTransition = require('./atn/Transition').RuleTransition;
1108 var NotSetTransition = require('./atn/Transition').NotSetTransition;
1109 var WildcardTransition = require('./atn/Transition').WildcardTransition;

1117 function LL1Analyzer (atn) {
1118     this.atn = atn;
1119 }
1120 
1121 //* Special value added to the lookahead sets to indicate that we hit
1122 //  a predicate during analysis if {@code seeThruPreds==false}.
1123 ///
1124 LL1Analyzer.HIT_PRED = Token.INVALID_TYPE;
1125 
1126 
1127 //*
1128 // Calculates the SLL(1) expected lookahead set for each outgoing transition
1129 // of an {@link ATNState}. The returned array has one element for each
1130 // outgoing transition in {@code s}. If the closure from transition
1131 // <em>i</em> leads to a semantic predicate before matching a symbol, the
1132 // element at index <em>i</em> of the result will be {@code null}.
1133 //
1134 // @param s the ATN state
1135 // @return the expected symbols for each outgoing transition of {@code s}.
1136 ///
1137 LL1Analyzer.prototype.getDecisionLookahead = function(s) {
1138     if (s === null) {
1139         return null;
1140     }
1141     var count = s.transitions.length;
1142     var look = [];
1143     for(var alt=0; alt< count; alt++) {
1144         look[alt] = new IntervalSet();
1145         var lookBusy = new Set();
1146         var seeThruPreds = false; // fail to get lookahead upon pred
1147         this._LOOK(s.transition(alt).target, null, PredictionContext.EMPTY,
1148               look[alt], lookBusy, new BitSet(), seeThruPreds, false);
1149         // Wipe out lookahead for this alternative if we found nothing
1150         // or we had a predicate when we !seeThruPreds
1151         if (look[alt].length===0 || look[alt].contains(LL1Analyzer.HIT_PRED)) {
1152             look[alt] = null;
1153         }
1154     }
1155     return look;
1156 };
1157 
1158 //*
1159 // Compute set of tokens that can follow {@code s} in the ATN in the
1160 // specified {@code ctx}.
1161 //
1162 // <p>If {@code ctx} is {@code null} and the end of the rule containing
1163 // {@code s} is reached, {@link Token//EPSILON} is added to the result set.
1164 // If {@code ctx} is not {@code null} and the end of the outermost rule is
1165 // reached, {@link Token//EOF} is added to the result set.</p>
1166 //
1167 // @param s the ATN state
1168 // @param stopState the ATN state to stop at. This can be a
1169 // {@link BlockEndState} to detect epsilon paths through a closure.
1170 // @param ctx the complete parser context, or {@code null} if the context
1171 // should be ignored
1172 //
1173 // @return The set of tokens that can follow {@code s} in the ATN in the
1174 // specified {@code ctx}.
1175 ///
1176 LL1Analyzer.prototype.LOOK = function(s, stopState, ctx) {
1177     var r = new IntervalSet();
1178     var seeThruPreds = true; // ignore preds; get all lookahead
1179 	ctx = ctx || null;
1180     var lookContext = ctx!==null ? predictionContextFromRuleContext(s.atn, ctx) : null;
1181     this._LOOK(s, stopState, lookContext, r, new Set(), new BitSet(), seeThruPreds, true);
1182     return r;
1183 };
1184 
1185 //*
1186 // Compute set of tokens that can follow {@code s} in the ATN in the
1187 // specified {@code ctx}.
1188 //
1189 // <p>If {@code ctx} is {@code null} and {@code stopState} or the end of the
1190 // rule containing {@code s} is reached, {@link Token//EPSILON} is added to
1191 // the result set. If {@code ctx} is not {@code null} and {@code addEOF} is
1192 // {@code true} and {@code stopState} or the end of the outermost rule is
1193 // reached, {@link Token//EOF} is added to the result set.</p>
1194 //
1195 // @param s the ATN state.
1196 // @param stopState the ATN state to stop at. This can be a
1197 // {@link BlockEndState} to detect epsilon paths through a closure.
1198 // @param ctx The outer context, or {@code null} if the outer context should
1199 // not be used.
1200 // @param look The result lookahead set.
1201 // @param lookBusy A set used for preventing epsilon closures in the ATN
1202 // from causing a stack overflow. Outside code should pass
1203 // {@code new Set<ATNConfig>} for this argument.
1204 // @param calledRuleStack A set used for preventing left recursion in the
1205 // ATN from causing a stack overflow. Outside code should pass
1206 // {@code new BitSet()} for this argument.
1207 // @param seeThruPreds {@code true} to true semantic predicates as
1208 // implicitly {@code true} and "see through them", otherwise {@code false}
1209 // to treat semantic predicates as opaque and add {@link //HIT_PRED} to the
1210 // result if one is encountered.
1211 // @param addEOF Add {@link Token//EOF} to the result if the end of the
1212 // outermost context is reached. This parameter has no effect if {@code ctx}
1213 // is {@code null}.
1214 ///
1215 LL1Analyzer.prototype._LOOK = function(s, stopState , ctx, look, lookBusy, calledRuleStack, seeThruPreds, addEOF) {
1216     var c = new ATNConfig({state:s, alt:0, context: ctx}, null);
1217     if (lookBusy.contains(c)) {
1218         return;
1219     }
1220     lookBusy.add(c);
1221     if (s === stopState) {
1222         if (ctx ===null) {
1223             look.addOne(Token.EPSILON);
1224             return;
1225         } else if (ctx.isEmpty() && addEOF) {
1226             look.addOne(Token.EOF);
1227             return;
1228         }
1229     }
1230     if (s instanceof RuleStopState ) {
1231         if (ctx ===null) {
1232             look.addOne(Token.EPSILON);
1233             return;
1234         } else if (ctx.isEmpty() && addEOF) {
1235             look.addOne(Token.EOF);
1236             return;
1237         }
1238         if (ctx !== PredictionContext.EMPTY) {
1239             // run thru all possible stack tops in ctx
1240             for(var i=0; i<ctx.length; i++) {
1241                 var returnState = this.atn.states[ctx.getReturnState(i)];
1242                 var removed = calledRuleStack.contains(returnState.ruleIndex);
1243                 try {
1244                     calledRuleStack.remove(returnState.ruleIndex);
1245                     this._LOOK(returnState, stopState, ctx.getParent(i), look, lookBusy, calledRuleStack, seeThruPreds, addEOF);
1246                 } finally {
1247                     if (removed) {
1248                         calledRuleStack.add(returnState.ruleIndex);
1249                     }
1250                 }
1251             }
1252             return;
1253         }
1254     }
1255     for(var j=0; j<s.transitions.length; j++) {
1256         var t = s.transitions[j];
1257         if (t.constructor === RuleTransition) {
1258             if (calledRuleStack.contains(t.target.ruleIndex)) {
1259                 continue;
1260             }
1261             var newContext = SingletonPredictionContext.create(ctx, t.followState.stateNumber);
1262             try {
1263                 calledRuleStack.add(t.target.ruleIndex);
1264                 this._LOOK(t.target, stopState, newContext, look, lookBusy, calledRuleStack, seeThruPreds, addEOF);
1265             } finally {
1266                 calledRuleStack.remove(t.target.ruleIndex);
1267             }
1268         } else if (t instanceof AbstractPredicateTransition ) {
1269             if (seeThruPreds) {
1270                 this._LOOK(t.target, stopState, ctx, look, lookBusy, calledRuleStack, seeThruPreds, addEOF);
1271             } else {
1272                 look.addOne(LL1Analyzer.HIT_PRED);
1273             }
1274         } else if( t.isEpsilon) {
1275             this._LOOK(t.target, stopState, ctx, look, lookBusy, calledRuleStack, seeThruPreds, addEOF);
1276         } else if (t.constructor === WildcardTransition) {
1277             look.addRange( Token.MIN_USER_TOKEN_TYPE, this.atn.maxTokenType );
1278         } else {
1279             var set = t.label;
1280             if (set !== null) {
1281                 if (t instanceof NotSetTransition) {
1282                     set = set.complement(Token.MIN_USER_TOKEN_TYPE, this.atn.maxTokenType);
1283                 }
1284                 look.addSet(set);
1285             }
1286         }
1287     }
1288 };

1300 // A lexer is recognizer that draws input symbols from a character stream.
1301 //  lexer grammars result in a subclass of this object. A Lexer object
1302 //  uses simplified match() and error recovery mechanisms in the interest of speed.
1303 
1304 var Token = require('./Token').Token;
1305 var Recognizer = require('./Recognizer').Recognizer;
1306 var CommonTokenFactory = require('./CommonTokenFactory').CommonTokenFactory;
1307 var RecognitionException  = require('./error/Errors').RecognitionException;
1308 var LexerNoViableAltException = require('./error/Errors').LexerNoViableAltException;
1309 
1310 function TokenSource() {
1311 	return this;
1312 }
1313 
1314 function Lexer(input) {
1315 	Recognizer.call(this);
1316 	this._input = input;
1317 	this._factory = CommonTokenFactory.DEFAULT;
1318 	this._tokenFactorySourcePair = [ this, input ];
1319 
1320 	this._interp = null; // child classes must populate this
1321 
1322 	// The goal of all lexer rules/methods is to create a token object.
1323 	// this is an instance variable as multiple rules may collaborate to
1324 	// create a single token. nextToken will return this object after
1325 	// matching lexer rule(s). If you subclass to allow multiple token
1326 	// emissions, then set this to the last token to be matched or
1327 	// something nonnull so that the auto token emit mechanism will not
1328 	// emit another token.
1329 	this._token = null;
1330 
1331 	// What character index in the stream did the current token start at?
1332 	// Needed, for example, to get the text for current token. Set at
1333 	// the start of nextToken.
1334 	this._tokenStartCharIndex = -1;
1335 
1336 	// The line on which the first character of the token resides///
1337 	this._tokenStartLine = -1;
1338 
1339 	// The character position of first character within the line///
1340 	this._tokenStartColumn = -1;
1341 
1342 	// Once we see EOF on char stream, next token will be EOF.
1343 	// If you have DONE : EOF ; then you see DONE EOF.
1344 	this._hitEOF = false;
1345 
1346 	// The channel number for the current token///
1347 	this._channel = Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL;
1348 
1349 	// The token type for the current token///
1350 	this._type = Token.INVALID_TYPE;
1351 
1352 	this._modeStack = [];
1353 	this._mode = Lexer.DEFAULT_MODE;
1354 
1355 	// You can set the text for the current token to override what is in
1356 	// the input char buffer. Use setText() or can set this instance var.
1357 	// /
1358 	this._text = null;
1359 
1360 	return this;
1361 }
1362 
1363 Lexer.prototype = Object.create(Recognizer.prototype);
1364 Lexer.prototype.constructor = Lexer;
1365 
1366 Lexer.DEFAULT_MODE = 0;
1367 Lexer.MORE = -2;
1368 Lexer.SKIP = -3;
1369 
1370 Lexer.DEFAULT_TOKEN_CHANNEL = Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL;
1371 Lexer.HIDDEN = Token.HIDDEN_CHANNEL;
1372 Lexer.MIN_CHAR_VALUE = 0x0000;
1373 Lexer.MAX_CHAR_VALUE = 0x10FFFF;
1374 
1375 Lexer.prototype.reset = function() {
1376 	// wack Lexer state variables
1377 	if (this._input !== null) {
1378 		this._input.seek(0); // rewind the input
1379 	}
1380 	this._token = null;
1381 	this._type = Token.INVALID_TYPE;
1382 	this._channel = Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL;
1383 	this._tokenStartCharIndex = -1;
1384 	this._tokenStartColumn = -1;
1385 	this._tokenStartLine = -1;
1386 	this._text = null;
1387 
1388 	this._hitEOF = false;
1389 	this._mode = Lexer.DEFAULT_MODE;
1390 	this._modeStack = [];
1391 
1392 	this._interp.reset();
1393 };
1394 
1395 // Return a token from this source; i.e., match a token on the char stream.
1396 Lexer.prototype.nextToken = function() {
1397 	if (this._input === null) {
1398 		throw "nextToken requires a non-null input stream.";
1399 	}
1400 
1401 	// Mark start location in char stream so unbuffered streams are
1402 	// guaranteed at least have text of current token
1403 	var tokenStartMarker = this._input.mark();
1404 	try {
1405 		while (true) {
1406 			if (this._hitEOF) {
1407 				this.emitEOF();
1408 				return this._token;
1409 			}
1410 			this._token = null;
1411 			this._channel = Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL;
1412 			this._tokenStartCharIndex = this._input.index;
1413 			this._tokenStartColumn = this._interp.column;
1414 			this._tokenStartLine = this._interp.line;
1415 			this._text = null;
1416 			var continueOuter = false;
1417 			while (true) {
1418 				this._type = Token.INVALID_TYPE;
1419 				var ttype = Lexer.SKIP;
1420 				try {
1421 					ttype = this._interp.match(this._input, this._mode);
1422 				} catch (e) {
1423 				    if(e instanceof RecognitionException) {
1424                         this.notifyListeners(e); // report error
1425                         this.recover(e);
1426                     } else {
1427                         console.log(e.stack);
1428                         throw e;
1429                     }
1430 				}
1431 				if (this._input.LA(1) === Token.EOF) {
1432 					this._hitEOF = true;
1433 				}
1434 				if (this._type === Token.INVALID_TYPE) {
1435 					this._type = ttype;
1436 				}
1437 				if (this._type === Lexer.SKIP) {
1438 					continueOuter = true;
1439 					break;
1440 				}
1441 				if (this._type !== Lexer.MORE) {
1442 					break;
1443 				}
1444 			}
1445 			if (continueOuter) {
1446 				continue;
1447 			}
1448 			if (this._token === null) {
1449 				this.emit();
1450 			}
1451 			return this._token;
1452 		}
1453 	} finally {
1454 		// make sure we release marker after match or
1455 		// unbuffered char stream will keep buffering
1456 		this._input.release(tokenStartMarker);
1457 	}
1458 };
1459 
1460 // Instruct the lexer to skip creating a token for current lexer rule
1461 // and look for another token. nextToken() knows to keep looking when
1462 // a lexer rule finishes with token set to SKIP_TOKEN. Recall that
1463 // if token==null at end of any token rule, it creates one for you
1464 // and emits it.
1465 // /
1466 Lexer.prototype.skip = function() {
1467 	this._type = Lexer.SKIP;
1468 };
1469 
1470 Lexer.prototype.more = function() {
1471 	this._type = Lexer.MORE;
1472 };
1473 
1474 Lexer.prototype.mode = function(m) {
1475 	this._mode = m;
1476 };
1477 
1478 Lexer.prototype.pushMode = function(m) {
1479 	if (this._interp.debug) {
1480 		console.log("pushMode " + m);
1481 	}
1482 	this._modeStack.push(this._mode);
1483 	this.mode(m);
1484 };
1485 
1486 Lexer.prototype.popMode = function() {
1487 	if (this._modeStack.length === 0) {
1488 		throw "Empty Stack";
1489 	}
1490 	if (this._interp.debug) {
1491 		console.log("popMode back to " + this._modeStack.slice(0, -1));
1492 	}
1493 	this.mode(this._modeStack.pop());
1494 	return this._mode;
1495 };

1501 	},

1507 		this._tokenFactorySourcePair = [ this, this._input ];

1517 // By default does not support multiple emits per nextToken invocation
1518 // for efficiency reasons. Subclass and override this method, nextToken,
1519 // and getToken (to push tokens into a list and pull from that list
1520 // rather than a single variable as this implementation does).
1521 // /
1522 Lexer.prototype.emitToken = function(token) {
1523 	this._token = token;

1526 // The standard method called to automatically emit a token at the
1527 // outermost lexical rule. The token object should point into the
1528 // char buffer start..stop. If there is a text override in 'text',
1529 // use that to set the token's text. Override this method to emit
1530 // custom Token objects or provide a new factory.
1531 // /
1532 Lexer.prototype.emit = function() {
1533 	var t = this._factory.create(this._tokenFactorySourcePair, this._type,
1534 			this._text, this._channel, this._tokenStartCharIndex, this
1535 					.getCharIndex() - 1, this._tokenStartLine,
1536 			this._tokenStartColumn);
1537 	this.emitToken(t);
1538 	return t;
1539 };
1540 
1541 Lexer.prototype.emitEOF = function() {
1542 	var cpos = this.column;
1543 	var lpos = this.line;
1544 	var eof = this._factory.create(this._tokenFactorySourcePair, Token.EOF,
1545 			null, Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL, this._input.index,
1546 			this._input.index - 1, lpos, cpos);
1547 	this.emitToken(eof);
1548 	return eof;
1549 };

1598 // Return a list of all Token objects in input char stream.
1599 // Forces load of all tokens. Does not include EOF token.
1600 // /
1601 Lexer.prototype.getAllTokens = function() {
1602 	var tokens = [];
1603 	var t = this.nextToken();
1604 	while (t.type !== Token.EOF) {
1605 		tokens.push(t);
1606 		t = this.nextToken();
1607 	}
1608 	return tokens;
1609 };

1611 Lexer.prototype.notifyListeners = function(e) {
1612 	var start = this._tokenStartCharIndex;
1613 	var stop = this._input.index;
1614 	var text = this._input.getText(start, stop);
1615 	var msg = "token recognition error at: '" + this.getErrorDisplay(text) + "'";
1616 	var listener = this.getErrorListenerDispatch();
1617 	listener.syntaxError(this, null, this._tokenStartLine,
1618 			this._tokenStartColumn, msg, e);
1619 };
1620 
1621 Lexer.prototype.getErrorDisplay = function(s) {
1622 	var d = [];
1623 	for (var i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
1624 		d.push(s[i]);
1625 	}
1626 	return d.join('');
1627 };
1628 
1629 Lexer.prototype.getErrorDisplayForChar = function(c) {
1630 	if (c.charCodeAt(0) === Token.EOF) {
1631 		return "<EOF>";
1632 	} else if (c === '\n') {
1633 		return "\\n";
1634 	} else if (c === '\t') {
1635 		return "\\t";
1636 	} else if (c === '\r') {
1637 		return "\\r";
1638 	} else {
1639 		return c;
1640 	}
1641 };
1642 
1643 Lexer.prototype.getCharErrorDisplay = function(c) {
1644 	return "'" + this.getErrorDisplayForChar(c) + "'";
1645 };

1647 // Lexers can normally match any char in it's vocabulary after matching
1648 // a token, so do the easy thing and just kill a character and hope
1649 // it all works out. You can instead use the rule invocation stack
1650 // to do sophisticated error recovery if you are in a fragment rule.
1651 // /
1652 Lexer.prototype.recover = function(re) {
1653 	if (this._input.LA(1) !== Token.EOF) {
1654 		if (re instanceof LexerNoViableAltException) {
1655 			// skip a char and try again
1656 			this._interp.consume(this._input);
1657 		} else {
1658 			// TODO: Do we lose character or line position information?
1659 			this._input.consume();
1660 		}
1661 	}
1662 };

1702 // this is all the parsing support code essentially; most of it is error
1703 // recovery stuff.//
1704 function Parser(input) {
1705 	Recognizer.call(this);
1706 	// The input stream.
1707 	this._input = null;
1708 	// The error handling strategy for the parser. The default value is a new
1709 	// instance of {@link DefaultErrorStrategy}.
1710 	this._errHandler = new DefaultErrorStrategy();
1711 	this._precedenceStack = [];
1712 	this._precedenceStack.push(0);
1713 	// The {@link ParserRuleContext} object for the currently executing rule.
1714 	// this is always non-null during the parsing process.
1715 	this._ctx = null;
1716 	// Specifies whether or not the parser should construct a parse tree during
1717 	// the parsing process. The default value is {@code true}.
1718 	this.buildParseTrees = true;
1719 	// When {@link //setTrace}{@code (true)} is called, a reference to the
1720 	// {@link TraceListener} is stored here so it can be easily removed in a
1721 	// later call to {@link //setTrace}{@code (false)}. The listener itself is
1722 	// implemented as a parser listener so this field is not directly used by
1723 	// other parser methods.
1724 	this._tracer = null;
1725 	// The list of {@link ParseTreeListener} listeners registered to receive
1726 	// events during the parse.
1727 	this._parseListeners = null;
1728 	// The number of syntax errors reported during parsing. this value is
1729 	// incremented each time {@link //notifyErrorListeners} is called.
1730 	this._syntaxErrors = 0;
1731 	this.setInputStream(input);
1732 	return this;
1733 }
1734 
1735 Parser.prototype = Object.create(Recognizer.prototype);
1736 Parser.prototype.contructor = Parser;
1737 
1738 // this field maps from the serialized ATN string to the deserialized {@link
1739 // ATN} with
1740 // bypass alternatives.
1741 //
1742 // @see ATNDeserializationOptions//isGenerateRuleBypassTransitions()
1743 //
1744 Parser.bypassAltsAtnCache = {};
1745 
1746 // reset the parser's state//
1747 Parser.prototype.reset = function() {
1748 	if (this._input !== null) {
1749 		this._input.seek(0);
1750 	}
1751 	this._errHandler.reset(this);
1752 	this._ctx = null;
1753 	this._syntaxErrors = 0;
1754 	this.setTrace(false);
1755 	this._precedenceStack = [];
1756 	this._precedenceStack.push(0);
1757 	if (this._interp !== null) {
1758 		this._interp.reset();
1759 	}
1760 };

1762 // Match current input symbol against {@code ttype}. If the symbol type
1763 // matches, {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//reportMatch} and {@link //consume} are
1764 // called to complete the match process.
1765 //
1766 // <p>If the symbol type does not match,
1767 // {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//recoverInline} is called on the current error
1768 // strategy to attempt recovery. If {@link //getBuildParseTree} is
1769 // {@code true} and the token index of the symbol returned by
1770 // {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//recoverInline} is -1, the symbol is added to
1771 // the parse tree by calling {@link ParserRuleContext//addErrorNode}.</p>
1772 //
1773 // @param ttype the token type to match
1774 // @return the matched symbol
1775 // @throws RecognitionException if the current input symbol did not match
1776 // {@code ttype} and the error strategy could not recover from the
1777 // mismatched symbol
1778 
1779 Parser.prototype.match = function(ttype) {
1780 	var t = this.getCurrentToken();
1781 	if (t.type === ttype) {
1782 		this._errHandler.reportMatch(this);
1783 		this.consume();
1784 	} else {
1785 		t = this._errHandler.recoverInline(this);
1786 		if (this.buildParseTrees && t.tokenIndex === -1) {
1787 			// we must have conjured up a new token during single token
1788 			// insertion
1789 			// if it's not the current symbol
1790 			this._ctx.addErrorNode(t);
1791 		}
1792 	}
1793 	return t;
1794 };
1795 // Match current input symbol as a wildcard. If the symbol type matches
1796 // (i.e. has a value greater than 0), {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//reportMatch}
1797 // and {@link //consume} are called to complete the match process.
1798 //
1799 // <p>If the symbol type does not match,
1800 // {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//recoverInline} is called on the current error
1801 // strategy to attempt recovery. If {@link //getBuildParseTree} is
1802 // {@code true} and the token index of the symbol returned by
1803 // {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//recoverInline} is -1, the symbol is added to
1804 // the parse tree by calling {@link ParserRuleContext//addErrorNode}.</p>
1805 //
1806 // @return the matched symbol
1807 // @throws RecognitionException if the current input symbol did not match
1808 // a wildcard and the error strategy could not recover from the mismatched
1809 // symbol
1810 
1811 Parser.prototype.matchWildcard = function() {
1812 	var t = this.getCurrentToken();
1813 	if (t.type > 0) {
1814 		this._errHandler.reportMatch(this);
1815 		this.consume();
1816 	} else {
1817 		t = this._errHandler.recoverInline(this);
1818 		if (this._buildParseTrees && t.tokenIndex === -1) {
1819 			// we must have conjured up a new token during single token
1820 			// insertion
1821 			// if it's not the current symbol
1822 			this._ctx.addErrorNode(t);
1823 		}
1824 	}
1825 	return t;
1826 };
1827 
1828 Parser.prototype.getParseListeners = function() {
1829 	return this._parseListeners || [];
1830 };
1831 
1832 // Registers {@code listener} to receive events during the parsing process.
1833 //
1834 // <p>To support output-preserving grammar transformations (including but not
1835 // limited to left-recursion removal, automated left-factoring, and
1836 // optimized code generation), calls to listener methods during the parse
1837 // may differ substantially from calls made by
1838 // {@link ParseTreeWalker//DEFAULT} used after the parse is complete. In
1839 // particular, rule entry and exit events may occur in a different order
1840 // during the parse than after the parser. In addition, calls to certain
1841 // rule entry methods may be omitted.</p>
1842 //
1843 // <p>With the following specific exceptions, calls to listener events are
1844 // <em>deterministic</em>, i.e. for identical input the calls to listener
1845 // methods will be the same.</p>
1846 //
1847 // <ul>
1848 // <li>Alterations to the grammar used to generate code may change the
1849 // behavior of the listener calls.</li>
1850 // <li>Alterations to the command line options passed to ANTLR 4 when
1851 // generating the parser may change the behavior of the listener calls.</li>
1852 // <li>Changing the version of the ANTLR Tool used to generate the parser
1853 // may change the behavior of the listener calls.</li>
1854 // </ul>
1855 //
1856 // @param listener the listener to add
1857 //
1858 // @throws NullPointerException if {@code} listener is {@code null}
1859 //
1860 Parser.prototype.addParseListener = function(listener) {
1861 	if (listener === null) {
1862 		throw "listener";
1863 	}
1864 	if (this._parseListeners === null) {
1865 		this._parseListeners = [];
1866 	}
1867 	this._parseListeners.push(listener);
1868 };
1869 
1870 //
1871 // Remove {@code listener} from the list of parse listeners.
1872 //
1873 // <p>If {@code listener} is {@code null} or has not been added as a parse
1874 // listener, this method does nothing.</p>
1875 // @param listener the listener to remove
1876 //
1877 Parser.prototype.removeParseListener = function(listener) {
1878 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
1879 		var idx = this._parseListeners.indexOf(listener);
1880 		if (idx >= 0) {
1881 			this._parseListeners.splice(idx, 1);
1882 		}
1883 		if (this._parseListeners.length === 0) {
1884 			this._parseListeners = null;
1885 		}
1886 	}
1887 };
1888 
1889 // Remove all parse listeners.
1890 Parser.prototype.removeParseListeners = function() {
1891 	this._parseListeners = null;
1892 };

1894 // Notify any parse listeners of an enter rule event.
1895 Parser.prototype.triggerEnterRuleEvent = function() {
1896 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
1897         var ctx = this._ctx;
1898 		this._parseListeners.map(function(listener) {
1899 			listener.enterEveryRule(ctx);
1900 			ctx.enterRule(listener);
1901 		});
1902 	}
1903 };
1904 
1905 //
1906 // Notify any parse listeners of an exit rule event.
1907 //
1908 // @see //addParseListener
1909 //
1910 Parser.prototype.triggerExitRuleEvent = function() {
1911 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
1912 		// reverse order walk of listeners
1913         var ctx = this._ctx;
1914 		this._parseListeners.slice(0).reverse().map(function(listener) {
1915 			ctx.exitRule(listener);
1916 			listener.exitEveryRule(ctx);
1917 		});
1918 	}
1919 };

1930 // The ATN with bypass alternatives is expensive to create so we create it
1931 // lazily.
1932 //
1933 // @throws UnsupportedOperationException if the current parser does not
1934 // implement the {@link //getSerializedATN()} method.
1935 //
1936 Parser.prototype.getATNWithBypassAlts = function() {
1937 	var serializedAtn = this.getSerializedATN();
1938 	if (serializedAtn === null) {
1939 		throw "The current parser does not support an ATN with bypass alternatives.";
1940 	}
1941 	var result = this.bypassAltsAtnCache[serializedAtn];
1942 	if (result === null) {
1943 		var deserializationOptions = new ATNDeserializationOptions();
1944 		deserializationOptions.generateRuleBypassTransitions = true;
1945 		result = new ATNDeserializer(deserializationOptions)
1946 				.deserialize(serializedAtn);
1947 		this.bypassAltsAtnCache[serializedAtn] = result;
1948 	}
1949 	return result;
1950 };

1952 // The preferred method of getting a tree pattern. For example, here's a
1953 // sample use:
1954 //
1955 // <pre>
1956 // ParseTree t = parser.expr();
1957 // ParseTreePattern p = parser.compileParseTreePattern("&lt;ID&gt;+0",
1958 // MyParser.RULE_expr);
1959 // ParseTreeMatch m = p.match(t);
1960 // String id = m.get("ID");
1961 // </pre>
1962 
1963 var Lexer = require('./Lexer').Lexer;
1964 
1965 Parser.prototype.compileParseTreePattern = function(pattern, patternRuleIndex, lexer) {
1966 	lexer = lexer || null;
1967 	if (lexer === null) {
1968 		if (this.getTokenStream() !== null) {
1969 			var tokenSource = this.getTokenStream().tokenSource;
1970 			if (tokenSource instanceof Lexer) {
1971 				lexer = tokenSource;
1972 			}
1973 		}
1974 	}
1975 	if (lexer === null) {
1976 		throw "Parser can't discover a lexer to use";
1977 	}
1978 	var m = new ParseTreePatternMatcher(lexer, this);
1979 	return m.compile(pattern, patternRuleIndex);
1980 };

2008 Parser.prototype.notifyErrorListeners = function(msg, offendingToken, err) {
2009 	offendingToken = offendingToken || null;
2010 	err = err || null;
2011 	if (offendingToken === null) {
2012 		offendingToken = this.getCurrentToken();
2013 	}
2014 	this._syntaxErrors += 1;
2015 	var line = offendingToken.line;
2016 	var column = offendingToken.column;
2017 	var listener = this.getErrorListenerDispatch();
2018 	listener.syntaxError(this, offendingToken, line, column, msg, err);
2019 };

2021 //
2022 // Consume and return the {@linkplain //getCurrentToken current symbol}.
2023 //
2024 // <p>E.g., given the following input with {@code A} being the current
2025 // lookahead symbol, this function moves the cursor to {@code B} and returns
2026 // {@code A}.</p>
2027 //
2028 // <pre>
2029 // A B
2030 // ^
2031 // </pre>
2032 //
2033 // If the parser is not in error recovery mode, the consumed symbol is added
2034 // to the parse tree using {@link ParserRuleContext//addChild(Token)}, and
2035 // {@link ParseTreeListener//visitTerminal} is called on any parse listeners.
2036 // If the parser <em>is</em> in error recovery mode, the consumed symbol is
2037 // added to the parse tree using
2038 // {@link ParserRuleContext//addErrorNode(Token)}, and
2039 // {@link ParseTreeListener//visitErrorNode} is called on any parse
2040 // listeners.
2041 //
2042 Parser.prototype.consume = function() {
2043 	var o = this.getCurrentToken();
2044 	if (o.type !== Token.EOF) {
2045 		this.getInputStream().consume();
2046 	}
2047 	var hasListener = this._parseListeners !== null && this._parseListeners.length > 0;
2048 	if (this.buildParseTrees || hasListener) {
2049 		var node;
2050 		if (this._errHandler.inErrorRecoveryMode(this)) {
2051 			node = this._ctx.addErrorNode(o);
2052 		} else {
2053 			node = this._ctx.addTokenNode(o);
2054 		}
2055         node.invokingState = this.state;
2056 		if (hasListener) {
2057 			this._parseListeners.map(function(listener) {
2058 				if (node instanceof ErrorNode || (node.isErrorNode !== undefined && node.isErrorNode())) {
2059 					listener.visitErrorNode(node);
2060 				} else if (node instanceof TerminalNode) {
2061 					listener.visitTerminal(node);
2062 				}
2063 			});
2064 		}
2065 	}
2066 	return o;
2067 };
2068 
2069 Parser.prototype.addContextToParseTree = function() {
2070 	// add current context to parent if we have a parent
2071 	if (this._ctx.parentCtx !== null) {
2072 		this._ctx.parentCtx.addChild(this._ctx);
2073 	}
2074 };

2076 // Always called by generated parsers upon entry to a rule. Access field
2077 // {@link //_ctx} get the current context.
2078 
2079 Parser.prototype.enterRule = function(localctx, state, ruleIndex) {
2080 	this.state = state;
2081 	this._ctx = localctx;
2082 	this._ctx.start = this._input.LT(1);
2083 	if (this.buildParseTrees) {
2084 		this.addContextToParseTree();
2085 	}
2086 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
2087 		this.triggerEnterRuleEvent();
2088 	}
2089 };
2090 
2091 Parser.prototype.exitRule = function() {
2092 	this._ctx.stop = this._input.LT(-1);
2093 	// trigger event on _ctx, before it reverts to parent
2094 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
2095 		this.triggerExitRuleEvent();
2096 	}
2097 	this.state = this._ctx.invokingState;
2098 	this._ctx = this._ctx.parentCtx;
2099 };

2101 Parser.prototype.enterOuterAlt = function(localctx, altNum) {
2102    	localctx.setAltNumber(altNum);
2103 	// if we have new localctx, make sure we replace existing ctx
2104 	// that is previous child of parse tree
2105 	if (this.buildParseTrees && this._ctx !== localctx) {
2106 		if (this._ctx.parentCtx !== null) {
2107 			this._ctx.parentCtx.removeLastChild();
2108 			this._ctx.parentCtx.addChild(localctx);
2109 		}
2110 	}
2111 	this._ctx = localctx;
2112 };

2119 Parser.prototype.getPrecedence = function() {
2120 	if (this._precedenceStack.length === 0) {
2121 		return -1;
2122 	} else {
2123 		return this._precedenceStack[this._precedenceStack.length-1];
2124 	}

2127 Parser.prototype.enterRecursionRule = function(localctx, state, ruleIndex,
2128 		precedence) {
2129 	this.state = state;
2130 	this._precedenceStack.push(precedence);
2131 	this._ctx = localctx;
2132 	this._ctx.start = this._input.LT(1);
2133 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
2134 		this.triggerEnterRuleEvent(); // simulates rule entry for
2135 										// left-recursive rules
2136 	}
2137 };

2139 //
2140 // Like {@link //enterRule} but for recursive rules.
2141 
2142 Parser.prototype.pushNewRecursionContext = function(localctx, state, ruleIndex) {
2143 	var previous = this._ctx;
2144 	previous.parentCtx = localctx;
2145 	previous.invokingState = state;
2146 	previous.stop = this._input.LT(-1);
2147 
2148 	this._ctx = localctx;
2149 	this._ctx.start = previous.start;
2150 	if (this.buildParseTrees) {
2151 		this._ctx.addChild(previous);
2152 	}
2153 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
2154 		this.triggerEnterRuleEvent(); // simulates rule entry for
2155 										// left-recursive rules
2156 	}
2157 };

2159 Parser.prototype.unrollRecursionContexts = function(parentCtx) {
2160 	this._precedenceStack.pop();
2161 	this._ctx.stop = this._input.LT(-1);
2162 	var retCtx = this._ctx; // save current ctx (return value)
2163 	// unroll so _ctx is as it was before call to recursive method
2164 	if (this._parseListeners !== null) {
2165 		while (this._ctx !== parentCtx) {
2166 			this.triggerExitRuleEvent();
2167 			this._ctx = this._ctx.parentCtx;
2168 		}
2169 	} else {
2170 		this._ctx = parentCtx;
2171 	}
2172 	// hook into tree
2173 	retCtx.parentCtx = parentCtx;
2174 	if (this.buildParseTrees && parentCtx !== null) {
2175 		// add return ctx into invoking rule's tree
2176 		parentCtx.addChild(retCtx);
2177 	}
2178 };

2180 Parser.prototype.getInvokingContext = function(ruleIndex) {
2181 	var ctx = this._ctx;
2182 	while (ctx !== null) {
2183 		if (ctx.ruleIndex === ruleIndex) {
2184 			return ctx;
2185 		}
2186 		ctx = ctx.parentCtx;
2187 	}
2188 	return null;
2189 };

2200 //
2201 // Checks whether or not {@code symbol} can follow the current state in the
2202 // ATN. The behavior of this method is equivalent to the following, but is
2203 // implemented such that the complete context-sensitive follow set does not
2204 // need to be explicitly constructed.
2205 //
2206 // <pre>
2207 // return getExpectedTokens().contains(symbol);
2208 // </pre>
2209 //
2210 // @param symbol the symbol type to check
2211 // @return {@code true} if {@code symbol} can follow the current state in
2212 // the ATN, otherwise {@code false}.
2213 
2214 Parser.prototype.isExpectedToken = function(symbol) {
2215 	var atn = this._interp.atn;
2216 	var ctx = this._ctx;
2217 	var s = atn.states[this.state];
2218 	var following = atn.nextTokens(s);
2219 	if (following.contains(symbol)) {
2220 		return true;
2221 	}
2222 	if (!following.contains(Token.EPSILON)) {
2223 		return false;
2224 	}
2225 	while (ctx !== null && ctx.invokingState >= 0 && following.contains(Token.EPSILON)) {
2226 		var invokingState = atn.states[ctx.invokingState];
2227 		var rt = invokingState.transitions[0];
2228 		following = atn.nextTokens(rt.followState);
2229 		if (following.contains(symbol)) {
2230 			return true;
2231 		}
2232 		ctx = ctx.parentCtx;
2233 	}
2234 	if (following.contains(Token.EPSILON) && symbol === Token.EOF) {
2235 		return true;
2236 	} else {
2237 		return false;
2238 	}
2239 };

2267 // Return List&lt;String&gt; of the rule names in your parser instance
2268 // leading up to a call to the current rule. You could override if
2269 // you want more details such as the file/line info of where
2270 // in the ATN a rule is invoked.
2271 //
2272 // this is very useful for error messages.
2273 //
2274 Parser.prototype.getRuleInvocationStack = function(p) {
2275 	p = p || null;
2276 	if (p === null) {
2277 		p = this._ctx;
2278 	}
2279 	var stack = [];
2280 	while (p !== null) {
2281 		// compute what follows who invoked us
2282 		var ruleIndex = p.ruleIndex;
2283 		if (ruleIndex < 0) {
2284 			stack.push("n/a");
2285 		} else {
2286 			stack.push(this.ruleNames[ruleIndex]);
2287 		}
2288 		p = p.parentCtx;
2289 	}
2290 	return stack;
2291 };

2297 // For debugging and other purposes.//

2300 	for (var i = 0; i < this._interp.decisionToDFA.length; i++) {
2301 		var dfa = this._interp.decisionToDFA[i];
2302 		if (dfa.states.length > 0) {
2303 			if (seenOne) {
2304 				console.log();
2305 			}
2306 			this.printer.println("Decision " + dfa.decision + ":");
2307 			this.printer.print(dfa.toString(this.literalNames, this.symbolicNames));
2308 			seenOne = true;
2309 		}
2310 	}
2311 };

2347 //* A rule invocation record for parsing.
2348 //
2349 //  Contains all of the information about the current rule not stored in the
2350 //  RuleContext. It handles parse tree children list, Any ATN state
2351 //  tracing, and the default values available for rule indications:
2352 //  start, stop, rule index, current alt number, current
2353 //  ATN state.
2354 //
2355 //  Subclasses made for each rule and grammar track the parameters,
2356 //  return values, locals, and labels specific to that rule. These
2357 //  are the objects that are returned from rules.
2358 //
2359 //  Note text is not an actual field of a rule return value; it is computed
2360 //  from start and stop using the input stream's toString() method.  I
2361 //  could add a ctor to this so that we can pass in and store the input
2362 //  stream, but I'm not sure we want to do that.  It would seem to be undefined
2363 //  to get the .text property anyway if the rule matches tokens from multiple
2364 //  input streams.
2365 //
2366 //  I do not use getters for fields of objects that are used simply to
2367 //  group values such as this aggregate.  The getters/setters are there to
2368 //  satisfy the superclass interface.
2369 
2370 var RuleContext = require('./RuleContext').RuleContext;
2371 var Tree = require('./tree/Tree');
2372 var INVALID_INTERVAL = Tree.INVALID_INTERVAL;
2373 var TerminalNode = Tree.TerminalNode;
2374 var TerminalNodeImpl = Tree.TerminalNodeImpl;
2375 var ErrorNodeImpl = Tree.ErrorNodeImpl;
2376 var Interval = require("./IntervalSet").Interval;
2377 
2378 function ParserRuleContext(parent, invokingStateNumber) {
2379 	parent = parent || null;
2380 	invokingStateNumber = invokingStateNumber || null;
2381 	RuleContext.call(this, parent, invokingStateNumber);
2382 	this.ruleIndex = -1;
2383     // * If we are debugging or building a parse tree for a visitor,
2384     // we need to track all of the tokens and rule invocations associated
2385     // with this rule's context. This is empty for parsing w/o tree constr.
2386     // operation because we don't the need to track the details about
2387     // how we parse this rule.
2388     // /
2389     this.children = null;
2390     this.start = null;
2391     this.stop = null;
2392     // The exception that forced this rule to return. If the rule successfully
2393     // completed, this is {@code null}.
2394     this.exception = null;
2395 }

2398 ParserRuleContext.prototype.constructor = ParserRuleContext;

2400 // * COPY a ctx (I'm deliberately not using copy constructor)///
2401 ParserRuleContext.prototype.copyFrom = function(ctx) {
2402     // from RuleContext
2403     this.parentCtx = ctx.parentCtx;
2404     this.invokingState = ctx.invokingState;
2405     this.children = null;
2406     this.start = ctx.start;
2407     this.stop = ctx.stop;
2408     // copy any error nodes to alt label node
2409     if(ctx.children) {
2410         this.children = [];
2411         // reset parent pointer for any error nodes
2412     	ctx.children.map(function(child) {
2413     		if (child instanceof ErrorNodeImpl) {
2414                 this.children.push(child);
2415                 child.parentCtx = this;
2416             }
2417 		}, this);
2418 	}
2419 };

2428 // * Does not set parent link; other add methods do that///
2429 ParserRuleContext.prototype.addChild = function(child) {
2430     if (this.children === null) {
2431         this.children = [];
2432     }
2433     this.children.push(child);
2434     return child;

2438 // we entered a rule. If we have // label, we will need to remove
2439 // generic ruleContext object.

2461 ParserRuleContext.prototype.getChild = function(i, type) {
2462 	type = type || null;
2463 	if (this.children === null || i < 0 || i >= this.children.length) {
2464 		return null;
2465 	}
2466 	if (type === null) {
2467 		return this.children[i];
2468 	} else {
2469 		for(var j=0; j<this.children.length; j++) {
2470 			var child = this.children[j];
2471 			if(child instanceof type) {
2472 				if(i===0) {
2473 					return child;
2474 				} else {
2475 					i -= 1;
2476 				}
2477 			}
2478 		}
2479 		return null;
2480     }
2481 };
2482 
2483 
2484 ParserRuleContext.prototype.getToken = function(ttype, i) {
2485 	if (this.children === null || i < 0 || i >= this.children.length) {
2486 		return null;
2487 	}
2488 	for(var j=0; j<this.children.length; j++) {
2489 		var child = this.children[j];
2490 		if (child instanceof TerminalNode) {
2491 			if (child.symbol.type === ttype) {
2492 				if(i===0) {
2493 					return child;
2494 				} else {
2495 					i -= 1;
2496 				}
2497 			}
2498         }
2499 	}
2500     return null;
2501 };
2502 
2503 ParserRuleContext.prototype.getTokens = function(ttype ) {
2504     if (this.children=== null) {
2505         return [];
2506     } else {
2507 		var tokens = [];
2508 		for(var j=0; j<this.children.length; j++) {
2509 			var child = this.children[j];
2510 			if (child instanceof TerminalNode) {
2511 				if (child.symbol.type === ttype) {
2512 					tokens.push(child);
2513 				}
2514 			}
2515 		}
2516 		return tokens;
2517     }
2518 };

2524 ParserRuleContext.prototype.getTypedRuleContexts = function(ctxType) {
2525     if (this.children=== null) {
2526         return [];
2527     } else {
2528 		var contexts = [];
2529 		for(var j=0; j<this.children.length; j++) {
2530 			var child = this.children[j];
2531 			if (child instanceof ctxType) {
2532 				contexts.push(child);
2533 			}
2534 		}
2535 		return contexts;
2536 	}
2537 };

2540 	if (this.children=== null) {
2541 		return 0;
2542 	} else {
2543 		return this.children.length;
2544 	}

2587 // Represents {@code $} in an array in full context mode, when {@code $}
2588 // doesn't mean wildcard: {@code $ + x = [$,x]}. Here,
2589 // {@code $} = {@link //EMPTY_RETURN_STATE}.
2590 // /

2596 // Stores the computed hash code of this {@link PredictionContext}. The hash
2597 // code is computed in parts to match the following reference algorithm.
2598 //
2599 // <pre>
2600 // private int referenceHashCode() {
2601 // int hash = {@link MurmurHash//initialize MurmurHash.initialize}({@link
2602 // //INITIAL_HASH});
2603 //
2604 // for (int i = 0; i &lt; {@link //size()}; i++) {
2605 // hash = {@link MurmurHash//update MurmurHash.update}(hash, {@link //getParent
2606 // getParent}(i));
2607 // }
2608 //
2609 // for (int i = 0; i &lt; {@link //size()}; i++) {
2610 // hash = {@link MurmurHash//update MurmurHash.update}(hash, {@link
2611 // //getReturnState getReturnState}(i));
2612 // }
2613 //
2614 // hash = {@link MurmurHash//finish MurmurHash.finish}(hash, 2// {@link
2615 // //size()});
2616 // return hash;
2617 // }
2618 // </pre>

2653 // Add a context to the cache and return it. If the context already exists,
2654 // return that one instead and do not add a new context to the cache.
2655 // Protect shared cache from unsafe thread access.
2656 //
2657 PredictionContextCache.prototype.add = function(ctx) {
2658 	if (ctx === PredictionContext.EMPTY) {
2659 		return PredictionContext.EMPTY;
2660 	}
2661 	var existing = this.cache[ctx] || null;
2662 	if (existing !== null) {
2663 		return existing;
2664 	}
2665 	this.cache[ctx] = ctx;
2666 	return ctx;
2667 };

2679 function SingletonPredictionContext(parent, returnState) {
2680 	var hashCode = 0;
2681 	if(parent !== null) {
2682 		var hash = new Hash();
2683 		hash.update(parent, returnState);
2684         hashCode = hash.finish();
2685 	}
2686 	PredictionContext.call(this, hashCode);
2687 	this.parentCtx = parent;
2688 	this.returnState = returnState;
2689 }

2694 SingletonPredictionContext.create = function(parent, returnState) {
2695 	if (returnState === PredictionContext.EMPTY_RETURN_STATE && parent === null) {
2696 		// someone can pass in the bits of an array ctx that mean $
2697 		return PredictionContext.EMPTY;
2698 	} else {
2699 		return new SingletonPredictionContext(parent, returnState);
2700 	}
2701 };

2717 SingletonPredictionContext.prototype.equals = function(other) {
2718 	if (this === other) {
2719 		return true;
2720 	} else if (!(other instanceof SingletonPredictionContext)) {
2721 		return false;
2722 	} else if (this.hashCode() !== other.hashCode()) {
2723 		return false; // can't be same if hash is different
2724 	} else {
2725 		if(this.returnState !== other.returnState)
2726             return false;
2727         else if(this.parentCtx==null)
2728             return other.parentCtx==null
2729 		else
2730             return this.parentCtx.equals(other.parentCtx);
2731 	}
2732 };
