5900 // When we hit an accept state in either the DFA or the ATN, we
5901 //  have to notify the character stream to start buffering characters
5902 //  via {@link IntStream//mark} and record the current state. The current sim state
5903 //  includes the current index into the input, the current line,
5904 //  and current character position in that line. Note that the Lexer is
5905 //  tracking the starting line and characterization of the token. These
5906 //  variables track the "state" of the simulator when it hits an accept state.
5907 //
5908 //  <p>We track these variables separately for the DFA and ATN simulation
5909 //  because the DFA simulation often has to fail over to the ATN
5910 //  simulation. If the ATN simulation fails, we need the DFA to fall
5911 //  back to its previously accepted state, if any. If the ATN succeeds,
5912 //  then the ATN does the accept and the DFA simulator that invoked it
5913 //  can simply return the predicted token type.</p>
5914 ///
5915 
5916 var Token = require('./../Token').Token;
5917 var Lexer = require('./../Lexer').Lexer;
5918 var ATN = require('./ATN').ATN;
5919 var ATNSimulator = require('./ATNSimulator').ATNSimulator;
5920 var DFAState = require('./../dfa/DFAState').DFAState;
5921 var ATNConfigSet = require('./ATNConfigSet').ATNConfigSet;
5922 var OrderedATNConfigSet = require('./ATNConfigSet').OrderedATNConfigSet;
5923 var PredictionContext = require('./../PredictionContext').PredictionContext;
5924 var SingletonPredictionContext = require('./../PredictionContext').SingletonPredictionContext;
5925 var RuleStopState = require('./ATNState').RuleStopState;
5926 var LexerATNConfig = require('./ATNConfig').LexerATNConfig;
5927 var Transition = require('./Transition').Transition;
5928 var LexerActionExecutor = require('./LexerActionExecutor').LexerActionExecutor;
5929 var LexerNoViableAltException = require('./../error/Errors').LexerNoViableAltException;
5930 
5931 function resetSimState(sim) {
5932 	sim.index = -1;
5933 	sim.line = 0;
5934 	sim.column = -1;
5935 	sim.dfaState = null;
5936 }
5937 
5938 function SimState() {
5939 	resetSimState(this);
5940 	return this;
5941 }
5942 
5943 SimState.prototype.reset = function() {
5944 	resetSimState(this);
5945 };
5946 
5947 function LexerATNSimulator(recog, atn, decisionToDFA, sharedContextCache) {
5948 	ATNSimulator.call(this, atn, sharedContextCache);
5949 	this.decisionToDFA = decisionToDFA;
5950 	this.recog = recog;
5951 	// The current token's starting index into the character stream.
5952 	// Shared across DFA to ATN simulation in case the ATN fails and the
5953 	// DFA did not have a previous accept state. In this case, we use the
5954 	// ATN-generated exception object.
5955 	this.startIndex = -1;
5956 	// line number 1..n within the input///
5957 	this.line = 1;
5958 	// The index of the character relative to the beginning of the line
5959 	// 0..n-1///
5960 	this.column = 0;
5961 	this.mode = Lexer.DEFAULT_MODE;
5962 	// Used during DFA/ATN exec to record the most recent accept configuration
5963 	// info
5964 	this.prevAccept = new SimState();
5965 	// done
5966 	return this;
5967 }
5968 
5969 LexerATNSimulator.prototype = Object.create(ATNSimulator.prototype);
5970 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.constructor = LexerATNSimulator;
5971 
5972 LexerATNSimulator.debug = false;
5973 LexerATNSimulator.dfa_debug = false;
5974 
5975 LexerATNSimulator.MIN_DFA_EDGE = 0;
5976 LexerATNSimulator.MAX_DFA_EDGE = 127; // forces unicode to stay in ATN
5977 
5978 LexerATNSimulator.match_calls = 0;
5979 
5980 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.copyState = function(simulator) {
5981 	this.column = simulator.column;
5982 	this.line = simulator.line;
5983 	this.mode = simulator.mode;
5984 	this.startIndex = simulator.startIndex;
5985 };
5986 
5987 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.match = function(input, mode) {
5988 	this.match_calls += 1;
5989 	this.mode = mode;
5990 	var mark = input.mark();
5991 	try {
5992 		this.startIndex = input.index;
5993 		this.prevAccept.reset();
5994 		var dfa = this.decisionToDFA[mode];
5995 		if (dfa.s0 === null) {
5996 			return this.matchATN(input);
5997 		} else {
5998 			return this.execATN(input, dfa.s0);
5999 		}
6000 	} finally {
6001 		input.release(mark);
6002 	}
6003 };
6004 
6005 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.reset = function() {
6006 	this.prevAccept.reset();
6007 	this.startIndex = -1;
6008 	this.line = 1;
6009 	this.column = 0;
6010 	this.mode = Lexer.DEFAULT_MODE;
6011 };
6012 
6013 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.matchATN = function(input) {
6014 	var startState = this.atn.modeToStartState[this.mode];
6015 
6016 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6017 		console.log("matchATN mode " + this.mode + " start: " + startState);
6018 	}
6019 	var old_mode = this.mode;
6020 	var s0_closure = this.computeStartState(input, startState);
6021 	var suppressEdge = s0_closure.hasSemanticContext;
6022 	s0_closure.hasSemanticContext = false;
6023 
6024 	var next = this.addDFAState(s0_closure);
6025 	if (!suppressEdge) {
6026 		this.decisionToDFA[this.mode].s0 = next;
6027 	}
6028 
6029 	var predict = this.execATN(input, next);
6030 
6031 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6032 		console.log("DFA after matchATN: " + this.decisionToDFA[old_mode].toLexerString());
6033 	}
6034 	return predict;
6035 };
6036 
6037 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.execATN = function(input, ds0) {
6038 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6039 		console.log("start state closure=" + ds0.configs);
6040 	}
6041 	if (ds0.isAcceptState) {
6042 		// allow zero-length tokens
6043 		this.captureSimState(this.prevAccept, input, ds0);
6044 	}
6045 	var t = input.LA(1);
6046 	var s = ds0; // s is current/from DFA state
6047 
6048 	while (true) { // while more work
6049 		if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6050 			console.log("execATN loop starting closure: " + s.configs);
6051 		}
6052 
6053 		// As we move src->trg, src->trg, we keep track of the previous trg to
6054 		// avoid looking up the DFA state again, which is expensive.
6055 		// If the previous target was already part of the DFA, we might
6056 		// be able to avoid doing a reach operation upon t. If s!=null,
6057 		// it means that semantic predicates didn't prevent us from
6058 		// creating a DFA state. Once we know s!=null, we check to see if
6059 		// the DFA state has an edge already for t. If so, we can just reuse
6060 		// it's configuration set; there's no point in re-computing it.
6061 		// This is kind of like doing DFA simulation within the ATN
6062 		// simulation because DFA simulation is really just a way to avoid
6063 		// computing reach/closure sets. Technically, once we know that
6064 		// we have a previously added DFA state, we could jump over to
6065 		// the DFA simulator. But, that would mean popping back and forth
6066 		// a lot and making things more complicated algorithmically.
6067 		// This optimization makes a lot of sense for loops within DFA.
6068 		// A character will take us back to an existing DFA state
6069 		// that already has lots of edges out of it. e.g., .* in comments.
6070 		// print("Target for:" + str(s) + " and:" + str(t))
6071 		var target = this.getExistingTargetState(s, t);
6072 		// print("Existing:" + str(target))
6073 		if (target === null) {
6074 			target = this.computeTargetState(input, s, t);
6075 			// print("Computed:" + str(target))
6076 		}
6077 		if (target === ATNSimulator.ERROR) {
6078 			break;
6079 		}
6080 		// If this is a consumable input element, make sure to consume before
6081 		// capturing the accept state so the input index, line, and char
6082 		// position accurately reflect the state of the interpreter at the
6083 		// end of the token.
6084 		if (t !== Token.EOF) {
6085 			this.consume(input);
6086 		}
6087 		if (target.isAcceptState) {
6088 			this.captureSimState(this.prevAccept, input, target);
6089 			if (t === Token.EOF) {
6090 				break;
6091 			}
6092 		}
6093 		t = input.LA(1);
6094 		s = target; // flip; current DFA target becomes new src/from state
6095 	}
6096 	return this.failOrAccept(this.prevAccept, input, s.configs, t);
6097 };
6098 
6099 // Get an existing target state for an edge in the DFA. If the target state
6100 // for the edge has not yet been computed or is otherwise not available,
6101 // this method returns {@code null}.
6102 //
6103 // @param s The current DFA state
6104 // @param t The next input symbol
6105 // @return The existing target DFA state for the given input symbol
6106 // {@code t}, or {@code null} if the target state for this edge is not
6107 // already cached
6108 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getExistingTargetState = function(s, t) {
6109 	if (s.edges === null || t < LexerATNSimulator.MIN_DFA_EDGE || t > LexerATNSimulator.MAX_DFA_EDGE) {
6110 		return null;
6111 	}
6112 
6113 	var target = s.edges[t - LexerATNSimulator.MIN_DFA_EDGE];
6114 	if(target===undefined) {
6115 		target = null;
6116 	}
6117 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug && target !== null) {
6118 		console.log("reuse state " + s.stateNumber + " edge to " + target.stateNumber);
6119 	}
6120 	return target;
6121 };
6122 
6123 // Compute a target state for an edge in the DFA, and attempt to add the
6124 // computed state and corresponding edge to the DFA.
6125 //
6126 // @param input The input stream
6127 // @param s The current DFA state
6128 // @param t The next input symbol
6129 //
6130 // @return The computed target DFA state for the given input symbol
6131 // {@code t}. If {@code t} does not lead to a valid DFA state, this method
6132 // returns {@link //ERROR}.
6133 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.computeTargetState = function(input, s, t) {
6134 	var reach = new OrderedATNConfigSet();
6135 	// if we don't find an existing DFA state
6136 	// Fill reach starting from closure, following t transitions
6137 	this.getReachableConfigSet(input, s.configs, reach, t);
6138 
6139 	if (reach.items.length === 0) { // we got nowhere on t from s
6140 		if (!reach.hasSemanticContext) {
6141 			// we got nowhere on t, don't throw out this knowledge; it'd
6142 			// cause a failover from DFA later.
6143 			this.addDFAEdge(s, t, ATNSimulator.ERROR);
6144 		}
6145 		// stop when we can't match any more char
6146 		return ATNSimulator.ERROR;
6147 	}
6148 	// Add an edge from s to target DFA found/created for reach
6149 	return this.addDFAEdge(s, t, null, reach);
6150 };
6151 
6152 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.failOrAccept = function(prevAccept, input, reach, t) {
6153 	if (this.prevAccept.dfaState !== null) {
6154 		var lexerActionExecutor = prevAccept.dfaState.lexerActionExecutor;
6155 		this.accept(input, lexerActionExecutor, this.startIndex,
6156 				prevAccept.index, prevAccept.line, prevAccept.column);
6157 		return prevAccept.dfaState.prediction;
6158 	} else {
6159 		// if no accept and EOF is first char, return EOF
6160 		if (t === Token.EOF && input.index === this.startIndex) {
6161 			return Token.EOF;
6162 		}
6163 		throw new LexerNoViableAltException(this.recog, input, this.startIndex, reach);
6164 	}
6165 };
6166 
6167 // Given a starting configuration set, figure out all ATN configurations
6168 // we can reach upon input {@code t}. Parameter {@code reach} is a return
6169 // parameter.
6170 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getReachableConfigSet = function(input, closure,
6171 		reach, t) {
6172 	// this is used to skip processing for configs which have a lower priority
6173 	// than a config that already reached an accept state for the same rule
6174 	var skipAlt = ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
6175 	for (var i = 0; i < closure.items.length; i++) {
6176 		var cfg = closure.items[i];
6177 		var currentAltReachedAcceptState = (cfg.alt === skipAlt);
6178 		if (currentAltReachedAcceptState && cfg.passedThroughNonGreedyDecision) {
6179 			continue;
6180 		}
6181 		if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6182 			console.log("testing %s at %s\n", this.getTokenName(t), cfg
6183 					.toString(this.recog, true));
6184 		}
6185 		for (var j = 0; j < cfg.state.transitions.length; j++) {
6186 			var trans = cfg.state.transitions[j]; // for each transition
6187 			var target = this.getReachableTarget(trans, t);
6188 			if (target !== null) {
6189 				var lexerActionExecutor = cfg.lexerActionExecutor;
6190 				if (lexerActionExecutor !== null) {
6191 					lexerActionExecutor = lexerActionExecutor.fixOffsetBeforeMatch(input.index - this.startIndex);
6192 				}
6193 				var treatEofAsEpsilon = (t === Token.EOF);
6194 				var config = new LexerATNConfig({state:target, lexerActionExecutor:lexerActionExecutor}, cfg);
6195 				if (this.closure(input, config, reach,
6196 						currentAltReachedAcceptState, true, treatEofAsEpsilon)) {
6197 					// any remaining configs for this alt have a lower priority
6198 					// than the one that just reached an accept state.
6199 					skipAlt = cfg.alt;
6200 				}
6201 			}
6202 		}
6203 	}
6204 };
6205 
6206 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.accept = function(input, lexerActionExecutor,
6207 		startIndex, index, line, charPos) {
6208 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6209 		console.log("ACTION %s\n", lexerActionExecutor);
6210 	}
6211 	// seek to after last char in token
6212 	input.seek(index);
6213 	this.line = line;
6214 	this.column = charPos;
6215 	if (lexerActionExecutor !== null && this.recog !== null) {
6216 		lexerActionExecutor.execute(this.recog, input, startIndex);
6217 	}
6218 };
6219 
6220 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getReachableTarget = function(trans, t) {
6221 	if (trans.matches(t, 0, Lexer.MAX_CHAR_VALUE)) {
6222 		return trans.target;
6223 	} else {
6224 		return null;
6225 	}
6226 };
6227 
6228 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.computeStartState = function(input, p) {
6229 	var initialContext = PredictionContext.EMPTY;
6230 	var configs = new OrderedATNConfigSet();
6231 	for (var i = 0; i < p.transitions.length; i++) {
6232 		var target = p.transitions[i].target;
6233         var cfg = new LexerATNConfig({state:target, alt:i+1, context:initialContext}, null);
6234 		this.closure(input, cfg, configs, false, false, false);
6235 	}
6236 	return configs;
6237 };
6238 
6239 // Since the alternatives within any lexer decision are ordered by
6240 // preference, this method stops pursuing the closure as soon as an accept
6241 // state is reached. After the first accept state is reached by depth-first
6242 // search from {@code config}, all other (potentially reachable) states for
6243 // this rule would have a lower priority.
6244 //
6245 // @return {@code true} if an accept state is reached, otherwise
6246 // {@code false}.
6247 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.closure = function(input, config, configs,
6248 		currentAltReachedAcceptState, speculative, treatEofAsEpsilon) {
6249 	var cfg = null;
6250 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6251 		console.log("closure(" + config.toString(this.recog, true) + ")");
6252 	}
6253 	if (config.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
6254 		if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6255 			if (this.recog !== null) {
6256 				console.log("closure at %s rule stop %s\n", this.recog.ruleNames[config.state.ruleIndex], config);
6257 			} else {
6258 				console.log("closure at rule stop %s\n", config);
6259 			}
6260 		}
6261 		if (config.context === null || config.context.hasEmptyPath()) {
6262 			if (config.context === null || config.context.isEmpty()) {
6263 				configs.add(config);
6264 				return true;
6265 			} else {
6266 				configs.add(new LexerATNConfig({ state:config.state, context:PredictionContext.EMPTY}, config));
6267 				currentAltReachedAcceptState = true;
6268 			}
6269 		}
6270 		if (config.context !== null && !config.context.isEmpty()) {
6271 			for (var i = 0; i < config.context.length; i++) {
6272 				if (config.context.getReturnState(i) !== PredictionContext.EMPTY_RETURN_STATE) {
6273 					var newContext = config.context.getParent(i); // "pop" return state
6274 					var returnState = this.atn.states[config.context.getReturnState(i)];
6275 					cfg = new LexerATNConfig({ state:returnState, context:newContext }, config);
6276 					currentAltReachedAcceptState = this.closure(input, cfg,
6277 							configs, currentAltReachedAcceptState, speculative,
6278 							treatEofAsEpsilon);
6279 				}
6280 			}
6281 		}
6282 		return currentAltReachedAcceptState;
6283 	}
6284 	// optimization
6285 	if (!config.state.epsilonOnlyTransitions) {
6286 		if (!currentAltReachedAcceptState || !config.passedThroughNonGreedyDecision) {
6287 			configs.add(config);
6288 		}
6289 	}
6290 	for (var j = 0; j < config.state.transitions.length; j++) {
6291 		var trans = config.state.transitions[j];
6292 		cfg = this.getEpsilonTarget(input, config, trans, configs, speculative, treatEofAsEpsilon);
6293 		if (cfg !== null) {
6294 			currentAltReachedAcceptState = this.closure(input, cfg, configs,
6295 					currentAltReachedAcceptState, speculative, treatEofAsEpsilon);
6296 		}
6297 	}
6298 	return currentAltReachedAcceptState;
6299 };
6300 
6301 // side-effect: can alter configs.hasSemanticContext
6302 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getEpsilonTarget = function(input, config, trans,
6303 		configs, speculative, treatEofAsEpsilon) {
6304 	var cfg = null;
6305 	if (trans.serializationType === Transition.RULE) {
6306 		var newContext = SingletonPredictionContext.create(config.context, trans.followState.stateNumber);
6307 		cfg = new LexerATNConfig( { state:trans.target, context:newContext}, config);
6308 	} else if (trans.serializationType === Transition.PRECEDENCE) {
6309 		throw "Precedence predicates are not supported in lexers.";
6310 	} else if (trans.serializationType === Transition.PREDICATE) {
6311 		// Track traversing semantic predicates. If we traverse,
6312 		// we cannot add a DFA state for this "reach" computation
6313 		// because the DFA would not test the predicate again in the
6314 		// future. Rather than creating collections of semantic predicates
6315 		// like v3 and testing them on prediction, v4 will test them on the
6316 		// fly all the time using the ATN not the DFA. This is slower but
6317 		// semantically it's not used that often. One of the key elements to
6318 		// this predicate mechanism is not adding DFA states that see
6319 		// predicates immediately afterwards in the ATN. For example,
6320 
6321 		// a : ID {p1}? | ID {p2}? ;
6322 
6323 		// should create the start state for rule 'a' (to save start state
6324 		// competition), but should not create target of ID state. The
6325 		// collection of ATN states the following ID references includes
6326 		// states reached by traversing predicates. Since this is when we
6327 		// test them, we cannot cash the DFA state target of ID.
6328 
6329 		if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6330 			console.log("EVAL rule " + trans.ruleIndex + ":" + trans.predIndex);
6331 		}
6332 		configs.hasSemanticContext = true;
6333 		if (this.evaluatePredicate(input, trans.ruleIndex, trans.predIndex, speculative)) {
6334 			cfg = new LexerATNConfig({ state:trans.target}, config);
6335 		}
6336 	} else if (trans.serializationType === Transition.ACTION) {
6337 		if (config.context === null || config.context.hasEmptyPath()) {
6338 			// execute actions anywhere in the start rule for a token.
6339 			//
6340 			// TODO: if the entry rule is invoked recursively, some
6341 			// actions may be executed during the recursive call. The
6342 			// problem can appear when hasEmptyPath() is true but
6343 			// isEmpty() is false. In this case, the config needs to be
6344 			// split into two contexts - one with just the empty path
6345 			// and another with everything but the empty path.
6346 			// Unfortunately, the current algorithm does not allow
6347 			// getEpsilonTarget to return two configurations, so
6348 			// additional modifications are needed before we can support
6349 			// the split operation.
6350 			var lexerActionExecutor = LexerActionExecutor.append(config.lexerActionExecutor,
6351 					this.atn.lexerActions[trans.actionIndex]);
6352 			cfg = new LexerATNConfig({ state:trans.target, lexerActionExecutor:lexerActionExecutor }, config);
6353 		} else {
6354 			// ignore actions in referenced rules
6355 			cfg = new LexerATNConfig( { state:trans.target}, config);
6356 		}
6357 	} else if (trans.serializationType === Transition.EPSILON) {
6358 		cfg = new LexerATNConfig({ state:trans.target}, config);
6359 	} else if (trans.serializationType === Transition.ATOM ||
6360 				trans.serializationType === Transition.RANGE ||
6361 				trans.serializationType === Transition.SET) {
6362 		if (treatEofAsEpsilon) {
6363 			if (trans.matches(Token.EOF, 0, Lexer.MAX_CHAR_VALUE)) {
6364 				cfg = new LexerATNConfig( { state:trans.target }, config);
6365 			}
6366 		}
6367 	}
6368 	return cfg;
6369 };
6370 
6371 // Evaluate a predicate specified in the lexer.
6372 //
6373 // <p>If {@code speculative} is {@code true}, this method was called before
6374 // {@link //consume} for the matched character. This method should call
6375 // {@link //consume} before evaluating the predicate to ensure position
6376 // sensitive values, including {@link Lexer//getText}, {@link Lexer//getLine},
6377 // and {@link Lexer//getcolumn}, properly reflect the current
6378 // lexer state. This method should restore {@code input} and the simulator
6379 // to the original state before returning (i.e. undo the actions made by the
6380 // call to {@link //consume}.</p>
6381 //
6382 // @param input The input stream.
6383 // @param ruleIndex The rule containing the predicate.
6384 // @param predIndex The index of the predicate within the rule.
6385 // @param speculative {@code true} if the current index in {@code input} is
6386 // one character before the predicate's location.
6387 //
6388 // @return {@code true} if the specified predicate evaluates to
6389 // {@code true}.
6390 // /
6391 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.evaluatePredicate = function(input, ruleIndex,
6392 		predIndex, speculative) {
6393 	// assume true if no recognizer was provided
6394 	if (this.recog === null) {
6395 		return true;
6396 	}
6397 	if (!speculative) {
6398 		return this.recog.sempred(null, ruleIndex, predIndex);
6399 	}
6400 	var savedcolumn = this.column;
6401 	var savedLine = this.line;
6402 	var index = input.index;
6403 	var marker = input.mark();
6404 	try {
6405 		this.consume(input);
6406 		return this.recog.sempred(null, ruleIndex, predIndex);
6407 	} finally {
6408 		this.column = savedcolumn;
6409 		this.line = savedLine;
6410 		input.seek(index);
6411 		input.release(marker);
6412 	}
6413 };
6414 
6415 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.captureSimState = function(settings, input, dfaState) {
6416 	settings.index = input.index;
6417 	settings.line = this.line;
6418 	settings.column = this.column;
6419 	settings.dfaState = dfaState;
6420 };
6421 
6422 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.addDFAEdge = function(from_, tk, to, cfgs) {
6423 	if (to === undefined) {
6424 		to = null;
6425 	}
6426 	if (cfgs === undefined) {
6427 		cfgs = null;
6428 	}
6429 	if (to === null && cfgs !== null) {
6430 		// leading to this call, ATNConfigSet.hasSemanticContext is used as a
6431 		// marker indicating dynamic predicate evaluation makes this edge
6432 		// dependent on the specific input sequence, so the static edge in the
6433 		// DFA should be omitted. The target DFAState is still created since
6434 		// execATN has the ability to resynchronize with the DFA state cache
6435 		// following the predicate evaluation step.
6436 		//
6437 		// TJP notes: next time through the DFA, we see a pred again and eval.
6438 		// If that gets us to a previously created (but dangling) DFA
6439 		// state, we can continue in pure DFA mode from there.
6440 		// /
6441 		var suppressEdge = cfgs.hasSemanticContext;
6442 		cfgs.hasSemanticContext = false;
6443 
6444 		to = this.addDFAState(cfgs);
6445 
6446 		if (suppressEdge) {
6447 			return to;
6448 		}
6449 	}
6450 	// add the edge
6451 	if (tk < LexerATNSimulator.MIN_DFA_EDGE || tk > LexerATNSimulator.MAX_DFA_EDGE) {
6452 		// Only track edges within the DFA bounds
6453 		return to;
6454 	}
6455 	if (LexerATNSimulator.debug) {
6456 		console.log("EDGE " + from_ + " -> " + to + " upon " + tk);
6457 	}
6458 	if (from_.edges === null) {
6459 		// make room for tokens 1..n and -1 masquerading as index 0
6460 		from_.edges = [];
6461 	}
6462 	from_.edges[tk - LexerATNSimulator.MIN_DFA_EDGE] = to; // connect
6463 
6464 	return to;
6465 };
6466 
6467 // Add a new DFA state if there isn't one with this set of
6468 // configurations already. This method also detects the first
6469 // configuration containing an ATN rule stop state. Later, when
6470 // traversing the DFA, we will know which rule to accept.
6471 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.addDFAState = function(configs) {
6472 	var proposed = new DFAState(null, configs);
6473 	var firstConfigWithRuleStopState = null;
6474 	for (var i = 0; i < configs.items.length; i++) {
6475 		var cfg = configs.items[i];
6476 		if (cfg.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
6477 			firstConfigWithRuleStopState = cfg;
6478 			break;
6479 		}
6480 	}
6481 	if (firstConfigWithRuleStopState !== null) {
6482 		proposed.isAcceptState = true;
6483 		proposed.lexerActionExecutor = firstConfigWithRuleStopState.lexerActionExecutor;
6484 		proposed.prediction = this.atn.ruleToTokenType[firstConfigWithRuleStopState.state.ruleIndex];
6485 	}
6486 	var dfa = this.decisionToDFA[this.mode];
6487 	var existing = dfa.states.get(proposed);
6488 	if (existing!==null) {
6489 		return existing;
6490 	}
6491 	var newState = proposed;
6492 	newState.stateNumber = dfa.states.length;
6493 	configs.setReadonly(true);
6494 	newState.configs = configs;
6495 	dfa.states.add(newState);
6496 	return newState;
6497 };
6498 
6499 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getDFA = function(mode) {
6500 	return this.decisionToDFA[mode];
6501 };

6503 // Get the text matched so far for the current token.
6504 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getText = function(input) {
6505 	// index is first lookahead char, don't include.
6506 	return input.getText(this.startIndex, input.index - 1);
6507 };

6509 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.consume = function(input) {
6510 	var curChar = input.LA(1);
6511 	if (curChar === "\n".charCodeAt(0)) {
6512 		this.line += 1;
6513 		this.column = 0;
6514 	} else {
6515 		this.column += 1;
6516 	}
6517 	input.consume();
6518 };

6520 LexerATNSimulator.prototype.getTokenName = function(tt) {
6521 	if (tt === -1) {
6522 		return "EOF";
6523 	} else {
6524 		return "'" + String.fromCharCode(tt) + "'";
6525 	}
6526 };

6905 // Represents an executor for a sequence of lexer actions which traversed during
6906 // the matching operation of a lexer rule (token).
6907 //
6908 // <p>The executor tracks position information for position-dependent lexer actions
6909 // efficiently, ensuring that actions appearing only at the end of the rule do
6910 // not cause bloating of the {@link DFA} created for the lexer.</p>
6911 
6912 var hashStuff = require("../Utils").hashStuff;
6913 var LexerIndexedCustomAction = require('./LexerAction').LexerIndexedCustomAction;
6914 
6915 function LexerActionExecutor(lexerActions) {
6916 	this.lexerActions = lexerActions === null ? [] : lexerActions;
6917 	// Caches the result of {@link //hashCode} since the hash code is an element
6918 	// of the performance-critical {@link LexerATNConfig//hashCode} operation.
6919 	this.cachedHashCode = hashStuff(lexerActions); // "".join([str(la) for la in
6920 	// lexerActions]))
6921 	return this;
6922 }
6923 
6924 // Creates a {@link LexerActionExecutor} which executes the actions for
6925 // the input {@code lexerActionExecutor} followed by a specified
6926 // {@code lexerAction}.
6927 //
6928 // @param lexerActionExecutor The executor for actions already traversed by
6929 // the lexer while matching a token within a particular
6930 // {@link LexerATNConfig}. If this is {@code null}, the method behaves as
6931 // though it were an empty executor.
6932 // @param lexerAction The lexer action to execute after the actions
6933 // specified in {@code lexerActionExecutor}.
6934 //
6935 // @return A {@link LexerActionExecutor} for executing the combine actions
6936 // of {@code lexerActionExecutor} and {@code lexerAction}.
6937 LexerActionExecutor.append = function(lexerActionExecutor, lexerAction) {
6938 	if (lexerActionExecutor === null) {
6939 		return new LexerActionExecutor([ lexerAction ]);
6940 	}
6941 	var lexerActions = lexerActionExecutor.lexerActions.concat([ lexerAction ]);
6942 	return new LexerActionExecutor(lexerActions);
6943 };
6944 
6945 // Creates a {@link LexerActionExecutor} which encodes the current offset
6946 // for position-dependent lexer actions.
6947 //
6948 // <p>Normally, when the executor encounters lexer actions where
6949 // {@link LexerAction//isPositionDependent} returns {@code true}, it calls
6950 // {@link IntStream//seek} on the input {@link CharStream} to set the input
6951 // position to the <em>end</em> of the current token. This behavior provides
6952 // for efficient DFA representation of lexer actions which appear at the end
6953 // of a lexer rule, even when the lexer rule matches a variable number of
6954 // characters.</p>
6955 //
6956 // <p>Prior to traversing a match transition in the ATN, the current offset
6957 // from the token start index is assigned to all position-dependent lexer
6958 // actions which have not already been assigned a fixed offset. By storing
6959 // the offsets relative to the token start index, the DFA representation of
6960 // lexer actions which appear in the middle of tokens remains efficient due
6961 // to sharing among tokens of the same length, regardless of their absolute
6962 // position in the input stream.</p>
6963 //
6964 // <p>If the current executor already has offsets assigned to all
6965 // position-dependent lexer actions, the method returns {@code this}.</p>
6966 //
6967 // @param offset The current offset to assign to all position-dependent
6968 // lexer actions which do not already have offsets assigned.
6969 //
6970 // @return A {@link LexerActionExecutor} which stores input stream offsets
6971 // for all position-dependent lexer actions.
6972 // /
6973 LexerActionExecutor.prototype.fixOffsetBeforeMatch = function(offset) {
6974 	var updatedLexerActions = null;
6975 	for (var i = 0; i < this.lexerActions.length; i++) {
6976 		if (this.lexerActions[i].isPositionDependent &&
6977 				!(this.lexerActions[i] instanceof LexerIndexedCustomAction)) {
6978 			if (updatedLexerActions === null) {
6979 				updatedLexerActions = this.lexerActions.concat([]);
6980 			}
6981 			updatedLexerActions[i] = new LexerIndexedCustomAction(offset,
6982 					this.lexerActions[i]);
6983 		}
6984 	}
6985 	if (updatedLexerActions === null) {
6986 		return this;
6987 	} else {
6988 		return new LexerActionExecutor(updatedLexerActions);
6989 	}
6990 };
6991 
6992 // Execute the actions encapsulated by this executor within the context of a
6993 // particular {@link Lexer}.
6994 //
6995 // <p>This method calls {@link IntStream//seek} to set the position of the
6996 // {@code input} {@link CharStream} prior to calling
6997 // {@link LexerAction//execute} on a position-dependent action. Before the
6998 // method returns, the input position will be restored to the same position
6999 // it was in when the method was invoked.</p>
7000 //
7001 // @param lexer The lexer instance.
7002 // @param input The input stream which is the source for the current token.
7003 // When this method is called, the current {@link IntStream//index} for
7004 // {@code input} should be the start of the following token, i.e. 1
7005 // character past the end of the current token.
7006 // @param startIndex The token start index. This value may be passed to
7007 // {@link IntStream//seek} to set the {@code input} position to the beginning
7008 // of the token.
7009 // /
7010 LexerActionExecutor.prototype.execute = function(lexer, input, startIndex) {
7011 	var requiresSeek = false;
7012 	var stopIndex = input.index;
7013 	try {
7014 		for (var i = 0; i < this.lexerActions.length; i++) {
7015 			var lexerAction = this.lexerActions[i];
7016 			if (lexerAction instanceof LexerIndexedCustomAction) {
7017 				var offset = lexerAction.offset;
7018 				input.seek(startIndex + offset);
7019 				lexerAction = lexerAction.action;
7020 				requiresSeek = (startIndex + offset) !== stopIndex;
7021 			} else if (lexerAction.isPositionDependent) {
7022 				input.seek(stopIndex);
7023 				requiresSeek = false;
7024 			}
7025 			lexerAction.execute(lexer);
7026 		}
7027 	} finally {
7028 		if (requiresSeek) {
7029 			input.seek(stopIndex);
7030 		}
7031 	}
7032 };
7033 
7034 LexerActionExecutor.prototype.hashCode = function() {
7035 	return this.cachedHashCode;
7036 };
7037 
7038 LexerActionExecutor.prototype.updateHashCode = function(hash) {
7039     hash.update(this.cachedHashCode);
7040 };
7041 
7042 
7043 LexerActionExecutor.prototype.equals = function(other) {
7044 	if (this === other) {
7045 		return true;
7046 	} else if (!(other instanceof LexerActionExecutor)) {
7047 		return false;
7048 	} else if (this.cachedHashCode != other.cachedHashCode) {
7049 		return false;
7050 	} else if (this.lexerActions.length != other.lexerActions.length) {
7051 		return false;
7052 	} else {
7053 		var numActions = this.lexerActions.length
7054 		for (var idx = 0; idx < numActions; ++idx) {
7055 			if (!this.lexerActions[idx].equals(other.lexerActions[idx])) {
7056 				return false;
7057 			}
7058 		}
7059 		return true;
7060 	}
7061 };
7062 
7063 exports.LexerActionExecutor = LexerActionExecutor;

7065 },{"../Utils":16,"./LexerAction":26}],28:[function(require,module,exports){
7066 //
7067 /* Copyright (c) 2012-2017 The ANTLR Project. All rights reserved. 
7068  * Use of this file is governed by the BSD 3-clause license that 
7069  * can be found in the LICENSE.txt file in the project root. 
7070  */
7071 //
7072 
7073 //
7074 // The embodiment of the adaptive LL(*), ALL(*), parsing strategy.
7075 //
7076 // <p>
7077 // The basic complexity of the adaptive strategy makes it harder to understand.
7078 // We begin with ATN simulation to build paths in a DFA. Subsequent prediction
7079 // requests go through the DFA first. If they reach a state without an edge for
7080 // the current symbol, the algorithm fails over to the ATN simulation to
7081 // complete the DFA path for the current input (until it finds a conflict state
7082 // or uniquely predicting state).</p>
7083 //
7084 // <p>
7085 // All of that is done without using the outer context because we want to create
7086 // a DFA that is not dependent upon the rule invocation stack when we do a
7087 // prediction. One DFA works in all contexts. We avoid using context not
7088 // necessarily because it's slower, although it can be, but because of the DFA
7089 // caching problem. The closure routine only considers the rule invocation stack
7090 // created during prediction beginning in the decision rule. For example, if
7091 // prediction occurs without invoking another rule's ATN, there are no context
7092 // stacks in the configurations. When lack of context leads to a conflict, we
7093 // don't know if it's an ambiguity or a weakness in the strong LL(*) parsing
7094 // strategy (versus full LL(*)).</p>
7095 //
7096 // <p>
7097 // When SLL yields a configuration set with conflict, we rewind the input and
7098 // retry the ATN simulation, this time using full outer context without adding
7099 // to the DFA. Configuration context stacks will be the full invocation stacks
7100 // from the start rule. If we get a conflict using full context, then we can
7101 // definitively say we have a true ambiguity for that input sequence. If we
7102 // don't get a conflict, it implies that the decision is sensitive to the outer
7103 // context. (It is not context-sensitive in the sense of context-sensitive
7104 // grammars.)</p>
7105 //
7106 // <p>
7107 // The next time we reach this DFA state with an SLL conflict, through DFA
7108 // simulation, we will again retry the ATN simulation using full context mode.
7109 // This is slow because we can't save the results and have to "interpret" the
7110 // ATN each time we get that input.</p>
7111 //
7112 // <p>
7113 // <strong>CACHING FULL CONTEXT PREDICTIONS</strong></p>
7114 //
7115 // <p>
7116 // We could cache results from full context to predicted alternative easily and
7117 // that saves a lot of time but doesn't work in presence of predicates. The set
7118 // of visible predicates from the ATN start state changes depending on the
7119 // context, because closure can fall off the end of a rule. I tried to cache
7120 // tuples (stack context, semantic context, predicted alt) but it was slower
7121 // than interpreting and much more complicated. Also required a huge amount of
7122 // memory. The goal is not to create the world's fastest parser anyway. I'd like
7123 // to keep this algorithm simple. By launching multiple threads, we can improve
7124 // the speed of parsing across a large number of files.</p>
7125 //
7126 // <p>
7127 // There is no strict ordering between the amount of input used by SLL vs LL,
7128 // which makes it really hard to build a cache for full context. Let's say that
7129 // we have input A B C that leads to an SLL conflict with full context X. That
7130 // implies that using X we might only use A B but we could also use A B C D to
7131 // resolve conflict. Input A B C D could predict alternative 1 in one position
7132 // in the input and A B C E could predict alternative 2 in another position in
7133 // input. The conflicting SLL configurations could still be non-unique in the
7134 // full context prediction, which would lead us to requiring more input than the
7135 // original A B C.  To make a   prediction cache work, we have to track the exact
7136 // input    used during the previous prediction. That amounts to a cache that maps
7137 // X to a specific DFA for that context.</p>
7138 //
7139 // <p>
7140 // Something should be done for left-recursive expression predictions. They are
7141 // likely LL(1) + pred eval. Easier to do the whole SLL unless error and retry
7142 // with full LL thing Sam does.</p>
7143 //
7144 // <p>
7145 // <strong>AVOIDING FULL CONTEXT PREDICTION</strong></p>
7146 //
7147 // <p>
7148 // We avoid doing full context retry when the outer context is empty, we did not
7149 // dip into the outer context by falling off the end of the decision state rule,
7150 // or when we force SLL mode.</p>
7151 //
7152 // <p>
7153 // As an example of the not dip into outer context case, consider as super
7154 // constructor calls versus function calls. One grammar might look like
7155 // this:</p>
7156 //
7157 // <pre>
7158 // ctorBody
7159 //   : '{' superCall? stat* '}'
7160 //   ;
7161 // </pre>
7162 //
7163 // <p>
7164 // Or, you might see something like</p>
7165 //
7166 // <pre>
7167 // stat
7168 //   : superCall ';'
7169 //   | expression ';'
7170 //   | ...
7171 //   ;
7172 // </pre>
7173 //
7174 // <p>
7175 // In both cases I believe that no closure operations will dip into the outer
7176 // context. In the first case ctorBody in the worst case will stop at the '}'.
7177 // In the 2nd case it should stop at the ';'. Both cases should stay within the
7178 // entry rule and not dip into the outer context.</p>
7179 //
7180 // <p>
7181 // <strong>PREDICATES</strong></p>
7182 //
7183 // <p>
7184 // Predicates are always evaluated if present in either SLL or LL both. SLL and
7185 // LL simulation deals with predicates differently. SLL collects predicates as
7186 // it performs closure operations like ANTLR v3 did. It delays predicate
7187 // evaluation until it reaches and accept state. This allows us to cache the SLL
7188 // ATN simulation whereas, if we had evaluated predicates on-the-fly during
7189 // closure, the DFA state configuration sets would be different and we couldn't
7190 // build up a suitable DFA.</p>
7191 //
7192 // <p>
7193 // When building a DFA accept state during ATN simulation, we evaluate any
7194 // predicates and return the sole semantically valid alternative. If there is
7195 // more than 1 alternative, we report an ambiguity. If there are 0 alternatives,
7196 // we throw an exception. Alternatives without predicates act like they have
7197 // true predicates. The simple way to think about it is to strip away all
7198 // alternatives with false predicates and choose the minimum alternative that
7199 // remains.</p>
7200 //
7201 // <p>
7202 // When we start in the DFA and reach an accept state that's predicated, we test
7203 // those and return the minimum semantically viable alternative. If no
7204 // alternatives are viable, we throw an exception.</p>
7205 //
7206 // <p>
7207 // During full LL ATN simulation, closure always evaluates predicates and
7208 // on-the-fly. This is crucial to reducing the configuration set size during
7209 // closure. It hits a landmine when parsing with the Java grammar, for example,
7210 // without this on-the-fly evaluation.</p>
7211 //
7212 // <p>
7213 // <strong>SHARING DFA</strong></p>
7214 //
7215 // <p>
7216 // All instances of the same parser share the same decision DFAs through a
7217 // static field. Each instance gets its own ATN simulator but they share the
7218 // same {@link //decisionToDFA} field. They also share a
7219 // {@link PredictionContextCache} object that makes sure that all
7220 // {@link PredictionContext} objects are shared among the DFA states. This makes
7221 // a big size difference.</p>
7222 //
7223 // <p>
7224 // <strong>THREAD SAFETY</strong></p>
7225 //
7226 // <p>
7227 // The {@link ParserATNSimulator} locks on the {@link //decisionToDFA} field when
7228 // it adds a new DFA object to that array. {@link //addDFAEdge}
7229 // locks on the DFA for the current decision when setting the
7230 // {@link DFAState//edges} field. {@link //addDFAState} locks on
7231 // the DFA for the current decision when looking up a DFA state to see if it
7232 // already exists. We must make sure that all requests to add DFA states that
7233 // are equivalent result in the same shared DFA object. This is because lots of
7234 // threads will be trying to update the DFA at once. The
7235 // {@link //addDFAState} method also locks inside the DFA lock
7236 // but this time on the shared context cache when it rebuilds the
7237 // configurations' {@link PredictionContext} objects using cached
7238 // subgraphs/nodes. No other locking occurs, even during DFA simulation. This is
7239 // safe as long as we can guarantee that all threads referencing
7240 // {@code s.edge[t]} get the same physical target {@link DFAState}, or
7241 // {@code null}. Once into the DFA, the DFA simulation does not reference the
7242 // {@link DFA//states} map. It follows the {@link DFAState//edges} field to new
7243 // targets. The DFA simulator will either find {@link DFAState//edges} to be
7244 // {@code null}, to be non-{@code null} and {@code dfa.edges[t]} null, or
7245 // {@code dfa.edges[t]} to be non-null. The
7246 // {@link //addDFAEdge} method could be racing to set the field
7247 // but in either case the DFA simulator works; if {@code null}, and requests ATN
7248 // simulation. It could also race trying to get {@code dfa.edges[t]}, but either
7249 // way it will work because it's not doing a test and set operation.</p>
7250 //
7251 // <p>
7252 // <strong>Starting with SLL then failing to combined SLL/LL (Two-Stage
7253 // Parsing)</strong></p>
7254 //
7255 // <p>
7256 // Sam pointed out that if SLL does not give a syntax error, then there is no
7257 // point in doing full LL, which is slower. We only have to try LL if we get a
7258 // syntax error. For maximum speed, Sam starts the parser set to pure SLL
7259 // mode with the {@link BailErrorStrategy}:</p>
7260 //
7261 // <pre>
7262 // parser.{@link Parser//getInterpreter() getInterpreter()}.{@link //setPredictionMode setPredictionMode}{@code (}{@link PredictionMode//SLL}{@code )};
7263 // parser.{@link Parser//setErrorHandler setErrorHandler}(new {@link BailErrorStrategy}());
7264 // </pre>
7265 //
7266 // <p>
7267 // If it does not get a syntax error, then we're done. If it does get a syntax
7268 // error, we need to retry with the combined SLL/LL strategy.</p>
7269 //
7270 // <p>
7271 // The reason this works is as follows. If there are no SLL conflicts, then the
7272 // grammar is SLL (at least for that input set). If there is an SLL conflict,
7273 // the full LL analysis must yield a set of viable alternatives which is a
7274 // subset of the alternatives reported by SLL. If the LL set is a singleton,
7275 // then the grammar is LL but not SLL. If the LL set is the same size as the SLL
7276 // set, the decision is SLL. If the LL set has size &gt; 1, then that decision
7277 // is truly ambiguous on the current input. If the LL set is smaller, then the
7278 // SLL conflict resolution might choose an alternative that the full LL would
7279 // rule out as a possibility based upon better context information. If that's
7280 // the case, then the SLL parse will definitely get an error because the full LL
7281 // analysis says it's not viable. If SLL conflict resolution chooses an
7282 // alternative within the LL set, them both SLL and LL would choose the same
7283 // alternative because they both choose the minimum of multiple conflicting
7284 // alternatives.</p>
7285 //
7286 // <p>
7287 // Let's say we have a set of SLL conflicting alternatives {@code {1, 2, 3}} and
7288 // a smaller LL set called <em>s</em>. If <em>s</em> is {@code {2, 3}}, then SLL
7289 // parsing will get an error because SLL will pursue alternative 1. If
7290 // <em>s</em> is {@code {1, 2}} or {@code {1, 3}} then both SLL and LL will
7291 // choose the same alternative because alternative one is the minimum of either
7292 // set. If <em>s</em> is {@code {2}} or {@code {3}} then SLL will get a syntax
7293 // error. If <em>s</em> is {@code {1}} then SLL will succeed.</p>
7294 //
7295 // <p>
7296 // Of course, if the input is invalid, then we will get an error for sure in
7297 // both SLL and LL parsing. Erroneous input will therefore require 2 passes over
7298 // the input.</p>
7299 //
7300

7304 var DoubleDict = Utils.DoubleDict;

7306 var ATNState = require('./ATNState').ATNState;
7307 var ATNConfig = require('./ATNConfig').ATNConfig;
7308 var ATNConfigSet = require('./ATNConfigSet').ATNConfigSet;
7309 var Token = require('./../Token').Token;
7310 var DFAState = require('./../dfa/DFAState').DFAState;
7311 var PredPrediction = require('./../dfa/DFAState').PredPrediction;
7312 var ATNSimulator = require('./ATNSimulator').ATNSimulator;
7313 var PredictionMode = require('./PredictionMode').PredictionMode;
7314 var RuleContext = require('./../RuleContext').RuleContext;
7315 var ParserRuleContext = require('./../ParserRuleContext').ParserRuleContext;
7316 var SemanticContext = require('./SemanticContext').SemanticContext;
7317 var StarLoopEntryState = require('./ATNState').StarLoopEntryState;
7318 var RuleStopState = require('./ATNState').RuleStopState;
7319 var PredictionContext = require('./../PredictionContext').PredictionContext;
7320 var Interval = require('./../IntervalSet').Interval;
7321 var Transitions = require('./Transition');
7322 var Transition = Transitions.Transition;

7332 function ParserATNSimulator(parser, atn, decisionToDFA, sharedContextCache) {
7333 	ATNSimulator.call(this, atn, sharedContextCache);
7334     this.parser = parser;
7335     this.decisionToDFA = decisionToDFA;
7336     // SLL, LL, or LL + exact ambig detection?//
7337     this.predictionMode = PredictionMode.LL;
7338     // LAME globals to avoid parameters!!!!! I need these down deep in predTransition
7339     this._input = null;
7340     this._startIndex = 0;
7341     this._outerContext = null;
7342     this._dfa = null;
7343     // Each prediction operation uses a cache for merge of prediction contexts.
7344     //  Don't keep around as it wastes huge amounts of memory. DoubleKeyMap
7345     //  isn't synchronized but we're ok since two threads shouldn't reuse same
7346     //  parser/atnsim object because it can only handle one input at a time.
7347     //  This maps graphs a and b to merged result c. (a,b)&rarr;c. We can avoid
7348     //  the merge if we ever see a and b again.  Note that (b,a)&rarr;c should
7349     //  also be examined during cache lookup.
7350     //
7351     this.mergeCache = null;
7352     return this;
7353 }

7355 ParserATNSimulator.prototype = Object.create(ATNSimulator.prototype);
7356 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.constructor = ParserATNSimulator;
7357 
7358 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.debug = false;
7359 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.debug_closure = false;
7360 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.debug_add = false;
7361 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.debug_list_atn_decisions = false;
7362 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.dfa_debug = false;
7363 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.retry_debug = false;
