7365 
7366 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.reset = function() {
7367 };
7368 
7369 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.adaptivePredict = function(input, decision, outerContext) {
7370     if (this.debug || this.debug_list_atn_decisions) {
7371         console.log("adaptivePredict decision " + decision +
7372                                " exec LA(1)==" + this.getLookaheadName(input) +
7373                                " line " + input.LT(1).line + ":" +
7374                                input.LT(1).column);
7375     }
7376     this._input = input;
7377     this._startIndex = input.index;
7378     this._outerContext = outerContext;
7379 
7380     var dfa = this.decisionToDFA[decision];
7381     this._dfa = dfa;
7382     var m = input.mark();
7383     var index = input.index;
7384 
7385     // Now we are certain to have a specific decision's DFA
7386     // But, do we still need an initial state?
7387     try {
7388         var s0;
7389         if (dfa.precedenceDfa) {
7390             // the start state for a precedence DFA depends on the current
7391             // parser precedence, and is provided by a DFA method.
7392             s0 = dfa.getPrecedenceStartState(this.parser.getPrecedence());
7393         } else {
7394             // the start state for a "regular" DFA is just s0
7395             s0 = dfa.s0;
7396         }
7397         if (s0===null) {
7398             if (outerContext===null) {
7399                 outerContext = RuleContext.EMPTY;
7400             }
7401             if (this.debug || this.debug_list_atn_decisions) {
7402                 console.log("predictATN decision " + dfa.decision +
7403                                    " exec LA(1)==" + this.getLookaheadName(input) +
7404                                    ", outerContext=" + outerContext.toString(this.parser.ruleNames));
7405             }
7406 
7407             var fullCtx = false;
7408             var s0_closure = this.computeStartState(dfa.atnStartState, RuleContext.EMPTY, fullCtx);
7409 
7410             if( dfa.precedenceDfa) {
7411                 // If this is a precedence DFA, we use applyPrecedenceFilter
7412                 // to convert the computed start state to a precedence start
7413                 // state. We then use DFA.setPrecedenceStartState to set the
7414                 // appropriate start state for the precedence level rather
7415                 // than simply setting DFA.s0.
7416                 //
7417                 dfa.s0.configs = s0_closure; // not used for prediction but useful to know start configs anyway
7418                 s0_closure = this.applyPrecedenceFilter(s0_closure);
7419                 s0 = this.addDFAState(dfa, new DFAState(null, s0_closure));
7420                 dfa.setPrecedenceStartState(this.parser.getPrecedence(), s0);
7421             } else {
7422                 s0 = this.addDFAState(dfa, new DFAState(null, s0_closure));
7423                 dfa.s0 = s0;
7424             }
7425         }
7426         var alt = this.execATN(dfa, s0, input, index, outerContext);
7427         if (this.debug) {
7428             console.log("DFA after predictATN: " + dfa.toString(this.parser.literalNames));
7429         }
7430         return alt;
7431     } finally {
7432         this._dfa = null;
7433         this.mergeCache = null; // wack cache after each prediction
7434         input.seek(index);
7435         input.release(m);
7436     }
7437 };
7438 // Performs ATN simulation to compute a predicted alternative based
7439 //  upon the remaining input, but also updates the DFA cache to avoid
7440 //  having to traverse the ATN again for the same input sequence.
7441 
7442 // There are some key conditions we're looking for after computing a new
7443 // set of ATN configs (proposed DFA state):
7444       // if the set is empty, there is no viable alternative for current symbol
7445       // does the state uniquely predict an alternative?
7446       // does the state have a conflict that would prevent us from
7447       //   putting it on the work list?
7448 
7449 // We also have some key operations to do:
7450       // add an edge from previous DFA state to potentially new DFA state, D,
7451       //   upon current symbol but only if adding to work list, which means in all
7452       //   cases except no viable alternative (and possibly non-greedy decisions?)
7453       // collecting predicates and adding semantic context to DFA accept states
7454       // adding rule context to context-sensitive DFA accept states
7455       // consuming an input symbol
7456       // reporting a conflict
7457       // reporting an ambiguity
7458       // reporting a context sensitivity
7459       // reporting insufficient predicates
7460 
7461 // cover these cases:
7462 //    dead end
7463 //    single alt
7464 //    single alt + preds
7465 //    conflict
7466 //    conflict + preds
7467 //
7468 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.execATN = function(dfa, s0, input, startIndex, outerContext ) {
7469     if (this.debug || this.debug_list_atn_decisions) {
7470         console.log("execATN decision " + dfa.decision +
7471                 " exec LA(1)==" + this.getLookaheadName(input) +
7472                 " line " + input.LT(1).line + ":" + input.LT(1).column);
7473     }
7474     var alt;
7475     var previousD = s0;
7476 
7477     if (this.debug) {
7478         console.log("s0 = " + s0);
7479     }
7480     var t = input.LA(1);
7481     while(true) { // while more work
7482         var D = this.getExistingTargetState(previousD, t);
7483         if(D===null) {
7484             D = this.computeTargetState(dfa, previousD, t);
7485         }
7486         if(D===ATNSimulator.ERROR) {
7487             // if any configs in previous dipped into outer context, that
7488             // means that input up to t actually finished entry rule
7489             // at least for SLL decision. Full LL doesn't dip into outer
7490             // so don't need special case.
7491             // We will get an error no matter what so delay until after
7492             // decision; better error message. Also, no reachable target
7493             // ATN states in SLL implies LL will also get nowhere.
7494             // If conflict in states that dip out, choose min since we
7495             // will get error no matter what.
7496             var e = this.noViableAlt(input, outerContext, previousD.configs, startIndex);
7497             input.seek(startIndex);
7498             alt = this.getSynValidOrSemInvalidAltThatFinishedDecisionEntryRule(previousD.configs, outerContext);
7499             if(alt!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
7500                 return alt;
7501             } else {
7502                 throw e;
7503             }
7504         }
7505         if(D.requiresFullContext && this.predictionMode !== PredictionMode.SLL) {
7506             // IF PREDS, MIGHT RESOLVE TO SINGLE ALT => SLL (or syntax error)
7507             var conflictingAlts = null;
7508             if (D.predicates!==null) {
7509                 if (this.debug) {
7510                     console.log("DFA state has preds in DFA sim LL failover");
7511                 }
7512                 var conflictIndex = input.index;
7513                 if(conflictIndex !== startIndex) {
7514                     input.seek(startIndex);
7515                 }
7516                 conflictingAlts = this.evalSemanticContext(D.predicates, outerContext, true);
7517                 if (conflictingAlts.length===1) {
7518                     if(this.debug) {
7519                         console.log("Full LL avoided");
7520                     }
7521                     return conflictingAlts.minValue();
7522                 }
7523                 if (conflictIndex !== startIndex) {
7524                     // restore the index so reporting the fallback to full
7525                     // context occurs with the index at the correct spot
7526                     input.seek(conflictIndex);
7527                 }
7528             }
7529             if (this.dfa_debug) {
7530                 console.log("ctx sensitive state " + outerContext +" in " + D);
7531             }
7532             var fullCtx = true;
7533             var s0_closure = this.computeStartState(dfa.atnStartState, outerContext, fullCtx);
7534             this.reportAttemptingFullContext(dfa, conflictingAlts, D.configs, startIndex, input.index);
7535             alt = this.execATNWithFullContext(dfa, D, s0_closure, input, startIndex, outerContext);
7536             return alt;
7537         }
7538         if (D.isAcceptState) {
7539             if (D.predicates===null) {
7540                 return D.prediction;
7541             }
7542             var stopIndex = input.index;
7543             input.seek(startIndex);
7544             var alts = this.evalSemanticContext(D.predicates, outerContext, true);
7545             if (alts.length===0) {
7546                 throw this.noViableAlt(input, outerContext, D.configs, startIndex);
7547             } else if (alts.length===1) {
7548                 return alts.minValue();
7549             } else {
7550                 // report ambiguity after predicate evaluation to make sure the correct set of ambig alts is reported.
7551                 this.reportAmbiguity(dfa, D, startIndex, stopIndex, false, alts, D.configs);
7552                 return alts.minValue();
7553             }
7554         }
7555         previousD = D;
7556 
7557         if (t !== Token.EOF) {
7558             input.consume();
7559             t = input.LA(1);
7560         }
7561     }
7562 };
7563 //
7564 // Get an existing target state for an edge in the DFA. If the target state
7565 // for the edge has not yet been computed or is otherwise not available,
7566 // this method returns {@code null}.
7567 //
7568 // @param previousD The current DFA state
7569 // @param t The next input symbol
7570 // @return The existing target DFA state for the given input symbol
7571 // {@code t}, or {@code null} if the target state for this edge is not
7572 // already cached
7573 //
7574 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getExistingTargetState = function(previousD, t) {
7575     var edges = previousD.edges;
7576     if (edges===null) {
7577         return null;
7578     } else {
7579         return edges[t + 1] || null;
7580     }
7581 };
7582 //
7583 // Compute a target state for an edge in the DFA, and attempt to add the
7584 // computed state and corresponding edge to the DFA.
7585 //
7586 // @param dfa The DFA
7587 // @param previousD The current DFA state
7588 // @param t The next input symbol
7589 //
7590 // @return The computed target DFA state for the given input symbol
7591 // {@code t}. If {@code t} does not lead to a valid DFA state, this method
7592 // returns {@link //ERROR}.
7593 //
7594 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.computeTargetState = function(dfa, previousD, t) {
7595    var reach = this.computeReachSet(previousD.configs, t, false);
7596     if(reach===null) {
7597         this.addDFAEdge(dfa, previousD, t, ATNSimulator.ERROR);
7598         return ATNSimulator.ERROR;
7599     }
7600     // create new target state; we'll add to DFA after it's complete
7601     var D = new DFAState(null, reach);
7602 
7603     var predictedAlt = this.getUniqueAlt(reach);
7604 
7605     if (this.debug) {
7606         var altSubSets = PredictionMode.getConflictingAltSubsets(reach);
7607         console.log("SLL altSubSets=" + Utils.arrayToString(altSubSets) +
7608                     ", previous=" + previousD.configs +
7609                     ", configs=" + reach +
7610                     ", predict=" + predictedAlt +
7611                     ", allSubsetsConflict=" +
7612                     PredictionMode.allSubsetsConflict(altSubSets) + ", conflictingAlts=" +
7613                     this.getConflictingAlts(reach));
7614     }
7615     if (predictedAlt!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
7616         // NO CONFLICT, UNIQUELY PREDICTED ALT
7617         D.isAcceptState = true;
7618         D.configs.uniqueAlt = predictedAlt;
7619         D.prediction = predictedAlt;
7620     } else if (PredictionMode.hasSLLConflictTerminatingPrediction(this.predictionMode, reach)) {
7621         // MORE THAN ONE VIABLE ALTERNATIVE
7622         D.configs.conflictingAlts = this.getConflictingAlts(reach);
7623         D.requiresFullContext = true;
7624         // in SLL-only mode, we will stop at this state and return the minimum alt
7625         D.isAcceptState = true;
7626         D.prediction = D.configs.conflictingAlts.minValue();
7627     }
7628     if (D.isAcceptState && D.configs.hasSemanticContext) {
7629         this.predicateDFAState(D, this.atn.getDecisionState(dfa.decision));
7630         if( D.predicates!==null) {
7631             D.prediction = ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
7632         }
7633     }
7634     // all adds to dfa are done after we've created full D state
7635     D = this.addDFAEdge(dfa, previousD, t, D);
7636     return D;
7637 };
7638 
7639 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.predicateDFAState = function(dfaState, decisionState) {
7640     // We need to test all predicates, even in DFA states that
7641     // uniquely predict alternative.
7642     var nalts = decisionState.transitions.length;
7643     // Update DFA so reach becomes accept state with (predicate,alt)
7644     // pairs if preds found for conflicting alts
7645     var altsToCollectPredsFrom = this.getConflictingAltsOrUniqueAlt(dfaState.configs);
7646     var altToPred = this.getPredsForAmbigAlts(altsToCollectPredsFrom, dfaState.configs, nalts);
7647     if (altToPred!==null) {
7648         dfaState.predicates = this.getPredicatePredictions(altsToCollectPredsFrom, altToPred);
7649         dfaState.prediction = ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER; // make sure we use preds
7650     } else {
7651         // There are preds in configs but they might go away
7652         // when OR'd together like {p}? || NONE == NONE. If neither
7653         // alt has preds, resolve to min alt
7654         dfaState.prediction = altsToCollectPredsFrom.minValue();
7655     }
7656 };
7657 
7658 // comes back with reach.uniqueAlt set to a valid alt
7659 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.execATNWithFullContext = function(dfa, D, // how far we got before failing over
7660                                      s0,
7661                                      input,
7662                                      startIndex,
7663                                      outerContext) {
7664     if (this.debug || this.debug_list_atn_decisions) {
7665         console.log("execATNWithFullContext "+s0);
7666     }
7667     var fullCtx = true;
7668     var foundExactAmbig = false;
7669     var reach = null;
7670     var previous = s0;
7671     input.seek(startIndex);
7672     var t = input.LA(1);
7673     var predictedAlt = -1;
7674     while (true) { // while more work
7675         reach = this.computeReachSet(previous, t, fullCtx);
7676         if (reach===null) {
7677             // if any configs in previous dipped into outer context, that
7678             // means that input up to t actually finished entry rule
7679             // at least for LL decision. Full LL doesn't dip into outer
7680             // so don't need special case.
7681             // We will get an error no matter what so delay until after
7682             // decision; better error message. Also, no reachable target
7683             // ATN states in SLL implies LL will also get nowhere.
7684             // If conflict in states that dip out, choose min since we
7685             // will get error no matter what.
7686             var e = this.noViableAlt(input, outerContext, previous, startIndex);
7687             input.seek(startIndex);
7688             var alt = this.getSynValidOrSemInvalidAltThatFinishedDecisionEntryRule(previous, outerContext);
7689             if(alt!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
7690                 return alt;
7691             } else {
7692                 throw e;
7693             }
7694         }
7695         var altSubSets = PredictionMode.getConflictingAltSubsets(reach);
7696         if(this.debug) {
7697             console.log("LL altSubSets=" + altSubSets + ", predict=" +
7698                   PredictionMode.getUniqueAlt(altSubSets) + ", resolvesToJustOneViableAlt=" +
7699                   PredictionMode.resolvesToJustOneViableAlt(altSubSets));
7700         }
7701         reach.uniqueAlt = this.getUniqueAlt(reach);
7702         // unique prediction?
7703         if(reach.uniqueAlt!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
7704             predictedAlt = reach.uniqueAlt;
7705             break;
7706         } else if (this.predictionMode !== PredictionMode.LL_EXACT_AMBIG_DETECTION) {
7707             predictedAlt = PredictionMode.resolvesToJustOneViableAlt(altSubSets);
7708             if(predictedAlt !== ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
7709                 break;
7710             }
7711         } else {
7712             // In exact ambiguity mode, we never try to terminate early.
7713             // Just keeps scarfing until we know what the conflict is
7714             if (PredictionMode.allSubsetsConflict(altSubSets) && PredictionMode.allSubsetsEqual(altSubSets)) {
7715                 foundExactAmbig = true;
7716                 predictedAlt = PredictionMode.getSingleViableAlt(altSubSets);
7717                 break;
7718             }
7719             // else there are multiple non-conflicting subsets or
7720             // we're not sure what the ambiguity is yet.
7721             // So, keep going.
7722         }
7723         previous = reach;
7724         if( t !== Token.EOF) {
7725             input.consume();
7726             t = input.LA(1);
7727         }
7728     }
7729     // If the configuration set uniquely predicts an alternative,
7730     // without conflict, then we know that it's a full LL decision
7731     // not SLL.
7732     if (reach.uniqueAlt !== ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER ) {
7733         this.reportContextSensitivity(dfa, predictedAlt, reach, startIndex, input.index);
7734         return predictedAlt;
7735     }
7736     // We do not check predicates here because we have checked them
7737     // on-the-fly when doing full context prediction.
7738 
7739     //
7740     // In non-exact ambiguity detection mode, we might  actually be able to
7741     // detect an exact ambiguity, but I'm not going to spend the cycles
7742     // needed to check. We only emit ambiguity warnings in exact ambiguity
7743     // mode.
7744     //
7745     // For example, we might know that we have conflicting configurations.
7746     // But, that does not mean that there is no way forward without a
7747     // conflict. It's possible to have nonconflicting alt subsets as in:
7748 
7749     // altSubSets=[{1, 2}, {1, 2}, {1}, {1, 2}]
7750 
7751     // from
7752     //
7753     //    [(17,1,[5 $]), (13,1,[5 10 $]), (21,1,[5 10 $]), (11,1,[$]),
7754     //     (13,2,[5 10 $]), (21,2,[5 10 $]), (11,2,[$])]
7755     //
7756     // In this case, (17,1,[5 $]) indicates there is some next sequence that
7757     // would resolve this without conflict to alternative 1. Any other viable
7758     // next sequence, however, is associated with a conflict.  We stop
7759     // looking for input because no amount of further lookahead will alter
7760     // the fact that we should predict alternative 1.  We just can't say for
7761     // sure that there is an ambiguity without looking further.
7762 
7763     this.reportAmbiguity(dfa, D, startIndex, input.index, foundExactAmbig, null, reach);
7764 
7765     return predictedAlt;
7766 };
7767 
7768 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.computeReachSet = function(closure, t, fullCtx) {
7769     if (this.debug) {
7770         console.log("in computeReachSet, starting closure: " + closure);
7771     }
7772     if( this.mergeCache===null) {
7773         this.mergeCache = new DoubleDict();
7774     }
7775     var intermediate = new ATNConfigSet(fullCtx);
7776 
7777     // Configurations already in a rule stop state indicate reaching the end
7778     // of the decision rule (local context) or end of the start rule (full
7779     // context). Once reached, these configurations are never updated by a
7780     // closure operation, so they are handled separately for the performance
7781     // advantage of having a smaller intermediate set when calling closure.
7782     //
7783     // For full-context reach operations, separate handling is required to
7784     // ensure that the alternative matching the longest overall sequence is
7785     // chosen when multiple such configurations can match the input.
7786 
7787     var skippedStopStates = null;
7788 
7789     // First figure out where we can reach on input t
7790     for (var i=0; i<closure.items.length;i++) {
7791         var c = closure.items[i];
7792         if(this.debug_add) {
7793             console.log("testing " + this.getTokenName(t) + " at " + c);
7794         }
7795         if (c.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
7796             if (fullCtx || t === Token.EOF) {
7797                 if (skippedStopStates===null) {
7798                     skippedStopStates = [];
7799                 }
7800                 skippedStopStates.push(c);
7801                 if(this.debug_add) {
7802                     console.log("added " + c + " to skippedStopStates");
7803                 }
7804             }
7805             continue;
7806         }
7807         for(var j=0;j<c.state.transitions.length;j++) {
7808             var trans = c.state.transitions[j];
7809             var target = this.getReachableTarget(trans, t);
7810             if (target!==null) {
7811                 var cfg = new ATNConfig({state:target}, c);
7812                 intermediate.add(cfg, this.mergeCache);
7813                 if(this.debug_add) {
7814                     console.log("added " + cfg + " to intermediate");
7815                 }
7816             }
7817         }
7818     }
7819     // Now figure out where the reach operation can take us...
7820     var reach = null;
7821 
7822     // This block optimizes the reach operation for intermediate sets which
7823     // trivially indicate a termination state for the overall
7824     // adaptivePredict operation.
7825     //
7826     // The conditions assume that intermediate
7827     // contains all configurations relevant to the reach set, but this
7828     // condition is not true when one or more configurations have been
7829     // withheld in skippedStopStates, or when the current symbol is EOF.
7830     //
7831     if (skippedStopStates===null && t!==Token.EOF) {
7832         if (intermediate.items.length===1) {
7833             // Don't pursue the closure if there is just one state.
7834             // It can only have one alternative; just add to result
7835             // Also don't pursue the closure if there is unique alternative
7836             // among the configurations.
7837             reach = intermediate;
7838         } else if (this.getUniqueAlt(intermediate)!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
7839             // Also don't pursue the closure if there is unique alternative
7840             // among the configurations.
7841             reach = intermediate;
7842         }
7843     }
7844     // If the reach set could not be trivially determined, perform a closure
7845     // operation on the intermediate set to compute its initial value.
7846     //
7847     if (reach===null) {
7848         reach = new ATNConfigSet(fullCtx);
7849         var closureBusy = new Set();
7850         var treatEofAsEpsilon = t === Token.EOF;
7851         for (var k=0; k<intermediate.items.length;k++) {
7852             this.closure(intermediate.items[k], reach, closureBusy, false, fullCtx, treatEofAsEpsilon);
7853         }
7854     }
7855     if (t === Token.EOF) {
7856         // After consuming EOF no additional input is possible, so we are
7857         // only interested in configurations which reached the end of the
7858         // decision rule (local context) or end of the start rule (full
7859         // context). Update reach to contain only these configurations. This
7860         // handles both explicit EOF transitions in the grammar and implicit
7861         // EOF transitions following the end of the decision or start rule.
7862         //
7863         // When reach==intermediate, no closure operation was performed. In
7864         // this case, removeAllConfigsNotInRuleStopState needs to check for
7865         // reachable rule stop states as well as configurations already in
7866         // a rule stop state.
7867         //
7868         // This is handled before the configurations in skippedStopStates,
7869         // because any configurations potentially added from that list are
7870         // already guaranteed to meet this condition whether or not it's
7871         // required.
7872         //
7873         reach = this.removeAllConfigsNotInRuleStopState(reach, reach === intermediate);
7874     }
7875     // If skippedStopStates!==null, then it contains at least one
7876     // configuration. For full-context reach operations, these
7877     // configurations reached the end of the start rule, in which case we
7878     // only add them back to reach if no configuration during the current
7879     // closure operation reached such a state. This ensures adaptivePredict
7880     // chooses an alternative matching the longest overall sequence when
7881     // multiple alternatives are viable.
7882     //
7883     if (skippedStopStates!==null && ( (! fullCtx) || (! PredictionMode.hasConfigInRuleStopState(reach)))) {
7884         for (var l=0; l<skippedStopStates.length;l++) {
7885             reach.add(skippedStopStates[l], this.mergeCache);
7886         }
7887     }
7888     if (reach.items.length===0) {
7889         return null;
7890     } else {
7891         return reach;
7892     }
7893 };
7894 //
7895 // Return a configuration set containing only the configurations from
7896 // {@code configs} which are in a {@link RuleStopState}. If all
7897 // configurations in {@code configs} are already in a rule stop state, this
7898 // method simply returns {@code configs}.
7899 //
7900 // <p>When {@code lookToEndOfRule} is true, this method uses
7901 // {@link ATN//nextTokens} for each configuration in {@code configs} which is
7902 // not already in a rule stop state to see if a rule stop state is reachable
7903 // from the configuration via epsilon-only transitions.</p>
7904 //
7905 // @param configs the configuration set to update
7906 // @param lookToEndOfRule when true, this method checks for rule stop states
7907 // reachable by epsilon-only transitions from each configuration in
7908 // {@code configs}.
7909 //
7910 // @return {@code configs} if all configurations in {@code configs} are in a
7911 // rule stop state, otherwise return a new configuration set containing only
7912 // the configurations from {@code configs} which are in a rule stop state
7913 //
7914 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.removeAllConfigsNotInRuleStopState = function(configs, lookToEndOfRule) {
7915     if (PredictionMode.allConfigsInRuleStopStates(configs)) {
7916         return configs;
7917     }
7918     var result = new ATNConfigSet(configs.fullCtx);
7919     for(var i=0; i<configs.items.length;i++) {
7920         var config = configs.items[i];
7921         if (config.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
7922             result.add(config, this.mergeCache);
7923             continue;
7924         }
7925         if (lookToEndOfRule && config.state.epsilonOnlyTransitions) {
7926             var nextTokens = this.atn.nextTokens(config.state);
7927             if (nextTokens.contains(Token.EPSILON)) {
7928                 var endOfRuleState = this.atn.ruleToStopState[config.state.ruleIndex];
7929                 result.add(new ATNConfig({state:endOfRuleState}, config), this.mergeCache);
7930             }
7931         }
7932     }
7933     return result;
7934 };
7935 
7936 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.computeStartState = function(p, ctx, fullCtx) {
7937     // always at least the implicit call to start rule
7938     var initialContext = predictionContextFromRuleContext(this.atn, ctx);
7939     var configs = new ATNConfigSet(fullCtx);
7940     for(var i=0;i<p.transitions.length;i++) {
7941         var target = p.transitions[i].target;
7942         var c = new ATNConfig({ state:target, alt:i+1, context:initialContext }, null);
7943         var closureBusy = new Set();
7944         this.closure(c, configs, closureBusy, true, fullCtx, false);
7945     }
7946     return configs;
7947 };
7948 
7949 //
7950 // This method transforms the start state computed by
7951 // {@link //computeStartState} to the special start state used by a
7952 // precedence DFA for a particular precedence value. The transformation
7953 // process applies the following changes to the start state's configuration
7954 // set.
7955 //
7956 // <ol>
7957 // <li>Evaluate the precedence predicates for each configuration using
7958 // {@link SemanticContext//evalPrecedence}.</li>
7959 // <li>Remove all configurations which predict an alternative greater than
7960 // 1, for which another configuration that predicts alternative 1 is in the
7961 // same ATN state with the same prediction context. This transformation is
7962 // valid for the following reasons:
7963 // <ul>
7964 // <li>The closure block cannot contain any epsilon transitions which bypass
7965 // the body of the closure, so all states reachable via alternative 1 are
7966 // part of the precedence alternatives of the transformed left-recursive
7967 // rule.</li>
7968 // <li>The "primary" portion of a left recursive rule cannot contain an
7969 // epsilon transition, so the only way an alternative other than 1 can exist
7970 // in a state that is also reachable via alternative 1 is by nesting calls
7971 // to the left-recursive rule, with the outer calls not being at the
7972 // preferred precedence level.</li>
7973 // </ul>
7974 // </li>
7975 // </ol>
7976 //
7977 // <p>
7978 // The prediction context must be considered by this filter to address
7979 // situations like the following.
7980 // </p>
7981 // <code>
7982 // <pre>
7983 // grammar TA;
7984 // prog: statement* EOF;
7985 // statement: letterA | statement letterA 'b' ;
7986 // letterA: 'a';
7987 // </pre>
7988 // </code>
7989 // <p>
7990 // If the above grammar, the ATN state immediately before the token
7991 // reference {@code 'a'} in {@code letterA} is reachable from the left edge
7992 // of both the primary and closure blocks of the left-recursive rule
7993 // {@code statement}. The prediction context associated with each of these
7994 // configurations distinguishes between them, and prevents the alternative
7995 // which stepped out to {@code prog} (and then back in to {@code statement}
7996 // from being eliminated by the filter.
7997 // </p>
7998 //
7999 // @param configs The configuration set computed by
8000 // {@link //computeStartState} as the start state for the DFA.
8001 // @return The transformed configuration set representing the start state
8002 // for a precedence DFA at a particular precedence level (determined by
8003 // calling {@link Parser//getPrecedence}).
8004 //
8005 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.applyPrecedenceFilter = function(configs) {
8006 	var config;
8007 	var statesFromAlt1 = [];
8008     var configSet = new ATNConfigSet(configs.fullCtx);
8009     for(var i=0; i<configs.items.length; i++) {
8010         config = configs.items[i];
8011         // handle alt 1 first
8012         if (config.alt !== 1) {
8013             continue;
8014         }
8015         var updatedContext = config.semanticContext.evalPrecedence(this.parser, this._outerContext);
8016         if (updatedContext===null) {
8017             // the configuration was eliminated
8018             continue;
8019         }
8020         statesFromAlt1[config.state.stateNumber] = config.context;
8021         if (updatedContext !== config.semanticContext) {
8022             configSet.add(new ATNConfig({semanticContext:updatedContext}, config), this.mergeCache);
8023         } else {
8024             configSet.add(config, this.mergeCache);
8025         }
8026     }
8027     for(i=0; i<configs.items.length; i++) {
8028         config = configs.items[i];
8029         if (config.alt === 1) {
8030             // already handled
8031             continue;
8032         }
8033         // In the future, this elimination step could be updated to also
8034         // filter the prediction context for alternatives predicting alt>1
8035         // (basically a graph subtraction algorithm).
8036 		if (!config.precedenceFilterSuppressed) {
8037             var context = statesFromAlt1[config.state.stateNumber] || null;
8038             if (context!==null && context.equals(config.context)) {
8039                 // eliminated
8040                 continue;
8041             }
8042 		}
8043         configSet.add(config, this.mergeCache);
8044     }
8045     return configSet;
8046 };
8047 
8048 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getReachableTarget = function(trans, ttype) {
8049     if (trans.matches(ttype, 0, this.atn.maxTokenType)) {
8050         return trans.target;
8051     } else {
8052         return null;
8053     }
8054 };
8055 
8056 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getPredsForAmbigAlts = function(ambigAlts, configs, nalts) {
8057     // REACH=[1|1|[]|0:0, 1|2|[]|0:1]
8058     // altToPred starts as an array of all null contexts. The entry at index i
8059     // corresponds to alternative i. altToPred[i] may have one of three values:
8060     //   1. null: no ATNConfig c is found such that c.alt==i
8061     //   2. SemanticContext.NONE: At least one ATNConfig c exists such that
8062     //      c.alt==i and c.semanticContext==SemanticContext.NONE. In other words,
8063     //      alt i has at least one unpredicated config.
8064     //   3. Non-NONE Semantic Context: There exists at least one, and for all
8065     //      ATNConfig c such that c.alt==i, c.semanticContext!=SemanticContext.NONE.
8066     //
8067     // From this, it is clear that NONE||anything==NONE.
8068     //
8069     var altToPred = [];
8070     for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length;i++) {
8071         var c = configs.items[i];
8072         if(ambigAlts.contains( c.alt )) {
8073             altToPred[c.alt] = SemanticContext.orContext(altToPred[c.alt] || null, c.semanticContext);
8074         }
8075     }
8076     var nPredAlts = 0;
8077     for (i =1;i< nalts+1;i++) {
8078         var pred = altToPred[i] || null;
8079         if (pred===null) {
8080             altToPred[i] = SemanticContext.NONE;
8081         } else if (pred !== SemanticContext.NONE) {
8082             nPredAlts += 1;
8083         }
8084     }
8085     // nonambig alts are null in altToPred
8086     if (nPredAlts===0) {
8087         altToPred = null;
8088     }
8089     if (this.debug) {
8090         console.log("getPredsForAmbigAlts result " + Utils.arrayToString(altToPred));
8091     }
8092     return altToPred;
8093 };
8094 
8095 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getPredicatePredictions = function(ambigAlts, altToPred) {
8096     var pairs = [];
8097     var containsPredicate = false;
8098     for (var i=1; i<altToPred.length;i++) {
8099         var pred = altToPred[i];
8100         // unpredicated is indicated by SemanticContext.NONE
8101         if( ambigAlts!==null && ambigAlts.contains( i )) {
8102             pairs.push(new PredPrediction(pred, i));
8103         }
8104         if (pred !== SemanticContext.NONE) {
8105             containsPredicate = true;
8106         }
8107     }
8108     if (! containsPredicate) {
8109         return null;
8110     }
8111     return pairs;
8112 };
8113 
8114 //
8115 // This method is used to improve the localization of error messages by
8116 // choosing an alternative rather than throwing a
8117 // {@link NoViableAltException} in particular prediction scenarios where the
8118 // {@link //ERROR} state was reached during ATN simulation.
8119 //
8120 // <p>
8121 // The default implementation of this method uses the following
8122 // algorithm to identify an ATN configuration which successfully parsed the
8123 // decision entry rule. Choosing such an alternative ensures that the
8124 // {@link ParserRuleContext} returned by the calling rule will be complete
8125 // and valid, and the syntax error will be reported later at a more
8126 // localized location.</p>
8127 //
8128 // <ul>
8129 // <li>If a syntactically valid path or paths reach the end of the decision rule and
8130 // they are semantically valid if predicated, return the min associated alt.</li>
8131 // <li>Else, if a semantically invalid but syntactically valid path exist
8132 // or paths exist, return the minimum associated alt.
8133 // </li>
8134 // <li>Otherwise, return {@link ATN//INVALID_ALT_NUMBER}.</li>
8135 // </ul>
8136 //
8137 // <p>
8138 // In some scenarios, the algorithm described above could predict an
8139 // alternative which will result in a {@link FailedPredicateException} in
8140 // the parser. Specifically, this could occur if the <em>only</em> configuration
8141 // capable of successfully parsing to the end of the decision rule is
8142 // blocked by a semantic predicate. By choosing this alternative within
8143 // {@link //adaptivePredict} instead of throwing a
8144 // {@link NoViableAltException}, the resulting
8145 // {@link FailedPredicateException} in the parser will identify the specific
8146 // predicate which is preventing the parser from successfully parsing the
8147 // decision rule, which helps developers identify and correct logic errors
8148 // in semantic predicates.
8149 // </p>
8150 //
8151 // @param configs The ATN configurations which were valid immediately before
8152 // the {@link //ERROR} state was reached
8153 // @param outerContext The is the \gamma_0 initial parser context from the paper
8154 // or the parser stack at the instant before prediction commences.
8155 //
8156 // @return The value to return from {@link //adaptivePredict}, or
8157 // {@link ATN//INVALID_ALT_NUMBER} if a suitable alternative was not
8158 // identified and {@link //adaptivePredict} should report an error instead.
8159 //
8160 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getSynValidOrSemInvalidAltThatFinishedDecisionEntryRule = function(configs, outerContext) {
8161     var cfgs = this.splitAccordingToSemanticValidity(configs, outerContext);
8162     var semValidConfigs = cfgs[0];
8163     var semInvalidConfigs = cfgs[1];
8164     var alt = this.getAltThatFinishedDecisionEntryRule(semValidConfigs);
8165     if (alt!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) { // semantically/syntactically viable path exists
8166         return alt;
8167     }
8168     // Is there a syntactically valid path with a failed pred?
8169     if (semInvalidConfigs.items.length>0) {
8170         alt = this.getAltThatFinishedDecisionEntryRule(semInvalidConfigs);
8171         if (alt!==ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) { // syntactically viable path exists
8172             return alt;
8173         }
8174     }
8175     return ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
8176 };
8177 
8178 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getAltThatFinishedDecisionEntryRule = function(configs) {
8179     var alts = [];
8180     for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length; i++) {
8181         var c = configs.items[i];
8182         if (c.reachesIntoOuterContext>0 || ((c.state instanceof RuleStopState) && c.context.hasEmptyPath())) {
8183             if(alts.indexOf(c.alt)<0) {
8184                 alts.push(c.alt);
8185             }
8186         }
8187     }
8188     if (alts.length===0) {
8189         return ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
8190     } else {
8191         return Math.min.apply(null, alts);
8192     }
8193 };
8194 // Walk the list of configurations and split them according to
8195 //  those that have preds evaluating to true/false.  If no pred, assume
8196 //  true pred and include in succeeded set.  Returns Pair of sets.
8197 //
8198 //  Create a new set so as not to alter the incoming parameter.
8199 //
8200 //  Assumption: the input stream has been restored to the starting point
8201 //  prediction, which is where predicates need to evaluate.
8202 //
8203 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.splitAccordingToSemanticValidity = function( configs, outerContext) {
8204     var succeeded = new ATNConfigSet(configs.fullCtx);
8205     var failed = new ATNConfigSet(configs.fullCtx);
8206     for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length; i++) {
8207         var c = configs.items[i];
8208         if (c.semanticContext !== SemanticContext.NONE) {
8209             var predicateEvaluationResult = c.semanticContext.evaluate(this.parser, outerContext);
8210             if (predicateEvaluationResult) {
8211                 succeeded.add(c);
8212             } else {
8213                 failed.add(c);
8214             }
8215         } else {
8216             succeeded.add(c);
8217         }
8218     }
8219     return [succeeded, failed];
8220 };
8221 
8222 // Look through a list of predicate/alt pairs, returning alts for the
8223 //  pairs that win. A {@code NONE} predicate indicates an alt containing an
8224 //  unpredicated config which behaves as "always true." If !complete
8225 //  then we stop at the first predicate that evaluates to true. This
8226 //  includes pairs with null predicates.
8227 //
8228 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.evalSemanticContext = function(predPredictions, outerContext, complete) {
8229     var predictions = new BitSet();
8230     for(var i=0;i<predPredictions.length;i++) {
8231     	var pair = predPredictions[i];
8232         if (pair.pred === SemanticContext.NONE) {
8233             predictions.add(pair.alt);
8234             if (! complete) {
8235                 break;
8236             }
8237             continue;
8238         }
8239         var predicateEvaluationResult = pair.pred.evaluate(this.parser, outerContext);
8240         if (this.debug || this.dfa_debug) {
8241             console.log("eval pred " + pair + "=" + predicateEvaluationResult);
8242         }
8243         if (predicateEvaluationResult) {
8244             if (this.debug || this.dfa_debug) {
8245                 console.log("PREDICT " + pair.alt);
8246             }
8247             predictions.add(pair.alt);
8248             if (! complete) {
8249                 break;
8250             }
8251         }
8252     }
8253     return predictions;
8254 };
8255 
8256 // TODO: If we are doing predicates, there is no point in pursuing
8257 //     closure operations if we reach a DFA state that uniquely predicts
8258 //     alternative. We will not be caching that DFA state and it is a
8259 //     waste to pursue the closure. Might have to advance when we do
8260 //     ambig detection thought :(
8261 //
8262 
8263 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.closure = function(config, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates, fullCtx, treatEofAsEpsilon) {
8264     var initialDepth = 0;
8265     this.closureCheckingStopState(config, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates,
8266                              fullCtx, initialDepth, treatEofAsEpsilon);
8267 };
8268 
8269 
8270 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.closureCheckingStopState = function(config, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates, fullCtx, depth, treatEofAsEpsilon) {
8271     if (this.debug || this.debug_closure) {
8272         console.log("closure(" + config.toString(this.parser,true) + ")");
8273         // console.log("configs(" + configs.toString() + ")");
8274         if(config.reachesIntoOuterContext>50) {
8275             throw "problem";
8276         }
8277     }
8278     if (config.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
8279         // We hit rule end. If we have context info, use it
8280         // run thru all possible stack tops in ctx
8281         if (! config.context.isEmpty()) {
8282             for ( var i =0; i<config.context.length; i++) {
8283                 if (config.context.getReturnState(i) === PredictionContext.EMPTY_RETURN_STATE) {
8284                     if (fullCtx) {
8285                         configs.add(new ATNConfig({state:config.state, context:PredictionContext.EMPTY}, config), this.mergeCache);
8286                         continue;
8287                     } else {
8288                         // we have no context info, just chase follow links (if greedy)
8289                         if (this.debug) {
8290                             console.log("FALLING off rule " + this.getRuleName(config.state.ruleIndex));
8291                         }
8292                         this.closure_(config, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates,
8293                                  fullCtx, depth, treatEofAsEpsilon);
8294                     }
8295                     continue;
8296                 }
8297                 var returnState = this.atn.states[config.context.getReturnState(i)];
8298                 var newContext = config.context.getParent(i); // "pop" return state
8299                 var parms = {state:returnState, alt:config.alt, context:newContext, semanticContext:config.semanticContext};
8300                 var c = new ATNConfig(parms, null);
8301                 // While we have context to pop back from, we may have
8302                 // gotten that context AFTER having falling off a rule.
8303                 // Make sure we track that we are now out of context.
8304                 c.reachesIntoOuterContext = config.reachesIntoOuterContext;
8305                 this.closureCheckingStopState(c, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates, fullCtx, depth - 1, treatEofAsEpsilon);
8306             }
8307             return;
8308         } else if( fullCtx) {
8309             // reached end of start rule
8310             configs.add(config, this.mergeCache);
8311             return;
8312         } else {
8313             // else if we have no context info, just chase follow links (if greedy)
8314             if (this.debug) {
8315                 console.log("FALLING off rule " + this.getRuleName(config.state.ruleIndex));
8316             }
8317         }
8318     }
8319     this.closure_(config, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates, fullCtx, depth, treatEofAsEpsilon);
8320 };
8321 
8322 
8323 // Do the actual work of walking epsilon edges//
8324 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.closure_ = function(config, configs, closureBusy, collectPredicates, fullCtx, depth, treatEofAsEpsilon) {
8325     var p = config.state;
8326     // optimization
8327     if (! p.epsilonOnlyTransitions) {
8328         configs.add(config, this.mergeCache);
8329         // make sure to not return here, because EOF transitions can act as
8330         // both epsilon transitions and non-epsilon transitions.
8331     }
8332     for(var i = 0;i<p.transitions.length; i++) {
8333         if(i==0 && this.canDropLoopEntryEdgeInLeftRecursiveRule(config))
8334             continue;
8335 
8336         var t = p.transitions[i];
8337         var continueCollecting = collectPredicates && !(t instanceof ActionTransition);
8338         var c = this.getEpsilonTarget(config, t, continueCollecting, depth === 0, fullCtx, treatEofAsEpsilon);
8339         if (c!==null) {
8340 			if (!t.isEpsilon && closureBusy.add(c)!==c){
8341 				// avoid infinite recursion for EOF* and EOF+
8342 				continue;
8343 			}
8344             var newDepth = depth;
8345             if ( config.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
8346                 // target fell off end of rule; mark resulting c as having dipped into outer context
8347                 // We can't get here if incoming config was rule stop and we had context
8348                 // track how far we dip into outer context.  Might
8349                 // come in handy and we avoid evaluating context dependent
8350                 // preds if this is > 0.
8351 
8352                 if (closureBusy.add(c)!==c) {
8353                     // avoid infinite recursion for right-recursive rules
8354                     continue;
8355                 }
8356 
8357 				if (this._dfa !== null && this._dfa.precedenceDfa) {
8358 					if (t.outermostPrecedenceReturn === this._dfa.atnStartState.ruleIndex) {
8359 						c.precedenceFilterSuppressed = true;
8360 					}
8361 				}
8362 
8363                 c.reachesIntoOuterContext += 1;
8364                 configs.dipsIntoOuterContext = true; // TODO: can remove? only care when we add to set per middle of this method
8365                 newDepth -= 1;
8366                 if (this.debug) {
8367                     console.log("dips into outer ctx: " + c);
8368                 }
8369             } else if (t instanceof RuleTransition) {
8370                 // latch when newDepth goes negative - once we step out of the entry context we can't return
8371                 if (newDepth >= 0) {
8372                     newDepth += 1;
8373                 }
8374             }
8375             this.closureCheckingStopState(c, configs, closureBusy, continueCollecting, fullCtx, newDepth, treatEofAsEpsilon);
8376         }
8377     }
8378 };
8379 
8380 
8381 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.canDropLoopEntryEdgeInLeftRecursiveRule = function(config) {
8382     // return False
8383     var p = config.state;
8384     // First check to see if we are in StarLoopEntryState generated during
8385     // left-recursion elimination. For efficiency, also check if
8386     // the context has an empty stack case. If so, it would mean
8387     // global FOLLOW so we can't perform optimization
8388     // Are we the special loop entry/exit state? or SLL wildcard
8389     if(p.stateType != ATNState.STAR_LOOP_ENTRY)
8390         return false;
8391     if(p.stateType != ATNState.STAR_LOOP_ENTRY || !p.isPrecedenceDecision ||
8392            config.context.isEmpty() || config.context.hasEmptyPath())
8393         return false;
8394 
8395     // Require all return states to return back to the same rule that p is in.
8396     var numCtxs = config.context.length;
8397     for(var i=0; i<numCtxs; i++) { // for each stack context
8398         var returnState = this.atn.states[config.context.getReturnState(i)];
8399         if (returnState.ruleIndex != p.ruleIndex)
8400             return false;
8401     }
8402 
8403     var decisionStartState = p.transitions[0].target;
8404     var blockEndStateNum = decisionStartState.endState.stateNumber;
8405     var blockEndState = this.atn.states[blockEndStateNum];
8406 
8407     // Verify that the top of each stack context leads to loop entry/exit
8408     // state through epsilon edges and w/o leaving rule.
8409     for(var i=0; i<numCtxs; i++) { // for each stack context
8410         var returnStateNumber = config.context.getReturnState(i);
8411         var returnState = this.atn.states[returnStateNumber];
8412         // all states must have single outgoing epsilon edge
8413         if (returnState.transitions.length != 1 || !returnState.transitions[0].isEpsilon)
8414             return false;
8415 
8416         // Look for prefix op case like 'not expr', (' type ')' expr
8417         var returnStateTarget = returnState.transitions[0].target;
8418         if ( returnState.stateType == ATNState.BLOCK_END && returnStateTarget == p )
8419             continue;
8420 
8421         // Look for 'expr op expr' or case where expr's return state is block end
8422         // of (...)* internal block; the block end points to loop back
8423         // which points to p but we don't need to check that
8424         if ( returnState == blockEndState )
8425             continue;
8426 
8427         // Look for ternary expr ? expr : expr. The return state points at block end,
8428         // which points at loop entry state
8429         if ( returnStateTarget == blockEndState )
8430             continue;
8431 
8432         // Look for complex prefix 'between expr and expr' case where 2nd expr's
8433         // return state points at block end state of (...)* internal block
8434         if (returnStateTarget.stateType == ATNState.BLOCK_END && returnStateTarget.transitions.length == 1
8435                 && returnStateTarget.transitions[0].isEpsilon && returnStateTarget.transitions[0].target == p)
8436             continue;
8437 
8438         // anything else ain't conforming
8439         return false;
8440     }
8441     return true;
8442 };

8445 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getRuleName = function( index) {
8446     if (this.parser!==null && index>=0) {
8447         return this.parser.ruleNames[index];
8448     } else {
8449         return "<rule " + index + ">";
8450     }
8451 };

8453 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getEpsilonTarget = function(config, t, collectPredicates, inContext, fullCtx, treatEofAsEpsilon) {
8454     switch(t.serializationType) {
8455     case Transition.RULE:
8456         return this.ruleTransition(config, t);
8457     case Transition.PRECEDENCE:
8458         return this.precedenceTransition(config, t, collectPredicates, inContext, fullCtx);
8459     case Transition.PREDICATE:
8460         return this.predTransition(config, t, collectPredicates, inContext, fullCtx);
8461     case Transition.ACTION:
8462         return this.actionTransition(config, t);
8463     case Transition.EPSILON:
8464         return new ATNConfig({state:t.target}, config);
8465     case Transition.ATOM:
8466     case Transition.RANGE:
8467     case Transition.SET:
8468         // EOF transitions act like epsilon transitions after the first EOF
8469         // transition is traversed
8470         if (treatEofAsEpsilon) {
8471             if (t.matches(Token.EOF, 0, 1)) {
8472                 return new ATNConfig({state: t.target}, config);
8473             }
8474         }
8475         return null;
8476     default:
8477     	return null;
8478     }
8479 };

8481 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.actionTransition = function(config, t) {
8482     if (this.debug) {
8483         var index = t.actionIndex==-1 ? 65535 : t.actionIndex;
8484         console.log("ACTION edge " + t.ruleIndex + ":" + index);
8485     }
8486     return new ATNConfig({state:t.target}, config);
8487 };

8489 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.precedenceTransition = function(config, pt,  collectPredicates, inContext, fullCtx) {
8490     if (this.debug) {
8491         console.log("PRED (collectPredicates=" + collectPredicates + ") " +
8492                 pt.precedence + ">=_p, ctx dependent=true");
8493         if (this.parser!==null) {
8494         	console.log("context surrounding pred is " + Utils.arrayToString(this.parser.getRuleInvocationStack()));
8495         }
8496     }
8497     var c = null;
8498     if (collectPredicates && inContext) {
8499         if (fullCtx) {
8500             // In full context mode, we can evaluate predicates on-the-fly
8501             // during closure, which dramatically reduces the size of
8502             // the config sets. It also obviates the need to test predicates
8503             // later during conflict resolution.
8504             var currentPosition = this._input.index;
8505             this._input.seek(this._startIndex);
8506             var predSucceeds = pt.getPredicate().evaluate(this.parser, this._outerContext);
8507             this._input.seek(currentPosition);
8508             if (predSucceeds) {
8509                 c = new ATNConfig({state:pt.target}, config); // no pred context
8510             }
8511         } else {
8512             var newSemCtx = SemanticContext.andContext(config.semanticContext, pt.getPredicate());
8513             c = new ATNConfig({state:pt.target, semanticContext:newSemCtx}, config);
8514         }
8515     } else {
8516         c = new ATNConfig({state:pt.target}, config);
8517     }
8518     if (this.debug) {
8519         console.log("config from pred transition=" + c);
8520     }
8521     return c;
8522 };

8524 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.predTransition = function(config, pt, collectPredicates, inContext, fullCtx) {
8525     if (this.debug) {
8526         console.log("PRED (collectPredicates=" + collectPredicates + ") " + pt.ruleIndex +
8527                 ":" + pt.predIndex + ", ctx dependent=" + pt.isCtxDependent);
8528         if (this.parser!==null) {
8529             console.log("context surrounding pred is " + Utils.arrayToString(this.parser.getRuleInvocationStack()));
8530         }
8531     }
8532     var c = null;
8533     if (collectPredicates && ((pt.isCtxDependent && inContext) || ! pt.isCtxDependent)) {
8534         if (fullCtx) {
8535             // In full context mode, we can evaluate predicates on-the-fly
8536             // during closure, which dramatically reduces the size of
8537             // the config sets. It also obviates the need to test predicates
8538             // later during conflict resolution.
8539             var currentPosition = this._input.index;
8540             this._input.seek(this._startIndex);
8541             var predSucceeds = pt.getPredicate().evaluate(this.parser, this._outerContext);
8542             this._input.seek(currentPosition);
8543             if (predSucceeds) {
8544                 c = new ATNConfig({state:pt.target}, config); // no pred context
8545             }
8546         } else {
8547             var newSemCtx = SemanticContext.andContext(config.semanticContext, pt.getPredicate());
8548             c = new ATNConfig({state:pt.target, semanticContext:newSemCtx}, config);
8549         }
8550     } else {
8551         c = new ATNConfig({state:pt.target}, config);
8552     }
8553     if (this.debug) {
8554         console.log("config from pred transition=" + c);
8555     }
8556     return c;
8557 };

8559 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.ruleTransition = function(config, t) {
8560     if (this.debug) {
8561         console.log("CALL rule " + this.getRuleName(t.target.ruleIndex) + ", ctx=" + config.context);
8562     }
8563     var returnState = t.followState;
8564     var newContext = SingletonPredictionContext.create(config.context, returnState.stateNumber);
8565     return new ATNConfig({state:t.target, context:newContext}, config );
8566 };

8568 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getConflictingAlts = function(configs) {
8569     var altsets = PredictionMode.getConflictingAltSubsets(configs);
8570     return PredictionMode.getAlts(altsets);

8572 
8573  // Sam pointed out a problem with the previous definition, v3, of
8574  // ambiguous states. If we have another state associated with conflicting
8575  // alternatives, we should keep going. For example, the following grammar
8576  //
8577  // s : (ID | ID ID?) ';' ;
8578  //
8579  // When the ATN simulation reaches the state before ';', it has a DFA
8580  // state that looks like: [12|1|[], 6|2|[], 12|2|[]]. Naturally
8581  // 12|1|[] and 12|2|[] conflict, but we cannot stop processing this node
8582  // because alternative to has another way to continue, via [6|2|[]].
8583  // The key is that we have a single state that has config's only associated
8584  // with a single alternative, 2, and crucially the state transitions
8585  // among the configurations are all non-epsilon transitions. That means
8586  // we don't consider any conflicts that include alternative 2. So, we
8587  // ignore the conflict between alts 1 and 2. We ignore a set of
8588  // conflicting alts when there is an intersection with an alternative
8589  // associated with a single alt state in the state&rarr;config-list map.
8590  //
8591  // It's also the case that we might have two conflicting configurations but
8592  // also a 3rd nonconflicting configuration for a different alternative:
8593  // [1|1|[], 1|2|[], 8|3|[]]. This can come about from grammar:
8594  //
8595  // a : A | A | A B ;
8596  //
8597  // After matching input A, we reach the stop state for rule A, state 1.
8598  // State 8 is the state right before B. Clearly alternatives 1 and 2
8599  // conflict and no amount of further lookahead will separate the two.
8600  // However, alternative 3 will be able to continue and so we do not
8601  // stop working on this state. In the previous example, we're concerned
8602  // with states associated with the conflicting alternatives. Here alt
8603  // 3 is not associated with the conflicting configs, but since we can continue
8604  // looking for input reasonably, I don't declare the state done. We
8605  // ignore a set of conflicting alts when we have an alternative
8606  // that we still need to pursue.
8607 //
8608 
8609 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getConflictingAltsOrUniqueAlt = function(configs) {
8610     var conflictingAlts = null;
8611     if (configs.uniqueAlt!== ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
8612         conflictingAlts = new BitSet();
8613         conflictingAlts.add(configs.uniqueAlt);
8614     } else {
8615         conflictingAlts = configs.conflictingAlts;
8616     }
8617     return conflictingAlts;
8618 };

8620 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getTokenName = function( t) {
8621     if (t===Token.EOF) {
8622         return "EOF";
8623     }
8624     if( this.parser!==null && this.parser.literalNames!==null) {
8625         if (t >= this.parser.literalNames.length && t >= this.parser.symbolicNames.length) {
8626             console.log("" + t + " ttype out of range: " + this.parser.literalNames);
8627             console.log("" + this.parser.getInputStream().getTokens());
8628         } else {
8629             var name = this.parser.literalNames[t] || this.parser.symbolicNames[t];
8630             return name + "<" + t + ">";
8631         }
8632     }
8633     return "" + t;
8634 };

8644 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.dumpDeadEndConfigs = function(nvae) {
8645     console.log("dead end configs: ");
8646     var decs = nvae.getDeadEndConfigs();
8647     for(var i=0; i<decs.length; i++) {
8648     	var c = decs[i];
8649         var trans = "no edges";
8650         if (c.state.transitions.length>0) {
8651             var t = c.state.transitions[0];
8652             if (t instanceof AtomTransition) {
8653                 trans = "Atom "+ this.getTokenName(t.label);
8654             } else if (t instanceof SetTransition) {
8655                 var neg = (t instanceof NotSetTransition);
8656                 trans = (neg ? "~" : "") + "Set " + t.set;
8657             }
8658         }
8659         console.error(c.toString(this.parser, true) + ":" + trans);
8660     }
8661 };

8667 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.getUniqueAlt = function(configs) {
8668     var alt = ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
8669     for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length;i++) {
8670     	var c = configs.items[i];
8671         if (alt === ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER) {
8672             alt = c.alt // found first alt
8673         } else if( c.alt!==alt) {
8674             return ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
8675         }
8676     }
8677     return alt;
8678 };

8680 //
8681 // Add an edge to the DFA, if possible. This method calls
8682 // {@link //addDFAState} to ensure the {@code to} state is present in the
8683 // DFA. If {@code from} is {@code null}, or if {@code t} is outside the
8684 // range of edges that can be represented in the DFA tables, this method
8685 // returns without adding the edge to the DFA.
8686 //
8687 // <p>If {@code to} is {@code null}, this method returns {@code null}.
8688 // Otherwise, this method returns the {@link DFAState} returned by calling
8689 // {@link //addDFAState} for the {@code to} state.</p>
8690 //
8691 // @param dfa The DFA
8692 // @param from The source state for the edge
8693 // @param t The input symbol
8694 // @param to The target state for the edge
8695 //
8696 // @return If {@code to} is {@code null}, this method returns {@code null};
8697 // otherwise this method returns the result of calling {@link //addDFAState}
8698 // on {@code to}
8699 //
8700 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.addDFAEdge = function(dfa, from_, t, to) {
8701     if( this.debug) {
8702         console.log("EDGE " + from_ + " -> " + to + " upon " + this.getTokenName(t));
8703     }
8704     if (to===null) {
8705         return null;
8706     }
8707     to = this.addDFAState(dfa, to); // used existing if possible not incoming
8708     if (from_===null || t < -1 || t > this.atn.maxTokenType) {
8709         return to;
8710     }
8711     if (from_.edges===null) {
8712         from_.edges = [];
8713     }
8714     from_.edges[t+1] = to; // connect
8715 
8716     if (this.debug) {
8717         var literalNames = this.parser===null ? null : this.parser.literalNames;
8718         var symbolicNames = this.parser===null ? null : this.parser.symbolicNames;
8719         console.log("DFA=\n" + dfa.toString(literalNames, symbolicNames));
8720     }
8721     return to;
8722 };
8723 //
8724 // Add state {@code D} to the DFA if it is not already present, and return
8725 // the actual instance stored in the DFA. If a state equivalent to {@code D}
8726 // is already in the DFA, the existing state is returned. Otherwise this
8727 // method returns {@code D} after adding it to the DFA.
8728 //
8729 // <p>If {@code D} is {@link //ERROR}, this method returns {@link //ERROR} and
8730 // does not change the DFA.</p>
8731 //
8732 // @param dfa The dfa
8733 // @param D The DFA state to add
8734 // @return The state stored in the DFA. This will be either the existing
8735 // state if {@code D} is already in the DFA, or {@code D} itself if the
8736 // state was not already present.
8737 //
8738 ParserATNSimulator.prototype.addDFAState = function(dfa, D) {
8739     if (D == ATNSimulator.ERROR) {
8740         return D;
8741     }
8742     var existing = dfa.states.get(D);
8743     if(existing!==null) {
8744         return existing;
8745     }
8746     D.stateNumber = dfa.states.length;
8747     if (! D.configs.readOnly) {
8748         D.configs.optimizeConfigs(this);
8749         D.configs.setReadonly(true);
8750     }
8751     dfa.states.add(D);
8752     if (this.debug) {
8753         console.log("adding new DFA state: " + D);
8754     }
8755     return D;
8756 };

8766     }

8802 // This enumeration defines the prediction modes available in ANTLR 4 along with
8803 // utility methods for analyzing configuration sets for conflicts and/or
8804 // ambiguities.

8819 function PredictionMode() {
8820 	return this;
