8822 
8823 //
8824 // The SLL(*) prediction mode. This prediction mode ignores the current
8825 // parser context when making predictions. This is the fastest prediction
8826 // mode, and provides correct results for many grammars. This prediction
8827 // mode is more powerful than the prediction mode provided by ANTLR 3, but
8828 // may result in syntax errors for grammar and input combinations which are
8829 // not SLL.
8830 //
8831 // <p>
8832 // When using this prediction mode, the parser will either return a correct
8833 // parse tree (i.e. the same parse tree that would be returned with the
8834 // {@link //LL} prediction mode), or it will report a syntax error. If a
8835 // syntax error is encountered when using the {@link //SLL} prediction mode,
8836 // it may be due to either an actual syntax error in the input or indicate
8837 // that the particular combination of grammar and input requires the more
8838 // powerful {@link //LL} prediction abilities to complete successfully.</p>
8839 //
8840 // <p>
8841 // This prediction mode does not provide any guarantees for prediction
8842 // behavior for syntactically-incorrect inputs.</p>
8843 //
8844 PredictionMode.SLL = 0;
8845 //
8846 // The LL(*) prediction mode. This prediction mode allows the current parser
8847 // context to be used for resolving SLL conflicts that occur during
8848 // prediction. This is the fastest prediction mode that guarantees correct
8849 // parse results for all combinations of grammars with syntactically correct
8850 // inputs.
8851 //
8852 // <p>
8853 // When using this prediction mode, the parser will make correct decisions
8854 // for all syntactically-correct grammar and input combinations. However, in
8855 // cases where the grammar is truly ambiguous this prediction mode might not
8856 // report a precise answer for <em>exactly which</em> alternatives are
8857 // ambiguous.</p>
8858 //
8859 // <p>
8860 // This prediction mode does not provide any guarantees for prediction
8861 // behavior for syntactically-incorrect inputs.</p>
8862 //
8863 PredictionMode.LL = 1;
8864 //
8865 // The LL(*) prediction mode with exact ambiguity detection. In addition to
8866 // the correctness guarantees provided by the {@link //LL} prediction mode,
8867 // this prediction mode instructs the prediction algorithm to determine the
8868 // complete and exact set of ambiguous alternatives for every ambiguous
8869 // decision encountered while parsing.
8870 //
8871 // <p>
8872 // This prediction mode may be used for diagnosing ambiguities during
8873 // grammar development. Due to the performance overhead of calculating sets
8874 // of ambiguous alternatives, this prediction mode should be avoided when
8875 // the exact results are not necessary.</p>
8876 //
8877 // <p>
8878 // This prediction mode does not provide any guarantees for prediction
8879 // behavior for syntactically-incorrect inputs.</p>
8880 //
8881 PredictionMode.LL_EXACT_AMBIG_DETECTION = 2;
8882 
8883 
8884 //
8885 // Computes the SLL prediction termination condition.
8886 //
8887 // <p>
8888 // This method computes the SLL prediction termination condition for both of
8889 // the following cases.</p>
8890 //
8891 // <ul>
8892 // <li>The usual SLL+LL fallback upon SLL conflict</li>
8893 // <li>Pure SLL without LL fallback</li>
8894 // </ul>
8895 //
8896 // <p><strong>COMBINED SLL+LL PARSING</strong></p>
8897 //
8898 // <p>When LL-fallback is enabled upon SLL conflict, correct predictions are
8899 // ensured regardless of how the termination condition is computed by this
8900 // method. Due to the substantially higher cost of LL prediction, the
8901 // prediction should only fall back to LL when the additional lookahead
8902 // cannot lead to a unique SLL prediction.</p>
8903 //
8904 // <p>Assuming combined SLL+LL parsing, an SLL configuration set with only
8905 // conflicting subsets should fall back to full LL, even if the
8906 // configuration sets don't resolve to the same alternative (e.g.
8907 // {@code {1,2}} and {@code {3,4}}. If there is at least one non-conflicting
8908 // configuration, SLL could continue with the hopes that more lookahead will
8909 // resolve via one of those non-conflicting configurations.</p>
8910 //
8911 // <p>Here's the prediction termination rule them: SLL (for SLL+LL parsing)
8912 // stops when it sees only conflicting configuration subsets. In contrast,
8913 // full LL keeps going when there is uncertainty.</p>
8914 //
8915 // <p><strong>HEURISTIC</strong></p>
8916 //
8917 // <p>As a heuristic, we stop prediction when we see any conflicting subset
8918 // unless we see a state that only has one alternative associated with it.
8919 // The single-alt-state thing lets prediction continue upon rules like
8920 // (otherwise, it would admit defeat too soon):</p>
8921 //
8922 // <p>{@code [12|1|[], 6|2|[], 12|2|[]]. s : (ID | ID ID?) ';' ;}</p>
8923 //
8924 // <p>When the ATN simulation reaches the state before {@code ';'}, it has a
8925 // DFA state that looks like: {@code [12|1|[], 6|2|[], 12|2|[]]}. Naturally
8926 // {@code 12|1|[]} and {@code 12|2|[]} conflict, but we cannot stop
8927 // processing this node because alternative to has another way to continue,
8928 // via {@code [6|2|[]]}.</p>
8929 //
8930 // <p>It also let's us continue for this rule:</p>
8931 //
8932 // <p>{@code [1|1|[], 1|2|[], 8|3|[]] a : A | A | A B ;}</p>
8933 //
8934 // <p>After matching input A, we reach the stop state for rule A, state 1.
8935 // State 8 is the state right before B. Clearly alternatives 1 and 2
8936 // conflict and no amount of further lookahead will separate the two.
8937 // However, alternative 3 will be able to continue and so we do not stop
8938 // working on this state. In the previous example, we're concerned with
8939 // states associated with the conflicting alternatives. Here alt 3 is not
8940 // associated with the conflicting configs, but since we can continue
8941 // looking for input reasonably, don't declare the state done.</p>
8942 //
8943 // <p><strong>PURE SLL PARSING</strong></p>
8944 //
8945 // <p>To handle pure SLL parsing, all we have to do is make sure that we
8946 // combine stack contexts for configurations that differ only by semantic
8947 // predicate. From there, we can do the usual SLL termination heuristic.</p>
8948 //
8949 // <p><strong>PREDICATES IN SLL+LL PARSING</strong></p>
8950 //
8951 // <p>SLL decisions don't evaluate predicates until after they reach DFA stop
8952 // states because they need to create the DFA cache that works in all
8953 // semantic situations. In contrast, full LL evaluates predicates collected
8954 // during start state computation so it can ignore predicates thereafter.
8955 // This means that SLL termination detection can totally ignore semantic
8956 // predicates.</p>
8957 //
8958 // <p>Implementation-wise, {@link ATNConfigSet} combines stack contexts but not
8959 // semantic predicate contexts so we might see two configurations like the
8960 // following.</p>
8961 //
8962 // <p>{@code (s, 1, x, {}), (s, 1, x', {p})}</p>
8963 //
8964 // <p>Before testing these configurations against others, we have to merge
8965 // {@code x} and {@code x'} (without modifying the existing configurations).
8966 // For example, we test {@code (x+x')==x''} when looking for conflicts in
8967 // the following configurations.</p>
8968 //
8969 // <p>{@code (s, 1, x, {}), (s, 1, x', {p}), (s, 2, x'', {})}</p>
8970 //
8971 // <p>If the configuration set has predicates (as indicated by
8972 // {@link ATNConfigSet//hasSemanticContext}), this algorithm makes a copy of
8973 // the configurations to strip out all of the predicates so that a standard
8974 // {@link ATNConfigSet} will merge everything ignoring predicates.</p>
8975 //
8976 PredictionMode.hasSLLConflictTerminatingPrediction = function( mode, configs) {
8977     // Configs in rule stop states indicate reaching the end of the decision
8978     // rule (local context) or end of start rule (full context). If all
8979     // configs meet this condition, then none of the configurations is able
8980     // to match additional input so we terminate prediction.
8981     //
8982     if (PredictionMode.allConfigsInRuleStopStates(configs)) {
8983         return true;
8984     }
8985     // pure SLL mode parsing
8986     if (mode === PredictionMode.SLL) {
8987         // Don't bother with combining configs from different semantic
8988         // contexts if we can fail over to full LL; costs more time
8989         // since we'll often fail over anyway.
8990         if (configs.hasSemanticContext) {
8991             // dup configs, tossing out semantic predicates
8992             var dup = new ATNConfigSet();
8993             for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length;i++) {
8994             	var c = configs.items[i];
8995                 c = new ATNConfig({semanticContext:SemanticContext.NONE}, c);
8996                 dup.add(c);
8997             }
8998             configs = dup;
8999         }
9000         // now we have combined contexts for configs with dissimilar preds
9001     }
9002     // pure SLL or combined SLL+LL mode parsing
9003     var altsets = PredictionMode.getConflictingAltSubsets(configs);
9004     return PredictionMode.hasConflictingAltSet(altsets) && !PredictionMode.hasStateAssociatedWithOneAlt(configs);
9005 };
9006 
9007 // Checks if any configuration in {@code configs} is in a
9008 // {@link RuleStopState}. Configurations meeting this condition have reached
9009 // the end of the decision rule (local context) or end of start rule (full
9010 // context).
9011 //
9012 // @param configs the configuration set to test
9013 // @return {@code true} if any configuration in {@code configs} is in a
9014 // {@link RuleStopState}, otherwise {@code false}
9015 PredictionMode.hasConfigInRuleStopState = function(configs) {
9016 	for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length;i++) {
9017 		var c = configs.items[i];
9018         if (c.state instanceof RuleStopState) {
9019             return true;
9020         }
9021 	}
9022     return false;
9023 };
9024 
9025 // Checks if all configurations in {@code configs} are in a
9026 // {@link RuleStopState}. Configurations meeting this condition have reached
9027 // the end of the decision rule (local context) or end of start rule (full
9028 // context).
9029 //
9030 // @param configs the configuration set to test
9031 // @return {@code true} if all configurations in {@code configs} are in a
9032 // {@link RuleStopState}, otherwise {@code false}
9033 PredictionMode.allConfigsInRuleStopStates = function(configs) {
9034 	for(var i=0;i<configs.items.length;i++) {
9035 		var c = configs.items[i];
9036         if (!(c.state instanceof RuleStopState)) {
9037             return false;
9038         }
9039 	}
9040     return true;
9041 };
9042 
9043 //
9044 // Full LL prediction termination.
9045 //
9046 // <p>Can we stop looking ahead during ATN simulation or is there some
9047 // uncertainty as to which alternative we will ultimately pick, after
9048 // consuming more input? Even if there are partial conflicts, we might know
9049 // that everything is going to resolve to the same minimum alternative. That
9050 // means we can stop since no more lookahead will change that fact. On the
9051 // other hand, there might be multiple conflicts that resolve to different
9052 // minimums. That means we need more look ahead to decide which of those
9053 // alternatives we should predict.</p>
9054 //
9055 // <p>The basic idea is to split the set of configurations {@code C}, into
9056 // conflicting subsets {@code (s, _, ctx, _)} and singleton subsets with
9057 // non-conflicting configurations. Two configurations conflict if they have
9058 // identical {@link ATNConfig//state} and {@link ATNConfig//context} values
9059 // but different {@link ATNConfig//alt} value, e.g. {@code (s, i, ctx, _)}
9060 // and {@code (s, j, ctx, _)} for {@code i!=j}.</p>
9061 //
9062 // <p>Reduce these configuration subsets to the set of possible alternatives.
9063 // You can compute the alternative subsets in one pass as follows:</p>
9064 //
9065 // <p>{@code A_s,ctx = {i | (s, i, ctx, _)}} for each configuration in
9066 // {@code C} holding {@code s} and {@code ctx} fixed.</p>
9067 //
9068 // <p>Or in pseudo-code, for each configuration {@code c} in {@code C}:</p>
9069 //
9070 // <pre>
9071 // map[c] U= c.{@link ATNConfig//alt alt} // map hash/equals uses s and x, not
9072 // alt and not pred
9073 // </pre>
9074 //
9075 // <p>The values in {@code map} are the set of {@code A_s,ctx} sets.</p>
9076 //
9077 // <p>If {@code |A_s,ctx|=1} then there is no conflict associated with
9078 // {@code s} and {@code ctx}.</p>
9079 //
9080 // <p>Reduce the subsets to singletons by choosing a minimum of each subset. If
9081 // the union of these alternative subsets is a singleton, then no amount of
9082 // more lookahead will help us. We will always pick that alternative. If,
9083 // however, there is more than one alternative, then we are uncertain which
9084 // alternative to predict and must continue looking for resolution. We may
9085 // or may not discover an ambiguity in the future, even if there are no
9086 // conflicting subsets this round.</p>
9087 //
9088 // <p>The biggest sin is to terminate early because it means we've made a
9089 // decision but were uncertain as to the eventual outcome. We haven't used
9090 // enough lookahead. On the other hand, announcing a conflict too late is no
9091 // big deal; you will still have the conflict. It's just inefficient. It
9092 // might even look until the end of file.</p>
9093 //
9094 // <p>No special consideration for semantic predicates is required because
9095 // predicates are evaluated on-the-fly for full LL prediction, ensuring that
9096 // no configuration contains a semantic context during the termination
9097 // check.</p>
9098 //
9099 // <p><strong>CONFLICTING CONFIGS</strong></p>
9100 //
9101 // <p>Two configurations {@code (s, i, x)} and {@code (s, j, x')}, conflict
9102 // when {@code i!=j} but {@code x=x'}. Because we merge all
9103 // {@code (s, i, _)} configurations together, that means that there are at
9104 // most {@code n} configurations associated with state {@code s} for
9105 // {@code n} possible alternatives in the decision. The merged stacks
9106 // complicate the comparison of configuration contexts {@code x} and
9107 // {@code x'}. Sam checks to see if one is a subset of the other by calling
9108 // merge and checking to see if the merged result is either {@code x} or
9109 // {@code x'}. If the {@code x} associated with lowest alternative {@code i}
9110 // is the superset, then {@code i} is the only possible prediction since the
9111 // others resolve to {@code min(i)} as well. However, if {@code x} is
9112 // associated with {@code j>i} then at least one stack configuration for
9113 // {@code j} is not in conflict with alternative {@code i}. The algorithm
9114 // should keep going, looking for more lookahead due to the uncertainty.</p>
9115 //
9116 // <p>For simplicity, I'm doing a equality check between {@code x} and
9117 // {@code x'} that lets the algorithm continue to consume lookahead longer
9118 // than necessary. The reason I like the equality is of course the
9119 // simplicity but also because that is the test you need to detect the
9120 // alternatives that are actually in conflict.</p>
9121 //
9122 // <p><strong>CONTINUE/STOP RULE</strong></p>
9123 //
9124 // <p>Continue if union of resolved alternative sets from non-conflicting and
9125 // conflicting alternative subsets has more than one alternative. We are
9126 // uncertain about which alternative to predict.</p>
9127 //
9128 // <p>The complete set of alternatives, {@code [i for (_,i,_)]}, tells us which
9129 // alternatives are still in the running for the amount of input we've
9130 // consumed at this point. The conflicting sets let us to strip away
9131 // configurations that won't lead to more states because we resolve
9132 // conflicts to the configuration with a minimum alternate for the
9133 // conflicting set.</p>
9134 //
9135 // <p><strong>CASES</strong></p>
9136 //
9137 // <ul>
9138 //
9139 // <li>no conflicts and more than 1 alternative in set =&gt; continue</li>
9140 //
9141 // <li> {@code (s, 1, x)}, {@code (s, 2, x)}, {@code (s, 3, z)},
9142 // {@code (s', 1, y)}, {@code (s', 2, y)} yields non-conflicting set
9143 // {@code {3}} U conflicting sets {@code min({1,2})} U {@code min({1,2})} =
9144 // {@code {1,3}} =&gt; continue
9145 // </li>
9146 //
9147 // <li>{@code (s, 1, x)}, {@code (s, 2, x)}, {@code (s', 1, y)},
9148 // {@code (s', 2, y)}, {@code (s'', 1, z)} yields non-conflicting set
9149 // {@code {1}} U conflicting sets {@code min({1,2})} U {@code min({1,2})} =
9150 // {@code {1}} =&gt; stop and predict 1</li>
9151 //
9152 // <li>{@code (s, 1, x)}, {@code (s, 2, x)}, {@code (s', 1, y)},
9153 // {@code (s', 2, y)} yields conflicting, reduced sets {@code {1}} U
9154 // {@code {1}} = {@code {1}} =&gt; stop and predict 1, can announce
9155 // ambiguity {@code {1,2}}</li>
9156 //
9157 // <li>{@code (s, 1, x)}, {@code (s, 2, x)}, {@code (s', 2, y)},
9158 // {@code (s', 3, y)} yields conflicting, reduced sets {@code {1}} U
9159 // {@code {2}} = {@code {1,2}} =&gt; continue</li>
9160 //
9161 // <li>{@code (s, 1, x)}, {@code (s, 2, x)}, {@code (s', 3, y)},
9162 // {@code (s', 4, y)} yields conflicting, reduced sets {@code {1}} U
9163 // {@code {3}} = {@code {1,3}} =&gt; continue</li>
9164 //
9165 // </ul>
9166 //
9167 // <p><strong>EXACT AMBIGUITY DETECTION</strong></p>
9168 //
9169 // <p>If all states report the same conflicting set of alternatives, then we
9170 // know we have the exact ambiguity set.</p>
9171 //
9172 // <p><code>|A_<em>i</em>|&gt;1</code> and
9173 // <code>A_<em>i</em> = A_<em>j</em></code> for all <em>i</em>, <em>j</em>.</p>
9174 //
9175 // <p>In other words, we continue examining lookahead until all {@code A_i}
9176 // have more than one alternative and all {@code A_i} are the same. If
9177 // {@code A={{1,2}, {1,3}}}, then regular LL prediction would terminate
9178 // because the resolved set is {@code {1}}. To determine what the real
9179 // ambiguity is, we have to know whether the ambiguity is between one and
9180 // two or one and three so we keep going. We can only stop prediction when
9181 // we need exact ambiguity detection when the sets look like
9182 // {@code A={{1,2}}} or {@code {{1,2},{1,2}}}, etc...</p>
9183 //
9184 PredictionMode.resolvesToJustOneViableAlt = function(altsets) {
9185     return PredictionMode.getSingleViableAlt(altsets);
9186 };
9187 
9188 //
9189 // Determines if every alternative subset in {@code altsets} contains more
9190 // than one alternative.
9191 //
9192 // @param altsets a collection of alternative subsets
9193 // @return {@code true} if every {@link BitSet} in {@code altsets} has
9194 // {@link BitSet//cardinality cardinality} &gt; 1, otherwise {@code false}
9195 //
9196 PredictionMode.allSubsetsConflict = function(altsets) {
9197     return ! PredictionMode.hasNonConflictingAltSet(altsets);
9198 };
9199 //
9200 // Determines if any single alternative subset in {@code altsets} contains
9201 // exactly one alternative.
9202 //
9203 // @param altsets a collection of alternative subsets
9204 // @return {@code true} if {@code altsets} contains a {@link BitSet} with
9205 // {@link BitSet//cardinality cardinality} 1, otherwise {@code false}
9206 //
9207 PredictionMode.hasNonConflictingAltSet = function(altsets) {
9208 	for(var i=0;i<altsets.length;i++) {
9209 		var alts = altsets[i];
9210         if (alts.length===1) {
9211             return true;
9212         }
9213 	}
9214     return false;
9215 };
9216 
9217 //
9218 // Determines if any single alternative subset in {@code altsets} contains
9219 // more than one alternative.
9220 //
9221 // @param altsets a collection of alternative subsets
9222 // @return {@code true} if {@code altsets} contains a {@link BitSet} with
9223 // {@link BitSet//cardinality cardinality} &gt; 1, otherwise {@code false}
9224 //
9225 PredictionMode.hasConflictingAltSet = function(altsets) {
9226 	for(var i=0;i<altsets.length;i++) {
9227 		var alts = altsets[i];
9228         if (alts.length>1) {
9229             return true;
9230         }
9231 	}
9232     return false;
9233 };
9234 
9235 //
9236 // Determines if every alternative subset in {@code altsets} is equivalent.
9237 //
9238 // @param altsets a collection of alternative subsets
9239 // @return {@code true} if every member of {@code altsets} is equal to the
9240 // others, otherwise {@code false}
9241 //
9242 PredictionMode.allSubsetsEqual = function(altsets) {
9243     var first = null;
9244 	for(var i=0;i<altsets.length;i++) {
9245 		var alts = altsets[i];
9246         if (first === null) {
9247             first = alts;
9248         } else if (alts!==first) {
9249             return false;
9250         }
9251 	}
9252     return true;
9253 };
9254 
9255 //
9256 // Returns the unique alternative predicted by all alternative subsets in
9257 // {@code altsets}. If no such alternative exists, this method returns
9258 // {@link ATN//INVALID_ALT_NUMBER}.
9259 //
9260 // @param altsets a collection of alternative subsets
9261 //
9262 PredictionMode.getUniqueAlt = function(altsets) {
9263     var all = PredictionMode.getAlts(altsets);
9264     if (all.length===1) {
9265         return all.minValue();
9266     } else {
9267         return ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
9268     }
9269 };
9270 
9271 // Gets the complete set of represented alternatives for a collection of
9272 // alternative subsets. This method returns the union of each {@link BitSet}
9273 // in {@code altsets}.
9274 //
9275 // @param altsets a collection of alternative subsets
9276 // @return the set of represented alternatives in {@code altsets}
9277 //
9278 PredictionMode.getAlts = function(altsets) {
9279     var all = new BitSet();
9280     altsets.map( function(alts) { all.or(alts); });
9281     return all;
9282 };

9284 //
9285 // This function gets the conflicting alt subsets from a configuration set.
9286 // For each configuration {@code c} in {@code configs}:
9287 //
9288 // <pre>
9289 // map[c] U= c.{@link ATNConfig//alt alt} // map hash/equals uses s and x, not
9290 // alt and not pred
9291 // </pre>
9292 
9293 PredictionMode.getConflictingAltSubsets = function(configs) {
9294     var configToAlts = new Map();
9295     configToAlts.hashFunction = function(cfg) { hashStuff(cfg.state.stateNumber, cfg.context); };
9296     configToAlts.equalsFunction = function(c1, c2) { return c1.state.stateNumber==c2.state.stateNumber && c1.context.equals(c2.context);}
9297     configs.items.map(function(cfg) {
9298         var alts = configToAlts.get(cfg);
9299         if (alts === null) {
9300             alts = new BitSet();
9301             configToAlts.put(cfg, alts);
9302         }
9303         alts.add(cfg.alt);
9304 	});
9305     return configToAlts.getValues();
9306 };
9307 
9308 //
9309 // Get a map from state to alt subset from a configuration set. For each
9310 // configuration {@code c} in {@code configs}:
9311 //
9312 // <pre>
9313 // map[c.{@link ATNConfig//state state}] U= c.{@link ATNConfig//alt alt}
9314 // </pre>
9315 //
9316 PredictionMode.getStateToAltMap = function(configs) {
9317     var m = new AltDict();
9318     configs.items.map(function(c) {
9319         var alts = m.get(c.state);
9320         if (alts === null) {
9321             alts = new BitSet();
9322             m.put(c.state, alts);
9323         }
9324         alts.add(c.alt);
9325     });
9326     return m;
9327 };
9328 
9329 PredictionMode.hasStateAssociatedWithOneAlt = function(configs) {
9330     var values = PredictionMode.getStateToAltMap(configs).values();
9331     for(var i=0;i<values.length;i++) {
9332         if (values[i].length===1) {
9333             return true;
9334         }
9335     }
9336     return false;
9337 };
9338 
9339 PredictionMode.getSingleViableAlt = function(altsets) {
9340     var result = null;
9341 	for(var i=0;i<altsets.length;i++) {
9342 		var alts = altsets[i];
9343         var minAlt = alts.minValue();
9344         if(result===null) {
9345             result = minAlt;
9346         } else if(result!==minAlt) { // more than 1 viable alt
9347             return ATN.INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
9348         }
9349 	}
9350     return result;
9351 };

9384 // For context independent predicates, we evaluate them without a local
9385 // context (i.e., null context). That way, we can evaluate them without
9386 // having to create proper rule-specific context during prediction (as
9387 // opposed to the parser, which creates them naturally). In a practical
9388 // sense, this avoids a cast exception from RuleContext to myruleContext.

9390 // <p>For context dependent predicates, we must pass in a local context so that
9391 // references such as $arg evaluate properly as _localctx.arg. We only
9392 // capture context dependent predicates in the context in which we begin
9393 // prediction, so we passed in the outer context here in case of context
9394 // dependent predicate evaluation.</p>

9405 // evaluated, which will be one of the following values.
9406 // <ul>
9407 // <li>{@link //NONE}: if the predicate simplifies to {@code true} after
9408 // precedence predicates are evaluated.</li>
9409 // <li>{@code null}: if the predicate simplifies to {@code false} after
9410 // precedence predicates are evaluated.</li>
9411 // <li>{@code this}: if the semantic context is not changed as a result of
9412 // precedence predicate evaluation.</li>

9414 // semantic context after precedence predicates are evaluated.</li>

9421 SemanticContext.andContext = function(a, b) {
9422 	if (a === null || a === SemanticContext.NONE) {
9423 		return b;
9424 	}
9425 	if (b === null || b === SemanticContext.NONE) {
9426 		return a;
9427 	}
9428 	var result = new AND(a, b);
9429 	if (result.opnds.length === 1) {
9430 		return result.opnds[0];
9431 	} else {
9432 		return result;
9433 	}
9434 };
9435 
9436 SemanticContext.orContext = function(a, b) {
9437 	if (a === null) {
9438 		return b;
9439 	}
9440 	if (b === null) {
9441 		return a;
9442 	}
9443 	if (a === SemanticContext.NONE || b === SemanticContext.NONE) {
9444 		return SemanticContext.NONE;
9445 	}
9446 	var result = new OR(a, b);
9447 	if (result.opnds.length === 1) {
9448 		return result.opnds[0];
9449 	} else {
9450 		return result;
9451 	}
9452 };

9454 function Predicate(ruleIndex, predIndex, isCtxDependent) {
9455 	SemanticContext.call(this);
9456 	this.ruleIndex = ruleIndex === undefined ? -1 : ruleIndex;
9457 	this.predIndex = predIndex === undefined ? -1 : predIndex;
9458 	this.isCtxDependent = isCtxDependent === undefined ? false : isCtxDependent; // e.g., $i ref in pred
9459 	return this;
9460 }

9471 Predicate.prototype.evaluate = function(parser, outerContext) {

9476 Predicate.prototype.updateHashCode = function(hash) {
9477 	hash.update(this.ruleIndex, this.predIndex, this.isCtxDependent);
9478 };

9482 		return true;
9483 	} else if (!(other instanceof Predicate)) {
9484 		return false;
9485 	} else {
9486 		return this.ruleIndex === other.ruleIndex &&
9487 				this.predIndex === other.predIndex &&
9488 				this.isCtxDependent === other.isCtxDependent;
9489 	}

9496 function PrecedencePredicate(precedence) {
9497 	SemanticContext.call(this);
9498 	this.precedence = precedence === undefined ? 0 : precedence;

9502 PrecedencePredicate.prototype.constructor = PrecedencePredicate;

9504 PrecedencePredicate.prototype.evaluate = function(parser, outerContext) {
9505 	return parser.precpred(outerContext, this.precedence);
9506 };
9507 
9508 PrecedencePredicate.prototype.evalPrecedence = function(parser, outerContext) {
9509 	if (parser.precpred(outerContext, this.precedence)) {
9510 		return SemanticContext.NONE;
9511 	} else {
9512 		return null;
9513 	}
9514 };

9517 	return this.precedence - other.precedence;
9518 };

9521     hash.update(31);
9522 };

9526 		return true;
9527 	} else if (!(other instanceof PrecedencePredicate)) {
9528 		return false;
9529 	} else {
9530 		return this.precedence === other.precedence;
9531 	}

9540 PrecedencePredicate.filterPrecedencePredicates = function(set) {
9541 	var result = [];
9542 	set.values().map( function(context) {
9543 		if (context instanceof PrecedencePredicate) {
9544 			result.push(context);
9545 		}
9546 	});
9547 	return result;

9551 // A semantic context which is true whenever none of the contained contexts
9552 // is false.
9553 //
9554 function AND(a, b) {
9555 	SemanticContext.call(this);
9556 	var operands = new Set();
9557 	if (a instanceof AND) {
9558 		a.opnds.map(function(o) {
9559 			operands.add(o);
9560 		});
9561 	} else {
9562 		operands.add(a);
9563 	}
9564 	if (b instanceof AND) {
9565 		b.opnds.map(function(o) {
9566 			operands.add(o);
9567 		});
9568 	} else {
9569 		operands.add(b);
9570 	}
9571 	var precedencePredicates = PrecedencePredicate.filterPrecedencePredicates(operands);
9572 	if (precedencePredicates.length > 0) {
9573 		// interested in the transition with the lowest precedence
9574 		var reduced = null;
9575 		precedencePredicates.map( function(p) {
9576 			if(reduced===null || p.precedence<reduced.precedence) {
9577 				reduced = p;
9578 			}
9579 		});
9580 		operands.add(reduced);
9581 	}
9582 	this.opnds = operands.values();
9583 	return this;
9584 }
9585 
9586 AND.prototype = Object.create(SemanticContext.prototype);
9587 AND.prototype.constructor = AND;
9588 
9589 AND.prototype.equals = function(other) {
9590 	if (this === other) {
9591 		return true;
9592 	} else if (!(other instanceof AND)) {
9593 		return false;
9594 	} else {
9595 		return this.opnds === other.opnds;
9596 	}
9597 };
9598 
9599 AND.prototype.updateHashCode = function(hash) {
9600     hash.update(this.opnds, "AND");
9601 };
9602 //
9603 // {@inheritDoc}
9604 //
9605 // <p>
9606 // The evaluation of predicates by this context is short-circuiting, but
9607 // unordered.</p>
9608 //
9609 AND.prototype.evaluate = function(parser, outerContext) {
9610 	for (var i = 0; i < this.opnds.length; i++) {
9611 		if (!this.opnds[i].evaluate(parser, outerContext)) {
9612 			return false;
9613 		}
9614 	}
9615 	return true;
9616 };
9617 
9618 AND.prototype.evalPrecedence = function(parser, outerContext) {
9619 	var differs = false;
9620 	var operands = [];
9621 	for (var i = 0; i < this.opnds.length; i++) {
9622 		var context = this.opnds[i];
9623 		var evaluated = context.evalPrecedence(parser, outerContext);
9624 		differs |= (evaluated !== context);
9625 		if (evaluated === null) {
9626 			// The AND context is false if any element is false
9627 			return null;
9628 		} else if (evaluated !== SemanticContext.NONE) {
9629 			// Reduce the result by skipping true elements
9630 			operands.push(evaluated);
9631 		}
9632 	}
9633 	if (!differs) {
9634 		return this;
9635 	}
9636 	if (operands.length === 0) {
9637 		// all elements were true, so the AND context is true
9638 		return SemanticContext.NONE;
9639 	}
9640 	var result = null;
9641 	operands.map(function(o) {
9642 		result = result === null ? o : SemanticContext.andContext(result, o);
9643 	});
9644 	return result;
9645 };
9646 
9647 AND.prototype.toString = function() {
9648 	var s = "";
9649 	this.opnds.map(function(o) {
9650 		s += "&& " + o.toString();
9651 	});
9652 	return s.length > 3 ? s.slice(3) : s;
9653 };
9654 
9655 //
9656 // A semantic context which is true whenever at least one of the contained
9657 // contexts is true.
9658 //
9659 function OR(a, b) {
9660 	SemanticContext.call(this);
9661 	var operands = new Set();
9662 	if (a instanceof OR) {
9663 		a.opnds.map(function(o) {
9664 			operands.add(o);
9665 		});
9666 	} else {
9667 		operands.add(a);
9668 	}
9669 	if (b instanceof OR) {
9670 		b.opnds.map(function(o) {
9671 			operands.add(o);
9672 		});
9673 	} else {
9674 		operands.add(b);
9675 	}
9676 
9677 	var precedencePredicates = PrecedencePredicate.filterPrecedencePredicates(operands);
9678 	if (precedencePredicates.length > 0) {
9679 		// interested in the transition with the highest precedence
9680 		var s = precedencePredicates.sort(function(a, b) {
9681 			return a.compareTo(b);
9682 		});
9683 		var reduced = s[s.length-1];
9684 		operands.add(reduced);
9685 	}
9686 	this.opnds = operands.values();
9687 	return this;
9688 }
9689 
9690 OR.prototype = Object.create(SemanticContext.prototype);
9691 OR.prototype.constructor = OR;
9692 
9693 OR.prototype.constructor = function(other) {
9694 	if (this === other) {
9695 		return true;
9696 	} else if (!(other instanceof OR)) {
9697 		return false;
9698 	} else {
9699 		return this.opnds === other.opnds;
9700 	}
9701 };
9702 
9703 OR.prototype.updateHashCode = function(hash) {
9704     hash.update(this.opnds, "OR");
9705 };
9706 
9707 // <p>
9708 // The evaluation of predicates by this context is short-circuiting, but
9709 // unordered.</p>
9710 //
9711 OR.prototype.evaluate = function(parser, outerContext) {
9712 	for (var i = 0; i < this.opnds.length; i++) {
9713 		if (this.opnds[i].evaluate(parser, outerContext)) {
9714 			return true;
9715 		}
9716 	}
9717 	return false;
9718 };
9719 
9720 OR.prototype.evalPrecedence = function(parser, outerContext) {
9721 	var differs = false;
9722 	var operands = [];
9723 	for (var i = 0; i < this.opnds.length; i++) {
9724 		var context = this.opnds[i];
9725 		var evaluated = context.evalPrecedence(parser, outerContext);
9726 		differs |= (evaluated !== context);
9727 		if (evaluated === SemanticContext.NONE) {
9728 			// The OR context is true if any element is true
9729 			return SemanticContext.NONE;
9730 		} else if (evaluated !== null) {
9731 			// Reduce the result by skipping false elements
9732 			operands.push(evaluated);
9733 		}
9734 	}
9735 	if (!differs) {
9736 		return this;
9737 	}
9738 	if (operands.length === 0) {
9739 		// all elements were false, so the OR context is false
9740 		return null;
9741 	}
9742 	var result = null;
9743 	operands.map(function(o) {
9744 		return result === null ? o : SemanticContext.orContext(result, o);
9745 	});
9746 	return result;
9747 };
9748 
9749 OR.prototype.toString = function() {
9750 	var s = "";
9751 	this.opnds.map(function(o) {
9752 		s += "|| " + o.toString();
9753 	});
9754 	return s.length > 3 ? s.slice(3) : s;
9755 };

9768 //  An ATN transition between any two ATN states.  Subclasses define
9769 //  atom, set, epsilon, action, predicate, rule transitions.
9770 //
9771 //  <p>This is a one way link.  It emanates from a state (usually via a list of
9772 //  transitions) and has a target state.</p>
9773 //
9774 //  <p>Since we never have to change the ATN transitions once we construct it,
9775 //  we can fix these transitions as specific classes. The DFA transitions
9776 //  on the other hand need to update the labels as it adds transitions to
9777 //  the states. We'll use the term Edge for the DFA to distinguish them from
9778 //  ATN transitions.</p>

9786 function Transition (target) {
9787     // The target of this transition.
9788     if (target===undefined || target===null) {
9789         throw "target cannot be null.";
9790     }
9791     this.target = target;
9792     // Are we epsilon, action, sempred?
9793     this.isEpsilon = false;
9794     this.label = null;
9795     return this;
9796 }
9797     // constants for serialization
9798 Transition.EPSILON = 1;
9799 Transition.RANGE = 2;
9800 Transition.RULE = 3;
9801 Transition.PREDICATE = 4; // e.g., {isType(input.LT(1))}?
9802 Transition.ATOM = 5;
9803 Transition.ACTION = 6;
9804 Transition.SET = 7; // ~(A|B) or ~atom, wildcard, which convert to next 2
9805 Transition.NOT_SET = 8;
9806 Transition.WILDCARD = 9;
9807 Transition.PRECEDENCE = 10;
9808 
9809 Transition.serializationNames = [
9810             "INVALID",
9811             "EPSILON",
9812             "RANGE",
9813             "RULE",
9814             "PREDICATE",
9815             "ATOM",
9816             "ACTION",
9817             "SET",
9818             "NOT_SET",
9819             "WILDCARD",
9820             "PRECEDENCE"
9821         ];
9822 
9823 Transition.serializationTypes = {
9824         EpsilonTransition: Transition.EPSILON,
9825         RangeTransition: Transition.RANGE,
9826         RuleTransition: Transition.RULE,
9827         PredicateTransition: Transition.PREDICATE,
9828         AtomTransition: Transition.ATOM,
9829         ActionTransition: Transition.ACTION,
9830         SetTransition: Transition.SET,
9831         NotSetTransition: Transition.NOT_SET,
9832         WildcardTransition: Transition.WILDCARD,
9833         PrecedencePredicateTransition: Transition.PRECEDENCE
9834     };

10106 function DFA(atnStartState, decision) {
10107 	if (decision === undefined) {
10108 		decision = 0;
10109 	}
10110 	// From which ATN state did we create this DFA?
10111 	this.atnStartState = atnStartState;
10112 	this.decision = decision;
10113 	// A set of all DFA states. Use {@link Map} so we can get old state back
10114 	// ({@link Set} only allows you to see if it's there).
10115 	this._states = new Set();
10116 	this.s0 = null;
10117 	// {@code true} if this DFA is for a precedence decision; otherwise,
10118 	// {@code false}. This is the backing field for {@link //isPrecedenceDfa},
10119 	// {@link //setPrecedenceDfa}.
10120 	this.precedenceDfa = false;
10121     if (atnStartState instanceof StarLoopEntryState)
10122     {
10123         if (atnStartState.isPrecedenceDecision) {
10124             this.precedenceDfa = true;
10125             var precedenceState = new DFAState(null, new ATNConfigSet());
10126             precedenceState.edges = [];
10127             precedenceState.isAcceptState = false;
10128             precedenceState.requiresFullContext = false;
10129             this.s0 = precedenceState;
10130         }
10131     }
10132 	return this;
10133 }
10134 
10135 // Get the start state for a specific precedence value.
10136 //
10137 // @param precedence The current precedence.
10138 // @return The start state corresponding to the specified precedence, or
10139 // {@code null} if no start state exists for the specified precedence.
10140 //
10141 // @throws IllegalStateException if this is not a precedence DFA.
10142 // @see //isPrecedenceDfa()
10143 
10144 DFA.prototype.getPrecedenceStartState = function(precedence) {
10145 	if (!(this.precedenceDfa)) {
10146 		throw ("Only precedence DFAs may contain a precedence start state.");
10147 	}
10148 	// s0.edges is never null for a precedence DFA
10149 	if (precedence < 0 || precedence >= this.s0.edges.length) {
10150 		return null;
10151 	}
10152 	return this.s0.edges[precedence] || null;
10153 };
10154 
10155 // Set the start state for a specific precedence value.
10156 //
10157 // @param precedence The current precedence.
10158 // @param startState The start state corresponding to the specified
10159 // precedence.
10160 //
10161 // @throws IllegalStateException if this is not a precedence DFA.
10162 // @see //isPrecedenceDfa()
10163 //
10164 DFA.prototype.setPrecedenceStartState = function(precedence, startState) {
10165 	if (!(this.precedenceDfa)) {
10166 		throw ("Only precedence DFAs may contain a precedence start state.");
10167 	}
10168 	if (precedence < 0) {
10169 		return;
10170 	}
10171 
10172 	// synchronization on s0 here is ok. when the DFA is turned into a
10173 	// precedence DFA, s0 will be initialized once and not updated again
10174 	// s0.edges is never null for a precedence DFA
10175 	this.s0.edges[precedence] = startState;
10176 };
10177 
10178 //
10179 // Sets whether this is a precedence DFA. If the specified value differs
10180 // from the current DFA configuration, the following actions are taken;
10181 // otherwise no changes are made to the current DFA.
10182 //
10183 // <ul>
10184 // <li>The {@link //states} map is cleared</li>
10185 // <li>If {@code precedenceDfa} is {@code false}, the initial state
10186 // {@link //s0} is set to {@code null}; otherwise, it is initialized to a new
10187 // {@link DFAState} with an empty outgoing {@link DFAState//edges} array to
10188 // store the start states for individual precedence values.</li>
10189 // <li>The {@link //precedenceDfa} field is updated</li>
10190 // </ul>
10191 //
10192 // @param precedenceDfa {@code true} if this is a precedence DFA; otherwise,
10193 // {@code false}
10194 
10195 DFA.prototype.setPrecedenceDfa = function(precedenceDfa) {
10196 	if (this.precedenceDfa!==precedenceDfa) {
10197 		this._states = new DFAStatesSet();
10198 		if (precedenceDfa) {
10199 			var precedenceState = new DFAState(null, new ATNConfigSet());
10200 			precedenceState.edges = [];
10201 			precedenceState.isAcceptState = false;
10202 			precedenceState.requiresFullContext = false;
10203 			this.s0 = precedenceState;
10204 		} else {
10205 			this.s0 = null;
10206 		}
10207 		this.precedenceDfa = precedenceDfa;
10208 	}
10209 };
10210 
10211 Object.defineProperty(DFA.prototype, "states", {
10212 	get : function() {
10213 		return this._states;
10214 	}
10215 });
10216 
10217 // Return a list of all states in this DFA, ordered by state number.
10218 DFA.prototype.sortedStates = function() {
10219 	var list = this._states.values();
10220 	return list.sort(function(a, b) {
10221 		return a.stateNumber - b.stateNumber;
10222 	});
10223 };
10224 
10225 DFA.prototype.toString = function(literalNames, symbolicNames) {
10226 	literalNames = literalNames || null;
10227 	symbolicNames = symbolicNames || null;
10228 	if (this.s0 === null) {
10229 		return "";
10230 	}
10231 	var serializer = new DFASerializer(this, literalNames, symbolicNames);
10232 	return serializer.toString();
10233 };

10235 DFA.prototype.toLexerString = function() {
10236 	if (this.s0 === null) {
10237 		return "";
10238 	}
10239 	var serializer = new LexerDFASerializer(this);
10240 	return serializer.toString();
10241 };

10246 /* Copyright (c) 2012-2017 The ANTLR Project. All rights reserved.

10251 // A DFA walker that knows how to dump them to serialized strings.#/
10252 
10253 
10254 function DFASerializer(dfa, literalNames, symbolicNames) {
10255 	this.dfa = dfa;
10256 	this.literalNames = literalNames || [];
10257 	this.symbolicNames = symbolicNames || [];
10258 	return this;
10259 }
10260 
10261 DFASerializer.prototype.toString = function() {
10262    if(this.dfa.s0 === null) {
10263        return null;
10264    }
10265    var buf = "";
10266    var states = this.dfa.sortedStates();
10267    for(var i=0;i<states.length;i++) {
10268        var s = states[i];
10269        if(s.edges!==null) {
10270             var n = s.edges.length;
10271             for(var j=0;j<n;j++) {
10272                 var t = s.edges[j] || null;
10273                 if(t!==null && t.stateNumber !== 0x7FFFFFFF) {
10274                     buf = buf.concat(this.getStateString(s));
10275                     buf = buf.concat("-");
10276                     buf = buf.concat(this.getEdgeLabel(j));
10277                     buf = buf.concat("->");
10278                     buf = buf.concat(this.getStateString(t));
10279                     buf = buf.concat('\n');
10280                 }
10281             }
10282        }
10283    }
10284    return buf.length===0 ? null : buf;
10285 };
10286 
10287 DFASerializer.prototype.getEdgeLabel = function(i) {
10288     if (i===0) {
10289         return "EOF";
10290     } else if(this.literalNames !==null || this.symbolicNames!==null) {
10291         return this.literalNames[i-1] || this.symbolicNames[i-1];
10292     } else {
10293         return String.fromCharCode(i-1);
10294     }
10295 };
10296 
10297 DFASerializer.prototype.getStateString = function(s) {
10298     var baseStateStr = ( s.isAcceptState ? ":" : "") + "s" + s.stateNumber + ( s.requiresFullContext ? "^" : "");
10299     if(s.isAcceptState) {
10300         if (s.predicates !== null) {
10301             return baseStateStr + "=>" + s.predicates.toString();
10302         } else {
10303             return baseStateStr + "=>" + s.prediction.toString();
10304         }
10305     } else {
10306         return baseStateStr;
10307     }
10308 };
10309 
10310 function LexerDFASerializer(dfa) {
10311 	DFASerializer.call(this, dfa, null);
10312 	return this;
10313 }
10314 
10315 LexerDFASerializer.prototype = Object.create(DFASerializer.prototype);
10316 LexerDFASerializer.prototype.constructor = LexerDFASerializer;
10317 
10318 LexerDFASerializer.prototype.getEdgeLabel = function(i) {
10319 	return "'" + String.fromCharCode(i) + "'";
10320 };
10321 
10322 exports.DFASerializer = DFASerializer;
10323 exports.LexerDFASerializer = LexerDFASerializer;

10351 // A DFA state represents a set of possible ATN configurations.
10352 // As Aho, Sethi, Ullman p. 117 says "The DFA uses its state
10353 // to keep track of all possible states the ATN can be in after
10354 // reading each input symbol. That is to say, after reading
10355 // input a1a2..an, the DFA is in a state that represents the
10356 // subset T of the states of the ATN that are reachable from the
10357 // ATN's start state along some path labeled a1a2..an."
10358 // In conventional NFA&rarr;DFA conversion, therefore, the subset T
10359 // would be a bitset representing the set of states the
10360 // ATN could be in. We need to track the alt predicted by each
10361 // state as well, however. More importantly, we need to maintain
10362 // a stack of states, tracking the closure operations as they
10363 // jump from rule to rule, emulating rule invocations (method calls).
10364 // I have to add a stack to simulate the proper lookahead sequences for
10365 // the underlying LL grammar from which the ATN was derived.
10366 //
10367 // <p>I use a set of ATNConfig objects not simple states. An ATNConfig
10368 // is both a state (ala normal conversion) and a RuleContext describing
10369 // the chain of rules (if any) followed to arrive at that state.</p>
10370 //
10371 // <p>A DFA state may have multiple references to a particular state,
10372 // but with different ATN contexts (with same or different alts)
10373 // meaning that state was reached via a different set of rule invocations.</p>
10374 // /
10375 
10376 function DFAState(stateNumber, configs) {
10377 	if (stateNumber === null) {
10378 		stateNumber = -1;
10379 	}
10380 	if (configs === null) {
10381 		configs = new ATNConfigSet();
10382 	}
10383 	this.stateNumber = stateNumber;
10384 	this.configs = configs;
10385 	// {@code edges[symbol]} points to target of symbol. Shift up by 1 so (-1)
10386 	// {@link Token//EOF} maps to {@code edges[0]}.
10387 	this.edges = null;
10388 	this.isAcceptState = false;
10389 	// if accept state, what ttype do we match or alt do we predict?
10390 	// This is set to {@link ATN//INVALID_ALT_NUMBER} when {@link
10391 	// //predicates}{@code !=null} or
10392 	// {@link //requiresFullContext}.
10393 	this.prediction = 0;
10394 	this.lexerActionExecutor = null;
10395 	// Indicates that this state was created during SLL prediction that
10396 	// discovered a conflict between the configurations in the state. Future
10397 	// {@link ParserATNSimulator//execATN} invocations immediately jumped doing
10398 	// full context prediction if this field is true.
10399 	this.requiresFullContext = false;
10400 	// During SLL parsing, this is a list of predicates associated with the
10401 	// ATN configurations of the DFA state. When we have predicates,
10402 	// {@link //requiresFullContext} is {@code false} since full context
10403 	// prediction evaluates predicates
10404 	// on-the-fly. If this is not null, then {@link //prediction} is
10405 	// {@link ATN//INVALID_ALT_NUMBER}.
10406 	//
10407 	// <p>We only use these for non-{@link //requiresFullContext} but
10408 	// conflicting states. That
10409 	// means we know from the context (it's $ or we don't dip into outer
10410 	// context) that it's an ambiguity not a conflict.</p>
10411 	//
10412 	// <p>This list is computed by {@link
10413 	// ParserATNSimulator//predicateDFAState}.</p>
10414 	this.predicates = null;
10415 	return this;
10416 }
10417 
10418 // Get the set of all alts mentioned by all ATN configurations in this
10419 // DFA state.
10420 DFAState.prototype.getAltSet = function() {
10421 	var alts = new Set();
10422 	if (this.configs !== null) {
10423 		for (var i = 0; i < this.configs.length; i++) {
10424 			var c = this.configs[i];
10425 			alts.add(c.alt);
10426 		}
10427 	}
10428 	if (alts.length === 0) {
10429 		return null;
10430 	} else {
10431 		return alts;
10432 	}
10433 };
10434 
10435 // Two {@link DFAState} instances are equal if their ATN configuration sets
10436 // are the same. This method is used to see if a state already exists.
10437 //
10438 // <p>Because the number of alternatives and number of ATN configurations are
10439 // finite, there is a finite number of DFA states that can be processed.
10440 // This is necessary to show that the algorithm terminates.</p>
10441 //
10442 // <p>Cannot test the DFA state numbers here because in
10443 // {@link ParserATNSimulator//addDFAState} we need to know if any other state
10444 // exists that has this exact set of ATN configurations. The
10445 // {@link //stateNumber} is irrelevant.</p>
10446 DFAState.prototype.equals = function(other) {
10447 	// compare set of ATN configurations in this set with other
10448 	return this === other ||
10449 			(other instanceof DFAState &&
10450 				this.configs.equals(other.configs));
10451 };
10452 
10453 DFAState.prototype.toString = function() {
10454 	var s = "" + this.stateNumber + ":" + this.configs;
10455 	if(this.isAcceptState) {
10456         s = s + "=>";
10457         if (this.predicates !== null)
10458             s = s + this.predicates;
10459         else
10460             s = s + this.prediction;
10461     }
10462 	return s;
10463 };
10464 
10465 DFAState.prototype.hashCode = function() {
10466 	var hash = new Hash();
10467 	hash.update(this.configs);
10468 	if(this.isAcceptState) {
10469         if (this.predicates !== null)
10470             hash.update(this.predicates);
10471         else
10472             hash.update(this.prediction);
10473     }
10474     return hash.finish();
10475 };
10476 
10477 exports.DFAState = DFAState;
10478 exports.PredPrediction = PredPrediction;

10500 // This implementation of {@link ANTLRErrorListener} can be used to identify
10501 // certain potential correctness and performance problems in grammars. "Reports"
10502 // are made by calling {@link Parser//notifyErrorListeners} with the appropriate
10503 // message.
10504 //
10505 // <ul>
10506 // <li><b>Ambiguities</b>: These are cases where more than one path through the
10507 // grammar can match the input.</li>
10508 // <li><b>Weak context sensitivity</b>: These are cases where full-context
10509 // prediction resolved an SLL conflict to a unique alternative which equaled the
10510 // minimum alternative of the SLL conflict.</li>
10511 // <li><b>Strong (forced) context sensitivity</b>: These are cases where the
10512 // full-context prediction resolved an SLL conflict to a unique alternative,
10513 // <em>and</em> the minimum alternative of the SLL conflict was found to not be
10514 // a truly viable alternative. Two-stage parsing cannot be used for inputs where
10515 // this situation occurs.</li>
10516 // </ul>
10517 
10518 var BitSet = require('./../Utils').BitSet;
10519 var ErrorListener = require('./ErrorListener').ErrorListener;
10520 var Interval = require('./../IntervalSet').Interval;
10521 
10522 function DiagnosticErrorListener(exactOnly) {
10523 	ErrorListener.call(this);
10524 	exactOnly = exactOnly || true;
10525 	// whether all ambiguities or only exact ambiguities are reported.
10526 	this.exactOnly = exactOnly;
10527 	return this;
10528 }
10529 
10530 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype = Object.create(ErrorListener.prototype);
10531 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype.constructor = DiagnosticErrorListener;
10532 
10533 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype.reportAmbiguity = function(recognizer, dfa,
10534 		startIndex, stopIndex, exact, ambigAlts, configs) {
10535 	if (this.exactOnly && !exact) {
10536 		return;
10537 	}
10538 	var msg = "reportAmbiguity d=" +
10539 			this.getDecisionDescription(recognizer, dfa) +
10540 			": ambigAlts=" +
10541 			this.getConflictingAlts(ambigAlts, configs) +
10542 			", input='" +
10543 			recognizer.getTokenStream().getText(new Interval(startIndex, stopIndex)) + "'";
10544 	recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg);
10545 };
10546 
10547 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype.reportAttemptingFullContext = function(
10548 		recognizer, dfa, startIndex, stopIndex, conflictingAlts, configs) {
10549 	var msg = "reportAttemptingFullContext d=" +
10550 			this.getDecisionDescription(recognizer, dfa) +
10551 			", input='" +
10552 			recognizer.getTokenStream().getText(new Interval(startIndex, stopIndex)) + "'";
10553 	recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg);
10554 };
10555 
10556 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype.reportContextSensitivity = function(
10557 		recognizer, dfa, startIndex, stopIndex, prediction, configs) {
10558 	var msg = "reportContextSensitivity d=" +
10559 			this.getDecisionDescription(recognizer, dfa) +
10560 			", input='" +
10561 			recognizer.getTokenStream().getText(new Interval(startIndex, stopIndex)) + "'";
10562 	recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg);
10563 };
10564 
10565 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype.getDecisionDescription = function(recognizer, dfa) {
10566 	var decision = dfa.decision;
10567 	var ruleIndex = dfa.atnStartState.ruleIndex;
10568 
10569 	var ruleNames = recognizer.ruleNames;
10570 	if (ruleIndex < 0 || ruleIndex >= ruleNames.length) {
10571 		return "" + decision;
10572 	}
10573 	var ruleName = ruleNames[ruleIndex] || null;
10574 	if (ruleName === null || ruleName.length === 0) {
10575 		return "" + decision;
10576 	}
10577 	return "" + decision + " (" + ruleName + ")";
10578 };

10580 //

10582 // configuration set, if that information was not already provided by the
10583 // parser.
10584 //
10585 // @param reportedAlts The set of conflicting or ambiguous alternatives, as
10586 // reported by the parser.
10587 // @param configs The conflicting or ambiguous configuration set.
10588 // @return Returns {@code reportedAlts} if it is not {@code null}, otherwise
10589 // returns the set of alternatives represented in {@code configs}.
10590 //
10591 DiagnosticErrorListener.prototype.getConflictingAlts = function(reportedAlts, configs) {
10592 	if (reportedAlts !== null) {
10593 		return reportedAlts;
10594 	}
10595 	var result = new BitSet();
10596 	for (var i = 0; i < configs.items.length; i++) {
10597 		result.add(configs.items[i].alt);
10598 	}
10599 	return "{" + result.values().join(", ") + "}";
10600 };

10733 
10734 // This is the default implementation of {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy} used for
10735 // error reporting and recovery in ANTLR parsers.
10736 //
10737 function DefaultErrorStrategy() {
10738 	ErrorStrategy.call(this);
10739     // Indicates whether the error strategy is currently "recovering from an
10740     // error". This is used to suppress reporting multiple error messages while
10741     // attempting to recover from a detected syntax error.
10742     //
10743     // @see //inErrorRecoveryMode
10744     //
10745     this.errorRecoveryMode = false;
10746 
10747     // The index into the input stream where the last error occurred.
10748     // This is used to prevent infinite loops where an error is found
10749     // but no token is consumed during recovery...another error is found,
10750     // ad nauseum. This is a failsafe mechanism to guarantee that at least
10751     // one token/tree node is consumed for two errors.
10752     //
10753     this.lastErrorIndex = -1;
10754     this.lastErrorStates = null;
10755     return this;
10756 }
10757 
10758 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype = Object.create(ErrorStrategy.prototype);
10759 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.constructor = DefaultErrorStrategy;
10760 
10761 // <p>The default implementation simply calls {@link //endErrorCondition} to
10762 // ensure that the handler is not in error recovery mode.</p>
10763 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reset = function(recognizer) {
10764     this.endErrorCondition(recognizer);
10765 };
10766 
10767 //
10768 // This method is called to enter error recovery mode when a recognition
10769 // exception is reported.
10770 //
10771 // @param recognizer the parser instance
10772 //
10773 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.beginErrorCondition = function(recognizer) {
10774     this.errorRecoveryMode = true;
10775 };
10776 
10777 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.inErrorRecoveryMode = function(recognizer) {
10778     return this.errorRecoveryMode;
10779 };

10781 //
10782 // This method is called to leave error recovery mode after recovering from
10783 // a recognition exception.
10784 //
10785 // @param recognizer
10786 //
10787 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.endErrorCondition = function(recognizer) {
10788     this.errorRecoveryMode = false;
10789     this.lastErrorStates = null;
10790     this.lastErrorIndex = -1;
10791 };
10792 
10793 //
10794 // {@inheritDoc}
10795 //
10796 // <p>The default implementation simply calls {@link //endErrorCondition}.</p>
10797 //
10798 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportMatch = function(recognizer) {
10799     this.endErrorCondition(recognizer);
10800 };
10801 
10802 //
10803 // {@inheritDoc}
10804 //
10805 // <p>The default implementation returns immediately if the handler is already
10806 // in error recovery mode. Otherwise, it calls {@link //beginErrorCondition}
10807 // and dispatches the reporting task based on the runtime type of {@code e}
10808 // according to the following table.</p>
10809 //
10810 // <ul>
10811 // <li>{@link NoViableAltException}: Dispatches the call to
10812 // {@link //reportNoViableAlternative}</li>
10813 // <li>{@link InputMismatchException}: Dispatches the call to
10814 // {@link //reportInputMismatch}</li>
10815 // <li>{@link FailedPredicateException}: Dispatches the call to
10816 // {@link //reportFailedPredicate}</li>
10817 // <li>All other types: calls {@link Parser//notifyErrorListeners} to report
10818 // the exception</li>
10819 // </ul>
10820 //
10821 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportError = function(recognizer, e) {
10822    // if we've already reported an error and have not matched a token
10823    // yet successfully, don't report any errors.
10824     if(this.inErrorRecoveryMode(recognizer)) {
10825         return; // don't report spurious errors
10826     }
10827     this.beginErrorCondition(recognizer);
10828     if ( e instanceof NoViableAltException ) {
10829         this.reportNoViableAlternative(recognizer, e);
10830     } else if ( e instanceof InputMismatchException ) {
10831         this.reportInputMismatch(recognizer, e);
10832     } else if ( e instanceof FailedPredicateException ) {
10833         this.reportFailedPredicate(recognizer, e);
10834     } else {
10835         console.log("unknown recognition error type: " + e.constructor.name);
10836         console.log(e.stack);
10837         recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(e.getOffendingToken(), e.getMessage(), e);
10838     }
10839 };
10840 //
10841 // {@inheritDoc}
10842 //
10843 // <p>The default implementation resynchronizes the parser by consuming tokens
10844 // until we find one in the resynchronization set--loosely the set of tokens
10845 // that can follow the current rule.</p>
10846 //
10847 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.recover = function(recognizer, e) {
10848     if (this.lastErrorIndex===recognizer.getInputStream().index &&
10849         this.lastErrorStates !== null && this.lastErrorStates.indexOf(recognizer.state)>=0) {
10850 		// uh oh, another error at same token index and previously-visited
10851 		// state in ATN; must be a case where LT(1) is in the recovery
10852 		// token set so nothing got consumed. Consume a single token
10853 		// at least to prevent an infinite loop; this is a failsafe.
10854 		recognizer.consume();
10855     }
10856     this.lastErrorIndex = recognizer._input.index;
10857     if (this.lastErrorStates === null) {
10858         this.lastErrorStates = [];
10859     }
10860     this.lastErrorStates.push(recognizer.state);
10861     var followSet = this.getErrorRecoverySet(recognizer);
10862     this.consumeUntil(recognizer, followSet);
10863 };
10864 
10865 // The default implementation of {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy//sync} makes sure
10866 // that the current lookahead symbol is consistent with what were expecting
10867 // at this point in the ATN. You can call this anytime but ANTLR only
10868 // generates code to check before subrules/loops and each iteration.
10869 //
10870 // <p>Implements Jim Idle's magic sync mechanism in closures and optional
10871 // subrules. E.g.,</p>
10872 //
10873 // <pre>
10874 // a : sync ( stuff sync )* ;
10875 // sync : {consume to what can follow sync} ;
10876 // </pre>
10877 //
10878 // At the start of a sub rule upon error, {@link //sync} performs single
10879 // token deletion, if possible. If it can't do that, it bails on the current
10880 // rule and uses the default error recovery, which consumes until the
10881 // resynchronization set of the current rule.
10882 //
10883 // <p>If the sub rule is optional ({@code (...)?}, {@code (...)*}, or block
10884 // with an empty alternative), then the expected set includes what follows
10885 // the subrule.</p>
10886 //
10887 // <p>During loop iteration, it consumes until it sees a token that can start a
10888 // sub rule or what follows loop. Yes, that is pretty aggressive. We opt to
10889 // stay in the loop as long as possible.</p>
10890 //
10891 // <p><strong>ORIGINS</strong></p>
10892 //
10893 // <p>Previous versions of ANTLR did a poor job of their recovery within loops.
10894 // A single mismatch token or missing token would force the parser to bail
10895 // out of the entire rules surrounding the loop. So, for rule</p>
10896 //
10897 // <pre>
10898 // classDef : 'class' ID '{' member* '}'
10899 // </pre>
10900 //
10901 // input with an extra token between members would force the parser to
10902 // consume until it found the next class definition rather than the next
10903 // member definition of the current class.
10904 //
10905 // <p>This functionality cost a little bit of effort because the parser has to
10906 // compare token set at the start of the loop and at each iteration. If for
10907 // some reason speed is suffering for you, you can turn off this
10908 // functionality by simply overriding this method as a blank { }.</p>
10909 //
10910 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.sync = function(recognizer) {
10911     // If already recovering, don't try to sync
10912     if (this.inErrorRecoveryMode(recognizer)) {
10913         return;
10914     }
10915     var s = recognizer._interp.atn.states[recognizer.state];
10916     var la = recognizer.getTokenStream().LA(1);
10917     // try cheaper subset first; might get lucky. seems to shave a wee bit off
10918     var nextTokens = recognizer.atn.nextTokens(s);
10919     if (nextTokens.contains(Token.EPSILON) || nextTokens.contains(la)) {
10920         return;
10921     }
10922     switch (s.stateType) {
10923     case ATNState.BLOCK_START:
10924     case ATNState.STAR_BLOCK_START:
10925     case ATNState.PLUS_BLOCK_START:
10926     case ATNState.STAR_LOOP_ENTRY:
10927        // report error and recover if possible
10928         if( this.singleTokenDeletion(recognizer) !== null) {
10929             return;
10930         } else {
10931             throw new InputMismatchException(recognizer);
10932         }
10933         break;
10934     case ATNState.PLUS_LOOP_BACK:
10935     case ATNState.STAR_LOOP_BACK:
10936         this.reportUnwantedToken(recognizer);
10937         var expecting = new IntervalSet();
10938         expecting.addSet(recognizer.getExpectedTokens());
10939         var whatFollowsLoopIterationOrRule = expecting.addSet(this.getErrorRecoverySet(recognizer));
10940         this.consumeUntil(recognizer, whatFollowsLoopIterationOrRule);
10941         break;
10942     default:
10943         // do nothing if we can't identify the exact kind of ATN state
10944     }
10945 };
10946 
10947 // This is called by {@link //reportError} when the exception is a
10948 // {@link NoViableAltException}.
10949 //
10950 // @see //reportError
10951 //
10952 // @param recognizer the parser instance
10953 // @param e the recognition exception
10954 //
10955 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportNoViableAlternative = function(recognizer, e) {
10956     var tokens = recognizer.getTokenStream();
10957     var input;
10958     if(tokens !== null) {
10959         if (e.startToken.type===Token.EOF) {
10960             input = "<EOF>";
10961         } else {
10962             input = tokens.getText(new Interval(e.startToken, e.offendingToken));
10963         }
10964     } else {
10965         input = "<unknown input>";
10966     }
10967     var msg = "no viable alternative at input " + this.escapeWSAndQuote(input);
10968     recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg, e.offendingToken, e);
10969 };
10970 
10971 //
10972 // This is called by {@link //reportError} when the exception is an
10973 // {@link InputMismatchException}.
10974 //
10975 // @see //reportError
10976 //
10977 // @param recognizer the parser instance
10978 // @param e the recognition exception
10979 //
10980 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportInputMismatch = function(recognizer, e) {
10981     var msg = "mismatched input " + this.getTokenErrorDisplay(e.offendingToken) +
10982           " expecting " + e.getExpectedTokens().toString(recognizer.literalNames, recognizer.symbolicNames);
10983     recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg, e.offendingToken, e);
10984 };
