10986 //
10987 // This is called by {@link //reportError} when the exception is a
10988 // {@link FailedPredicateException}.
10989 //
10990 // @see //reportError
10991 //
10992 // @param recognizer the parser instance
10993 // @param e the recognition exception
10994 //
10995 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportFailedPredicate = function(recognizer, e) {
10996     var ruleName = recognizer.ruleNames[recognizer._ctx.ruleIndex];
10997     var msg = "rule " + ruleName + " " + e.message;
10998     recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg, e.offendingToken, e);
10999 };
11000 
11001 // This method is called to report a syntax error which requires the removal
11002 // of a token from the input stream. At the time this method is called, the
11003 // erroneous symbol is current {@code LT(1)} symbol and has not yet been
11004 // removed from the input stream. When this method returns,
11005 // {@code recognizer} is in error recovery mode.
11006 //
11007 // <p>This method is called when {@link //singleTokenDeletion} identifies
11008 // single-token deletion as a viable recovery strategy for a mismatched
11009 // input error.</p>
11010 //
11011 // <p>The default implementation simply returns if the handler is already in
11012 // error recovery mode. Otherwise, it calls {@link //beginErrorCondition} to
11013 // enter error recovery mode, followed by calling
11014 // {@link Parser//notifyErrorListeners}.</p>
11015 //
11016 // @param recognizer the parser instance
11017 //
11018 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportUnwantedToken = function(recognizer) {
11019     if (this.inErrorRecoveryMode(recognizer)) {
11020         return;
11021     }
11022     this.beginErrorCondition(recognizer);
11023     var t = recognizer.getCurrentToken();
11024     var tokenName = this.getTokenErrorDisplay(t);
11025     var expecting = this.getExpectedTokens(recognizer);
11026     var msg = "extraneous input " + tokenName + " expecting " +
11027         expecting.toString(recognizer.literalNames, recognizer.symbolicNames);
11028     recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg, t, null);
11029 };
11030 // This method is called to report a syntax error which requires the
11031 // insertion of a missing token into the input stream. At the time this
11032 // method is called, the missing token has not yet been inserted. When this
11033 // method returns, {@code recognizer} is in error recovery mode.
11034 //
11035 // <p>This method is called when {@link //singleTokenInsertion} identifies
11036 // single-token insertion as a viable recovery strategy for a mismatched
11037 // input error.</p>
11038 //
11039 // <p>The default implementation simply returns if the handler is already in
11040 // error recovery mode. Otherwise, it calls {@link //beginErrorCondition} to
11041 // enter error recovery mode, followed by calling
11042 // {@link Parser//notifyErrorListeners}.</p>
11043 //
11044 // @param recognizer the parser instance
11045 //
11046 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.reportMissingToken = function(recognizer) {
11047     if ( this.inErrorRecoveryMode(recognizer)) {
11048         return;
11049     }
11050     this.beginErrorCondition(recognizer);
11051     var t = recognizer.getCurrentToken();
11052     var expecting = this.getExpectedTokens(recognizer);
11053     var msg = "missing " + expecting.toString(recognizer.literalNames, recognizer.symbolicNames) +
11054           " at " + this.getTokenErrorDisplay(t);
11055     recognizer.notifyErrorListeners(msg, t, null);
11056 };
11057 
11058 // <p>The default implementation attempts to recover from the mismatched input
11059 // by using single token insertion and deletion as described below. If the
11060 // recovery attempt fails, this method throws an
11061 // {@link InputMismatchException}.</p>
11062 //
11063 // <p><strong>EXTRA TOKEN</strong> (single token deletion)</p>
11064 //
11065 // <p>{@code LA(1)} is not what we are looking for. If {@code LA(2)} has the
11066 // right token, however, then assume {@code LA(1)} is some extra spurious
11067 // token and delete it. Then consume and return the next token (which was
11068 // the {@code LA(2)} token) as the successful result of the match operation.</p>
11069 //
11070 // <p>This recovery strategy is implemented by {@link
11071 // //singleTokenDeletion}.</p>
11072 //
11073 // <p><strong>MISSING TOKEN</strong> (single token insertion)</p>
11074 //
11075 // <p>If current token (at {@code LA(1)}) is consistent with what could come
11076 // after the expected {@code LA(1)} token, then assume the token is missing
11077 // and use the parser's {@link TokenFactory} to create it on the fly. The
11078 // "insertion" is performed by returning the created token as the successful
11079 // result of the match operation.</p>
11080 //
11081 // <p>This recovery strategy is implemented by {@link
11082 // //singleTokenInsertion}.</p>
11083 //
11084 // <p><strong>EXAMPLE</strong></p>
11085 //
11086 // <p>For example, Input {@code i=(3;} is clearly missing the {@code ')'}. When
11087 // the parser returns from the nested call to {@code expr}, it will have
11088 // call chain:</p>
11089 //
11090 // <pre>
11091 // stat &rarr; expr &rarr; atom
11092 // </pre>
11093 //
11094 // and it will be trying to match the {@code ')'} at this point in the
11095 // derivation:
11096 //
11097 // <pre>
11098 // =&gt; ID '=' '(' INT ')' ('+' atom)* ';'
11099 // ^
11100 // </pre>
11101 //
11102 // The attempt to match {@code ')'} will fail when it sees {@code ';'} and
11103 // call {@link //recoverInline}. To recover, it sees that {@code LA(1)==';'}
11104 // is in the set of tokens that can follow the {@code ')'} token reference
11105 // in rule {@code atom}. It can assume that you forgot the {@code ')'}.
11106 //
11107 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.recoverInline = function(recognizer) {
11108     // SINGLE TOKEN DELETION
11109     var matchedSymbol = this.singleTokenDeletion(recognizer);
11110     if (matchedSymbol !== null) {
11111         // we have deleted the extra token.
11112         // now, move past ttype token as if all were ok
11113         recognizer.consume();
11114         return matchedSymbol;
11115     }
11116     // SINGLE TOKEN INSERTION
11117     if (this.singleTokenInsertion(recognizer)) {
11118         return this.getMissingSymbol(recognizer);
11119     }
11120     // even that didn't work; must throw the exception
11121     throw new InputMismatchException(recognizer);
11122 };
11123 
11124 //
11125 // This method implements the single-token insertion inline error recovery
11126 // strategy. It is called by {@link //recoverInline} if the single-token
11127 // deletion strategy fails to recover from the mismatched input. If this
11128 // method returns {@code true}, {@code recognizer} will be in error recovery
11129 // mode.
11130 //
11131 // <p>This method determines whether or not single-token insertion is viable by
11132 // checking if the {@code LA(1)} input symbol could be successfully matched
11133 // if it were instead the {@code LA(2)} symbol. If this method returns
11134 // {@code true}, the caller is responsible for creating and inserting a
11135 // token with the correct type to produce this behavior.</p>
11136 //
11137 // @param recognizer the parser instance
11138 // @return {@code true} if single-token insertion is a viable recovery
11139 // strategy for the current mismatched input, otherwise {@code false}
11140 //
11141 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.singleTokenInsertion = function(recognizer) {
11142     var currentSymbolType = recognizer.getTokenStream().LA(1);
11143     // if current token is consistent with what could come after current
11144     // ATN state, then we know we're missing a token; error recovery
11145     // is free to conjure up and insert the missing token
11146     var atn = recognizer._interp.atn;
11147     var currentState = atn.states[recognizer.state];
11148     var next = currentState.transitions[0].target;
11149     var expectingAtLL2 = atn.nextTokens(next, recognizer._ctx);
11150     if (expectingAtLL2.contains(currentSymbolType) ){
11151         this.reportMissingToken(recognizer);
11152         return true;
11153     } else {
11154         return false;
11155     }
11156 };
11157 
11158 // This method implements the single-token deletion inline error recovery
11159 // strategy. It is called by {@link //recoverInline} to attempt to recover
11160 // from mismatched input. If this method returns null, the parser and error
11161 // handler state will not have changed. If this method returns non-null,
11162 // {@code recognizer} will <em>not</em> be in error recovery mode since the
11163 // returned token was a successful match.
11164 //
11165 // <p>If the single-token deletion is successful, this method calls
11166 // {@link //reportUnwantedToken} to report the error, followed by
11167 // {@link Parser//consume} to actually "delete" the extraneous token. Then,
11168 // before returning {@link //reportMatch} is called to signal a successful
11169 // match.</p>
11170 //
11171 // @param recognizer the parser instance
11172 // @return the successfully matched {@link Token} instance if single-token
11173 // deletion successfully recovers from the mismatched input, otherwise
11174 // {@code null}
11175 //
11176 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.singleTokenDeletion = function(recognizer) {
11177     var nextTokenType = recognizer.getTokenStream().LA(2);
11178     var expecting = this.getExpectedTokens(recognizer);
11179     if (expecting.contains(nextTokenType)) {
11180         this.reportUnwantedToken(recognizer);
11181         // print("recoverFromMismatchedToken deleting " \
11182         // + str(recognizer.getTokenStream().LT(1)) \
11183         // + " since " + str(recognizer.getTokenStream().LT(2)) \
11184         // + " is what we want", file=sys.stderr)
11185         recognizer.consume(); // simply delete extra token
11186         // we want to return the token we're actually matching
11187         var matchedSymbol = recognizer.getCurrentToken();
11188         this.reportMatch(recognizer); // we know current token is correct
11189         return matchedSymbol;
11190     } else {
11191         return null;
11192     }
11193 };
11194 
11195 // Conjure up a missing token during error recovery.
11196 //
11197 // The recognizer attempts to recover from single missing
11198 // symbols. But, actions might refer to that missing symbol.
11199 // For example, x=ID {f($x);}. The action clearly assumes
11200 // that there has been an identifier matched previously and that
11201 // $x points at that token. If that token is missing, but
11202 // the next token in the stream is what we want we assume that
11203 // this token is missing and we keep going. Because we
11204 // have to return some token to replace the missing token,
11205 // we have to conjure one up. This method gives the user control
11206 // over the tokens returned for missing tokens. Mostly,
11207 // you will want to create something special for identifier
11208 // tokens. For literals such as '{' and ',', the default
11209 // action in the parser or tree parser works. It simply creates
11210 // a CommonToken of the appropriate type. The text will be the token.
11211 // If you change what tokens must be created by the lexer,
11212 // override this method to create the appropriate tokens.
11213 //
11214 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.getMissingSymbol = function(recognizer) {
11215     var currentSymbol = recognizer.getCurrentToken();
11216     var expecting = this.getExpectedTokens(recognizer);
11217     var expectedTokenType = expecting.first(); // get any element
11218     var tokenText;
11219     if (expectedTokenType===Token.EOF) {
11220         tokenText = "<missing EOF>";
11221     } else {
11222         tokenText = "<missing " + recognizer.literalNames[expectedTokenType] + ">";
11223     }
11224     var current = currentSymbol;
11225     var lookback = recognizer.getTokenStream().LT(-1);
11226     if (current.type===Token.EOF && lookback !== null) {
11227         current = lookback;
11228     }
11229     return recognizer.getTokenFactory().create(current.source,
11230         expectedTokenType, tokenText, Token.DEFAULT_CHANNEL,
11231         -1, -1, current.line, current.column);
11232 };
11233 
11234 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.getExpectedTokens = function(recognizer) {
11235     return recognizer.getExpectedTokens();
11236 };
11237 
11238 // How should a token be displayed in an error message? The default
11239 // is to display just the text, but during development you might
11240 // want to have a lot of information spit out. Override in that case
11241 // to use t.toString() (which, for CommonToken, dumps everything about
11242 // the token). This is better than forcing you to override a method in
11243 // your token objects because you don't have to go modify your lexer
11244 // so that it creates a new Java type.
11245 //
11246 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.getTokenErrorDisplay = function(t) {
11247     if (t === null) {
11248         return "<no token>";
11249     }
11250     var s = t.text;
11251     if (s === null) {
11252         if (t.type===Token.EOF) {
11253             s = "<EOF>";
11254         } else {
11255             s = "<" + t.type + ">";
11256         }
11257     }
11258     return this.escapeWSAndQuote(s);
11259 };
11260 
11261 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.escapeWSAndQuote = function(s) {
11262     s = s.replace(/\n/g,"\\n");
11263     s = s.replace(/\r/g,"\\r");
11264     s = s.replace(/\t/g,"\\t");
11265     return "'" + s + "'";
11266 };
11267 
11268 // Compute the error recovery set for the current rule. During
11269 // rule invocation, the parser pushes the set of tokens that can
11270 // follow that rule reference on the stack; this amounts to
11271 // computing FIRST of what follows the rule reference in the
11272 // enclosing rule. See LinearApproximator.FIRST().
11273 // This local follow set only includes tokens
11274 // from within the rule; i.e., the FIRST computation done by
11275 // ANTLR stops at the end of a rule.
11276 //
11277 // EXAMPLE
11278 //
11279 // When you find a "no viable alt exception", the input is not
11280 // consistent with any of the alternatives for rule r. The best
11281 // thing to do is to consume tokens until you see something that
11282 // can legally follow a call to r//or* any rule that called r.
11283 // You don't want the exact set of viable next tokens because the
11284 // input might just be missing a token--you might consume the
11285 // rest of the input looking for one of the missing tokens.
11286 //
11287 // Consider grammar:
11288 //
11289 // a : '[' b ']'
11290 // | '(' b ')'
11291 // ;
11292 // b : c '^' INT ;
11293 // c : ID
11294 // | INT
11295 // ;
11296 //
11297 // At each rule invocation, the set of tokens that could follow
11298 // that rule is pushed on a stack. Here are the various
11299 // context-sensitive follow sets:
11300 //
11301 // FOLLOW(b1_in_a) = FIRST(']') = ']'
11302 // FOLLOW(b2_in_a) = FIRST(')') = ')'
11303 // FOLLOW(c_in_b) = FIRST('^') = '^'
11304 //
11305 // Upon erroneous input "[]", the call chain is
11306 //
11307 // a -> b -> c
11308 //
11309 // and, hence, the follow context stack is:
11310 //
11311 // depth follow set start of rule execution
11312 // 0 <EOF> a (from main())
11313 // 1 ']' b
11314 // 2 '^' c
11315 //
11316 // Notice that ')' is not included, because b would have to have
11317 // been called from a different context in rule a for ')' to be
11318 // included.
11319 //
11320 // For error recovery, we cannot consider FOLLOW(c)
11321 // (context-sensitive or otherwise). We need the combined set of
11322 // all context-sensitive FOLLOW sets--the set of all tokens that
11323 // could follow any reference in the call chain. We need to
11324 // resync to one of those tokens. Note that FOLLOW(c)='^' and if
11325 // we resync'd to that token, we'd consume until EOF. We need to
11326 // sync to context-sensitive FOLLOWs for a, b, and c: {']','^'}.
11327 // In this case, for input "[]", LA(1) is ']' and in the set, so we would
11328 // not consume anything. After printing an error, rule c would
11329 // return normally. Rule b would not find the required '^' though.
11330 // At this point, it gets a mismatched token error and throws an
11331 // exception (since LA(1) is not in the viable following token
11332 // set). The rule exception handler tries to recover, but finds
11333 // the same recovery set and doesn't consume anything. Rule b
11334 // exits normally returning to rule a. Now it finds the ']' (and
11335 // with the successful match exits errorRecovery mode).
11336 //
11337 // So, you can see that the parser walks up the call chain looking
11338 // for the token that was a member of the recovery set.
11339 //
11340 // Errors are not generated in errorRecovery mode.
11341 //
11342 // ANTLR's error recovery mechanism is based upon original ideas:
11343 //
11344 // "Algorithms + Data Structures = Programs" by Niklaus Wirth
11345 //
11346 // and
11347 //
11348 // "A note on error recovery in recursive descent parsers":
11349 // http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=947902.947905
11350 //
11351 // Later, Josef Grosch had some good ideas:
11352 //
11353 // "Efficient and Comfortable Error Recovery in Recursive Descent
11354 // Parsers":
11355 // ftp://www.cocolab.com/products/cocktail/doca4.ps/ell.ps.zip
11356 //
11357 // Like Grosch I implement context-sensitive FOLLOW sets that are combined
11358 // at run-time upon error to avoid overhead during parsing.
11359 //
11360 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.getErrorRecoverySet = function(recognizer) {
11361     var atn = recognizer._interp.atn;
11362     var ctx = recognizer._ctx;
11363     var recoverSet = new IntervalSet();
11364     while (ctx !== null && ctx.invokingState>=0) {
11365         // compute what follows who invoked us
11366         var invokingState = atn.states[ctx.invokingState];
11367         var rt = invokingState.transitions[0];
11368         var follow = atn.nextTokens(rt.followState);
11369         recoverSet.addSet(follow);
11370         ctx = ctx.parentCtx;
11371     }
11372     recoverSet.removeOne(Token.EPSILON);
11373     return recoverSet;
11374 };
11375 
11376 // Consume tokens until one matches the given token set.//
11377 DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype.consumeUntil = function(recognizer, set) {
11378     var ttype = recognizer.getTokenStream().LA(1);
11379     while( ttype !== Token.EOF && !set.contains(ttype)) {
11380         recognizer.consume();
11381         ttype = recognizer.getTokenStream().LA(1);
11382     }
11383 };
11384 
11385 //
11386 // This implementation of {@link ANTLRErrorStrategy} responds to syntax errors
11387 // by immediately canceling the parse operation with a
11388 // {@link ParseCancellationException}. The implementation ensures that the
11389 // {@link ParserRuleContext//exception} field is set for all parse tree nodes
11390 // that were not completed prior to encountering the error.
11391 //
11392 // <p>
11393 // This error strategy is useful in the following scenarios.</p>
11394 //
11395 // <ul>
11396 // <li><strong>Two-stage parsing:</strong> This error strategy allows the first
11397 // stage of two-stage parsing to immediately terminate if an error is
11398 // encountered, and immediately fall back to the second stage. In addition to
11399 // avoiding wasted work by attempting to recover from errors here, the empty
11400 // implementation of {@link BailErrorStrategy//sync} improves the performance of
11401 // the first stage.</li>
11402 // <li><strong>Silent validation:</strong> When syntax errors are not being
11403 // reported or logged, and the parse result is simply ignored if errors occur,
11404 // the {@link BailErrorStrategy} avoids wasting work on recovering from errors
11405 // when the result will be ignored either way.</li>
11406 // </ul>
11407 //
11408 // <p>
11409 // {@code myparser.setErrorHandler(new BailErrorStrategy());}</p>
11410 //
11411 // @see Parser//setErrorHandler(ANTLRErrorStrategy)
11412 //
11413 function BailErrorStrategy() {
11414 	DefaultErrorStrategy.call(this);
11415 	return this;
11416 }
11417 
11418 BailErrorStrategy.prototype = Object.create(DefaultErrorStrategy.prototype);
11419 BailErrorStrategy.prototype.constructor = BailErrorStrategy;
11420 
11421 // Instead of recovering from exception {@code e}, re-throw it wrapped
11422 // in a {@link ParseCancellationException} so it is not caught by the
11423 // rule function catches. Use {@link Exception//getCause()} to get the
11424 // original {@link RecognitionException}.
11425 //
11426 BailErrorStrategy.prototype.recover = function(recognizer, e) {
11427     var context = recognizer._ctx;
11428     while (context !== null) {
11429         context.exception = e;
11430         context = context.parentCtx;
11431     }
11432     throw new ParseCancellationException(e);
11433 };
11434 
11435 // Make sure we don't attempt to recover inline; if the parser
11436 // successfully recovers, it won't throw an exception.
11437 //
11438 BailErrorStrategy.prototype.recoverInline = function(recognizer) {
11439     this.recover(recognizer, new InputMismatchException(recognizer));
11440 };
11441 
11442 // Make sure we don't attempt to recover from problems in subrules.//
11443 BailErrorStrategy.prototype.sync = function(recognizer) {
11444     // pass
11445 };
11446 
11447 exports.BailErrorStrategy = BailErrorStrategy;
11448 exports.DefaultErrorStrategy = DefaultErrorStrategy;

11455 // The root of the ANTLR exception hierarchy. In general, ANTLR tracks just
11456 //  3 kinds of errors: prediction errors, failed predicate errors, and
11457 //  mismatched input errors. In each case, the parser knows where it is
11458 //  in the input, where it is in the ATN, the rule invocation stack,
11459 //  and what kind of problem occurred.

11463 function RecognitionException(params) {
11464 	Error.call(this);
11465 	if (!!Error.captureStackTrace) {
11466         Error.captureStackTrace(this, RecognitionException);
11467 	} else {
11468 		var stack = new Error().stack;
11469 	}
11470 	this.message = params.message;
11471     this.recognizer = params.recognizer;
11472     this.input = params.input;
11473     this.ctx = params.ctx;
11474     // The current {@link Token} when an error occurred. Since not all streams
11475     // support accessing symbols by index, we have to track the {@link Token}
11476     // instance itself.
11477     this.offendingToken = null;
11478     // Get the ATN state number the parser was in at the time the error
11479     // occurred. For {@link NoViableAltException} and
11480     // {@link LexerNoViableAltException} exceptions, this is the
11481     // {@link DecisionState} number. For others, it is the state whose outgoing
11482     // edge we couldn't match.
11483     this.offendingState = -1;
11484     if (this.recognizer!==null) {
11485         this.offendingState = this.recognizer.state;
11486     }
11487     return this;
11488 }
11489

11495 //
11496 // Gets the set of input symbols which could potentially follow the
11497 // previously matched symbol at the time this exception was thrown.
11498 //
11499 // <p>If the set of expected tokens is not known and could not be computed,
11500 // this method returns {@code null}.</p>

11502 // @return The set of token types that could potentially follow the current
11503 // state in the ATN, or {@code null} if the information is not available.

11505 RecognitionException.prototype.getExpectedTokens = function() {
11506     if (this.recognizer!==null) {
11507         return this.recognizer.atn.getExpectedTokens(this.offendingState, this.ctx);
11508     } else {
11509         return null;

11517 function LexerNoViableAltException(lexer, input, startIndex, deadEndConfigs) {

11528     var symbol = "";
11529     if (this.startIndex >= 0 && this.startIndex < this.input.size) {
11530         symbol = this.input.getText((this.startIndex,this.startIndex));
11531     }

11535 // Indicates that the parser could not decide which of two or more paths
11536 // to take based upon the remaining input. It tracks the starting token
11537 // of the offending input and also knows where the parser was
11538 // in the various paths when the error. Reported by reportNoViableAlternative()
11539 //
11540 function NoViableAltException(recognizer, input, startToken, offendingToken, deadEndConfigs, ctx) {
11541 	ctx = ctx || recognizer._ctx;
11542 	offendingToken = offendingToken || recognizer.getCurrentToken();
11543 	startToken = startToken || recognizer.getCurrentToken();
11544 	input = input || recognizer.getInputStream();
11545 	RecognitionException.call(this, {message:"", recognizer:recognizer, input:input, ctx:ctx});
11546     // Which configurations did we try at input.index() that couldn't match
11547 	// input.LT(1)?//
11548     this.deadEndConfigs = deadEndConfigs;
11549     // The token object at the start index; the input stream might
11550     // not be buffering tokens so get a reference to it. (At the
11551     // time the error occurred, of course the stream needs to keep a
11552     // buffer all of the tokens but later we might not have access to those.)
11553     this.startToken = startToken;
11554     this.offendingToken = offendingToken;
11555 }

11661 /*! https://mths.be/codepointat v0.2.0 by @mathias */
11662 if (!String.prototype.codePointAt) {
11663 	(function() {
11664 		'use strict'; // needed to support `apply`/`call` with `undefined`/`null`
11665 		var defineProperty = (function() {
11666 			// IE 8 only supports `Object.defineProperty` on DOM elements
11667 			try {
11668 				var object = {};
11669 				var $defineProperty = Object.defineProperty;
11670 				var result = $defineProperty(object, object, object) && $defineProperty;
11671 			} catch(error) {}
11672 			return result;
11673 		}());
11674 		var codePointAt = function(position) {
11675 			if (this == null) {
11676 				throw TypeError();
11677 			}
11678 			var string = String(this);
11679 			var size = string.length;
11680 			// `ToInteger`
11681 			var index = position ? Number(position) : 0;
11682 			if (index != index) { // better `isNaN`
11683 				index = 0;
11684 			}
11685 			// Account for out-of-bounds indices:
11686 			if (index < 0 || index >= size) {
11687 				return undefined;
11688 			}
11689 			// Get the first code unit
11690 			var first = string.charCodeAt(index);
11691 			var second;
11692 			if ( // check if its the start of a surrogate pair
11693 				first >= 0xD800 && first <= 0xDBFF && // high surrogate
11694 				size > index + 1 // there is a next code unit
11695 			) {
11696 				second = string.charCodeAt(index + 1);
11697 				if (second >= 0xDC00 && second <= 0xDFFF) { // low surrogate
11698 					// https://mathiasbynens.be/notes/javascript-encoding#surrogate-formulae
11699 					return (first - 0xD800) * 0x400 + second - 0xDC00 + 0x10000;
11700 				}
11701 			}
11702 			return first;
11703 		};
11704 		if (defineProperty) {
11705 			defineProperty(String.prototype, 'codePointAt', {
11706 				'value': codePointAt,
11707 				'configurable': true,
11708 				'writable': true
11709 			});
11710 		} else {
11711 			String.prototype.codePointAt = codePointAt;
11712 		}
11713 	}());
11714 }

11718 if (!String.fromCodePoint) {
11719 	(function() {
11720 		var defineProperty = (function() {
11721 			// IE 8 only supports `Object.defineProperty` on DOM elements
11722 			try {
11723 				var object = {};
11724 				var $defineProperty = Object.defineProperty;
11725 				var result = $defineProperty(object, object, object) && $defineProperty;
11726 			} catch(error) {}
11727 			return result;
11728 		}());
11729 		var stringFromCharCode = String.fromCharCode;
11730 		var floor = Math.floor;
11731 		var fromCodePoint = function(_) {
11732 			var MAX_SIZE = 0x4000;
11733 			var codeUnits = [];
11734 			var highSurrogate;
11735 			var lowSurrogate;
11736 			var index = -1;
11737 			var length = arguments.length;
11738 			if (!length) {
11739 				return '';
11740 			}
11741 			var result = '';
11742 			while (++index < length) {
11743 				var codePoint = Number(arguments[index]);
11744 				if (
11745 					!isFinite(codePoint) || // `NaN`, `+Infinity`, or `-Infinity`
11746 					codePoint < 0 || // not a valid Unicode code point
11747 					codePoint > 0x10FFFF || // not a valid Unicode code point
11748 					floor(codePoint) != codePoint // not an integer
11749 				) {
11750 					throw RangeError('Invalid code point: ' + codePoint);
11751 				}
11752 				if (codePoint <= 0xFFFF) { // BMP code point
11753 					codeUnits.push(codePoint);
11754 				} else { // Astral code point; split in surrogate halves
11755 					// https://mathiasbynens.be/notes/javascript-encoding#surrogate-formulae
11756 					codePoint -= 0x10000;
11757 					highSurrogate = (codePoint >> 10) + 0xD800;
11758 					lowSurrogate = (codePoint % 0x400) + 0xDC00;
11759 					codeUnits.push(highSurrogate, lowSurrogate);
11760 				}
11761 				if (index + 1 == length || codeUnits.length > MAX_SIZE) {
11762 					result += stringFromCharCode.apply(null, codeUnits);
11763 					codeUnits.length = 0;
11764 				}
11765 			}
11766 			return result;
11767 		};
11768 		if (defineProperty) {
11769 			defineProperty(String, 'fromCodePoint', {
11770 				'value': fromCodePoint,
11771 				'configurable': true,
11772 				'writable': true
11773 			});
11774 		} else {
11775 			String.fromCodePoint = fromCodePoint;
11776 		}
11777 	}());

11909 	if (this.symbol === null) {
11910 		return INVALID_INTERVAL;
11911 	}
11912 	var tokenIndex = this.symbol.tokenIndex;
11913 	return new Interval(tokenIndex, tokenIndex);
11914 };

11917 	return 0;

11920 TerminalNodeImpl.prototype.accept = function(visitor) {

11922 };

11928 TerminalNodeImpl.prototype.toString = function() {
11929 	if (this.symbol.type === Token.EOF) {
11930 		return "<EOF>";
11931 	} else {
11932 		return this.symbol.text;
11933 	}
11934 };

11936 // Represents a token that was consumed during resynchronization
11937 // rather than during a valid match operation. For example,
11938 // we will create this kind of a node during single token insertion
11939 // and deletion as well as during "consume until error recovery set"
11940 // upon no viable alternative exceptions.
11941 
11942 function ErrorNodeImpl(token) {
11943 	TerminalNodeImpl.call(this, token);
11944 	return this;
11945 }
11946 
11947 ErrorNodeImpl.prototype = Object.create(TerminalNodeImpl.prototype);
11948 ErrorNodeImpl.prototype.constructor = ErrorNodeImpl;
11949 
11950 ErrorNodeImpl.prototype.isErrorNode = function() {
11951 	return true;
11952 };
11953 
11954 ErrorNodeImpl.prototype.accept = function(visitor) {
11955 	return visitor.visitErrorNode(this);
11956 };

11958 function ParseTreeWalker() {
11959 	return this;
11960 }
11961 
11962 ParseTreeWalker.prototype.walk = function(listener, t) {
11963 	var errorNode = t instanceof ErrorNode ||
11964 			(t.isErrorNode !== undefined && t.isErrorNode());
11965 	if (errorNode) {
11966 		listener.visitErrorNode(t);
11967 	} else if (t instanceof TerminalNode) {
11968 		listener.visitTerminal(t);
11969 	} else {
11970 		this.enterRule(listener, t);
11971 		for (var i = 0; i < t.getChildCount(); i++) {
11972 			var child = t.getChild(i);
11973 			this.walk(listener, child);
11974 		}
11975 		this.exitRule(listener, t);
11976 	}
11977 };
11978 //
11979 // The discovery of a rule node, involves sending two events: the generic
11980 // {@link ParseTreeListener//enterEveryRule} and a
11981 // {@link RuleContext}-specific event. First we trigger the generic and then
11982 // the rule specific. We to them in reverse order upon finishing the node.
11983 //
11984 ParseTreeWalker.prototype.enterRule = function(listener, r) {
11985 	var ctx = r.getRuleContext();
11986 	listener.enterEveryRule(ctx);
11987 	ctx.enterRule(listener);
11988 };
11989 
11990 ParseTreeWalker.prototype.exitRule = function(listener, r) {
11991 	var ctx = r.getRuleContext();
11992 	ctx.exitRule(listener);
11993 	listener.exitEveryRule(ctx);
11994 };
11995 
11996 ParseTreeWalker.DEFAULT = new ParseTreeWalker();

12014 var Utils = require('./../Utils');
12015 var Token = require('./../Token').Token;
12016 var RuleNode = require('./Tree').RuleNode;
12017 var ErrorNode = require('./Tree').ErrorNode;
12018 var TerminalNode = require('./Tree').TerminalNode;
12019 var ParserRuleContext = require('./../ParserRuleContext').ParserRuleContext;
12020 var RuleContext = require('./../RuleContext').RuleContext;
12021 var INVALID_ALT_NUMBER = require('./../atn/ATN').INVALID_ALT_NUMBER;
12022 
12023 
12024 /** A set of utility routines useful for all kinds of ANTLR trees. */
12025 function Trees() {
12026 }
12027 
12028 // Print out a whole tree in LISP form. {@link //getNodeText} is used on the
12029 //  node payloads to get the text for the nodes.  Detect
12030 //  parse trees and extract data appropriately.
12031 Trees.toStringTree = function(tree, ruleNames, recog) {
12032 	ruleNames = ruleNames || null;
12033 	recog = recog || null;
12034     if(recog!==null) {
12035        ruleNames = recog.ruleNames;
12036     }
12037     var s = Trees.getNodeText(tree, ruleNames);
12038     s = Utils.escapeWhitespace(s, false);
12039     var c = tree.getChildCount();
12040     if(c===0) {
12041         return s;
12042     }
12043     var res = "(" + s + ' ';
12044     if(c>0) {
12045         s = Trees.toStringTree(tree.getChild(0), ruleNames);
12046         res = res.concat(s);
12047     }
12048     for(var i=1;i<c;i++) {
12049         s = Trees.toStringTree(tree.getChild(i), ruleNames);
12050         res = res.concat(' ' + s);
12051     }
12052     res = res.concat(")");
12053     return res;
12054 };
12055 
12056 Trees.getNodeText = function(t, ruleNames, recog) {
12057 	ruleNames = ruleNames || null;
12058 	recog = recog || null;
12059     if(recog!==null) {
12060         ruleNames = recog.ruleNames;
12061     }
12062     if(ruleNames!==null) {
12063        if (t instanceof RuleContext) {
12064            var altNumber = t.getAltNumber();
12065            if ( altNumber!=INVALID_ALT_NUMBER ) {
12066                return ruleNames[t.ruleIndex]+":"+altNumber;
12067            }
12068            return ruleNames[t.ruleIndex];
12069        } else if ( t instanceof ErrorNode) {
12070            return t.toString();
12071        } else if(t instanceof TerminalNode) {
12072            if(t.symbol!==null) {
12073                return t.symbol.text;
12074            }
12075        }
12076     }
12077     // no recog for rule names
12078     var payload = t.getPayload();
12079     if (payload instanceof Token ) {
12080        return payload.text;
12081     }
12082     return t.getPayload().toString();
12083 };
12084 
12085 
12086 // Return ordered list of all children of this node
12087 Trees.getChildren = function(t) {
12088 	var list = [];
12089 	for(var i=0;i<t.getChildCount();i++) {
12090 		list.push(t.getChild(i));
12091 	}
12092 	return list;
12093 };
12094 
12095 // Return a list of all ancestors of this node.  The first node of
12096 //  list is the root and the last is the parent of this node.
12097 //
12098 Trees.getAncestors = function(t) {
12099     var ancestors = [];
12100     t = t.getParent();
12101     while(t!==null) {
12102         ancestors = [t].concat(ancestors);
12103         t = t.getParent();
12104     }
12105     return ancestors;
12106 };
12107 
12108 Trees.findAllTokenNodes = function(t, ttype) {
12109     return Trees.findAllNodes(t, ttype, true);
12110 };
12111 
12112 Trees.findAllRuleNodes = function(t, ruleIndex) {
12113 	return Trees.findAllNodes(t, ruleIndex, false);
12114 };
12115 
12116 Trees.findAllNodes = function(t, index, findTokens) {
12117 	var nodes = [];
12118 	Trees._findAllNodes(t, index, findTokens, nodes);
12119 	return nodes;
12120 };
12121 
12122 Trees._findAllNodes = function(t, index, findTokens, nodes) {
12123 	// check this node (the root) first
12124 	if(findTokens && (t instanceof TerminalNode)) {
12125 		if(t.symbol.type===index) {
12126 			nodes.push(t);
12127 		}
12128 	} else if(!findTokens && (t instanceof ParserRuleContext)) {
12129 		if(t.ruleIndex===index) {
12130 			nodes.push(t);
12131 		}
12132 	}
12133 	// check children
12134 	for(var i=0;i<t.getChildCount();i++) {
12135 		Trees._findAllNodes(t.getChild(i), index, findTokens, nodes);
12136 	}
12137 };
12138 
12139 Trees.descendants = function(t) {
12140 	var nodes = [t];
12141     for(var i=0;i<t.getChildCount();i++) {
12142         nodes = nodes.concat(Trees.descendants(t.getChild(i)));
12143     }
12144     return nodes;
12145 };
